<FIRST>u i AM-Trans-AtlanticRecord     07-26 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trans-Atlantic Record,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Takes Record for Fastest Trans-Atlantic Sea Crossing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. MARY'S, Isles of Scilly (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American powerboat racer Tom
Gentry set a record Thursday for the fastest trans-Atlantic
crossing.
   The wealthy 58-year-old property developer from Honolulu and his
five-man crew aboard the Gentry Eagle crossed the finish line at
Bishop Rock lighthouse off the Isles of Scilly at 3:56 a.m. (10:56
p.m. EDT Wednesday).
   Their voyage from Ambrose Light, New York, to Bishop Rock took
two days, 14 hours and seven minutes.
   The previous record was held by British business tycoon Richard
Branson.
   In June 1986, Branson and his team completed the 3,386-mile
crossing aboard the 72-foot powerboat Virgin Atlantic Challenger II
in three days, eight hours and 31 minutes.
   Gentry tried the break the record in July 1988, but equipment
aboard his 110-foot powerboat Continental Proud Bird was damaged in
heavy seas and he was force to abandon the crossing after traveling
1,500 miles.
   Branson, whose business interests include the airline Virgin
Atlantic and a records and entertainment empire, tried to claim the
150-year-old Blue Riband trophy for his 1986 crossing, which cut
two hours and nine minutes off the speed record held since 1952 by
the American liner United States.
   But the U.S. Merchant Marine Museum at King's Point, New York,
refused to hand over the trophy. Museum curator Frank Braynard said
at the time that it was for ocean liners, not ``little toy boats''
like Virgin Atlantic Challenger II.
   Branson then offered his own Virgin Atlantic Challenger Trophy
to anyone who could beat his record, saying he wanted to ``promote
and encourage new technology.''
</TEXT>
