<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Drugs     07-26 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Drugs,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Drug Addicts Rounded Up In 48 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of drug addicts have been
rounded up and sent to labor camps with the expiration of a
six-month grace period that abusers were given to kick the habit,
Tehran radio reported.
   The deadline expired Sunday and drug addicts are now being
arrested as common criminals, said the broadcast, monitored Tuesday
in Nicosia.
   Mokhtar Kalantari, head of an intensive anti-narcotics campaign
launched last year, told the radio that every Iranian province will
have a hard labor camp to house the addicts.
   Iran has 50 million people and an estimated 2 million drug
addicts.
   Reports in recent days said 40 percent of the divorces in the
country are caused by drugs.
   Kalantari said that in the initial stage of the crackdown,
15,000 drug abusers will be sent to labor camps and another 40,000
will be cared for by the prison system.
   The fierce anti-narcotics campaign was launched following the
August cease-fire in the 8-year Iran-Iraq war.
   In the first phase of the crackdown, authorities focused on
stamping out drug traffickers: About 800 alleged drug smugglers
have been hanged since December.
</TEXT>
