<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     07-26 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Continues Record In Week of Reruns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With seven of the top 10 shows, NBC dominated
the A.C. Nielsen Co. television ratings for the 56th consecutive
week, and Fox Television managed a strong showing on Sunday night.
   NBC had an overall rating of 10.8 and a 21 share for the week
ending July 23, followed by ABC with a 9.0 rating and a 17 share,
and CBS with 8.7 and a 17.
   The ratings are a percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes
in the United States with television. The share is the percentage
of sets in use.
   Fox Television's ``Totally Hidden Video,'' briefly shaken by the
dismissal of a producer and tossing of segments that were staged
instead of spontaneous, rebounded from 34th place to 29th place
with a 10.8 rating on Sunday night.
   It was preceded by ``America's Most Wanted,'' which also had a
10.8 rating. The two shows helped the network lead the ratings for
the 8 p.m. to 9 p.m. time slot on Sunday.
   The week's Top 10: A first-place tie between NBC's ``Cheers''
and ABC's ``Roseanne,'' followed by ``A Different World,'' ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``Dear John,'' ``The Golden Girls,'' ``Empty Nest''
and ``Hunter,'' all NBC; ``The CBS Sunday Night Movie,'' and ABC's
``The Wonder Years.''
   The five lowest-rated network shows were NBC's ``Jim Henson
Hour,'' followed in ascending order by four parts of the spoof
``Fresno'' miniseries on CBS.
   CBS won the nightly news show ratings with an average of 9.3,
followed by ABC with 9.2 and NBC with 8.6.
</TEXT>
