<FIRST>u a AM-ChurchShooting     07-26 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Shooting,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Shootings Resulted From Domestic Dispute, Police Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man's dispute with his estranged wife led
him and his half-brother to open fire on church members during a
Bible study class, killing the wife's cousin and an elderly woman,
police said Tuesday.
   Albert Lewis Jr., 33, and his half-brother, Anthony Oliver, 27,
were arrested at 7 p.m. Monday for investigation of murder in the
Friday night shooting by two hooded gunmen at Mount Olive Church of
God in Christ, said Cmdr. William Booth. They were held without
bail.
   Just hours before the attack, a judge ordered Lewis to remain
more than 100 yards from the church and several family members
after his wife, Cynthia Worthen-Lewis, claimed he had abused her,
according to court records.
   Mrs. Worthen-Lewis said that Lewis had called her earlier in the
week and said ``he was going to kill me,'' according to her court
declaration to obtain a restraining order.
   Mrs. Worthen-Lewis is the cousin of gospel singer Patronella
Worthen Luke, fatally shot in the attack that also killed
76-year-old Mae Lee and wounded Mrs. Luke's husband in the leg,
Booth said.
   ``We want to assure the public that this was not gang-related,''
Booth said. ``Detectives ... believe the shooting stemmed from a
domestic dispute.''
   Clergy members and parishioners had voiced fear that the
killings were committed by gang members or drug dealers in the
church's neighborhood.
   Ms. Lee appeared to be a bystander hit by gunfire as she went
toward the church door, but police were investigating whether she
was linked to the Luke or Lewis families, said Lt. Charles Massey.
</TEXT>
