<FIRST>r w PM-MarineReading     07-26 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine Reading,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Says Marines Fight Better When They Fight Smarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines fight better when they fight smarter,
says the commanding officer, so the order of the day mandates more
reading.
   For sergeants, a book list starts by saying: ``Read a minimum of
two books (ideally four) annually ...'' The mandate for colonels is
three to start, with ``six ideally.''
   The idea to tote books, not just guns, comes from the commandant
of the Marine Corps, Gen. A.M. Gray.
   ``I firmly believe that professional reading is essential to the
professional growth of our leaders,'' Gray said in a recent message
to all Marine barracks. ``The profession of arms, in particular,
has a profound body of knowledge which requires constant study if a
leader is to remain proficient.''
   All of the books on the list give some military lessons, whether
it be leadership qualities from E.B. Hubbard's ``A Message to
Garcia'' or tactics taken from Mao Zedong's ``On Guerrilla
Warfare.''
   The Marines can select from biographies such as ``The Patton
Papers'' or ``The Years of MacArthur.'' Leo Tolstoy's ``War and
Peace'' is on the list, along with Alexander Solzhenitsyn's
``August 1914,'' Von Clausewitz's ``On War'' and Neil Sheehan's
Pulitzer Prize winner, ``A Bright Shining Lie.''
   ``The study of our profession through the selected readings will
assist each Marine's efforts to achieve operational competence and
to better understand the nature of our `calling' as leaders of
Marines,'' Gray said.
   The reading program is part of an overall educational update for
the corps, explained Chief Warrant Officer Eric Carlson, a Marine
Corps spokesman, who added: ``Marines already do a lot of reading
on their own.''
   Carlson said the educational program also calls for setting up
the Marine Corps University at the Combat Development Command at
Quantico, Va., starting Aug. 1. He said the university will act as
an umbrella for the corps' four officers' training schools at
Quantico and ``will provide uniform training.''
</TEXT>
