<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     07-26 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Gains Squabble Grows As Lawmakers Move 6 Spending Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax deadlock between Congress and President
Bush is dampening hopes for a 1991 budget deal, but lawmakers are
pushing ahead with six multibillion dollar spending bills for the
coming fiscal year.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said Tuesday that Bush's
aggressive campaign to cut the capital gains tax is troubling and
may result in Democrats leaving the president with the task of
proposing how to slash the 1991 federal deficit to $64 billion.
   The budget blueprint for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1, calls
for $5.3 billion in new tax receipts.
   To raise most of that money, Bush has been trying to persuade
wavering Democrats on the tax-writing House Ways and Means
Committee to join Republicans and cut the capital gains tax paid
when property is sold at a profit.
   The administration says a lower rate would stimulate sales of
property, and thus generate money for the government. Democrats say
the cut would mainly put money in the pockets of the rich and cost
the government revenue in the long run.
   Coupled with Bush's continued refusal to raise taxes, the
president's effort is annoying growing numbers of Democrats. Among
the angry lawmakers are some who hope to negotiate a budget deal
for fiscal 1991 in talks later this year, including House Budget
Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
   Panetta said it would be hard for him to hammer out a
deficit-cutting agreement with the White House if it's seen as
``purely a political operation that doesn't want to work out a
resolution on substance.''
   On more immediate business, congressional committees approved
six fiscal 1990 spending bills Tuesday. With less than six weeks of
congressional business left until Oct. 1, the House has passed five
of the appropriations bills needed annually to keep the government
functioning, and the Senate has approved none.
   The House Appropriations Committee approved an $18.4 billion
measure for the Treasury, Postal Service and a slew of other
agencies, a $155.2 billion bill for the departments of Health and
Human Services, Labor and Education and a $5.8 billion package for
the departments of commerce, justice, state and the federal
judiciary.
   Across the Capitol, the Senate Appropriations Committee passed
bills containing $44 billion for agriculture programs, $18 billion
for energy and water projects and $10.5 billion for the Interior
Department and for federal cultural programs.
   The Senate Finance Committee also approved adding $60 billion to
the amount the government can borrow, enough to see it through Oct.
31. The $2.8 trillion debt limit is expected to be breached
sometime next month, and lawmakers want to add some leeway before
they leave Aug. 5 for their four-week recess.
</TEXT>
