<FIRST>r w PM-DroughtRelief     07-26 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Relief,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Passes Drought Bill on Party-Line Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole says
partisan differences over a Democratic-backed disaster-relief bill
could scuttle chances of getting quick assistance to farmers who
have lost crops.
   However, Democrats say Dole is exaggerating the dispute over the
$955 million measure, which the Senate Agriculture Committee
approved Tuesday on a party-line vote.
   The legislation costs at least $300 million less than the House
version, but that's $70 million more than President Bush wants to
spend. Republicans say the measure covers too many crops, more than
500.
   ``We've got to find some way to bring (the two sides) together
or there may not be a drought bill,'' said Dole, concerned about
getting help to drought-stricken wheat farmers in his home state of
Kansas.
   Calling the legislation ``a disaster itself,'' Dole said
differences may not be resolved in time to get drought relief to
the president's desk before the August congressional recess.
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said the differences between committee
Republicans and Democrats were ``almost indistinguishable.''
   Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., had postponed a vote
last week in the hope of reaching a bipartisan accord. He brought
the bill to a vote Tuesday after it became apparent Republicans
would insist on targeting disaster relief to soybeans and crops in
the government's farm program _ primarily wheat, corn, rice and
cotton.
   Wheat and other crops have been damaged because of the lingering
drought across much of the Great Plains, from Texas to North
Dakota, and flooding has destroyed rice and cotton in the South.
   The Senate Democrats' bill would cover the same crops as the
House legislation, but farmers would have to show a bigger loss to
qualify for disaster relief and the government payments would be
smaller.
   The administration is trying to limit disaster relief to $870
million, but Senate Democrats argue that an additional $85 million
could be made available if some of the payments come from this
year's budget instead of next year's.
   The administration insists all the drought relief come from the
1990 budget.
   Under the committee bill, farmers who grow wheat, corn and other
program crops could qualify for relief if they lost at least 40
percent of the grain. Farmers of other crops would have to show a
45 percent loss to qualify.
   The minimum loss required by the House bill is 35 percent.
   Democrats say that the GOP position that crops in the farm
program should get first crack at drought relief is unfair to
farmers who grow other commodities, discourages farms from
diversifying and makes it politically more difficult to pass the
legislation.
   The debate spilled onto the Senate floor after the committee
vote Tuesday when Dole denounced the Democratic bill.
   ``The American farmer doesn't expect us to shovel out money
every time something happens,'' Dole said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
