<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MedicalWaste     07-26 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medical Waste,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Tracking Law Won't Reduce Medical Waste, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most medical waste that washes up on the
nation's beaches comes from illegal drug users and individuals, not
hospitals, according to a new study.
   The Medical Waste Policy Committee said in its report that a
federal law that took effect last month won't do much to reduce the
used needles, syringes and other medical trash plaguing the
nation's shoreline.
   Legislators have said the law will prevent a repeat of last
summer, when waves of medical waste washed up along popular East
Coast beaches.
   ``Laws and regulations specifically aimed at medical waste, such
as the Medical Waste Tracking Act, are unlikely to have a
significant effect on the amount of medical waste found on the
beaches,'' said Richard A. Bernstein, head of General Medical Corp.
and chairman of the committee.
   The problem, Bernstein said, isn't with hospitals but with home
health uses, which account for nearly 1 billion syringes annually.
   The committee, under the auspices of the Rockefeller Institute
of Government at the State University of New York, encouraged
public education programs on proper disposal of used medical items.
   Bernstein presented the results of the six-month study Tuesday
to the House Small Business subcommittee on regulation and business
opportunities.
   Authors of the measure defended it.
   ``There is no reason why medical waste shouldn't be tracked in
the same way other hazardous waste is tracked. That was a hole in
the law,'' said Jason Isaacson, spokesman for Sen. Christopher J.
Dodd, D-Conn., a chief backer of the legislation.
   ``Did it finally resolve all present and future problems with
medical waste? Of course not? Is there room to do more? Of course
there is, but it was a substantial first step,'' Isaacson said.
   Robin Woods, of the Environmental Protection Agency, said the
law would help because it regulates, for the first time, small
health-care providers such as clinics, laboratories and doctors'
offices.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., chairman of the subcommittee, said the
research ``shows that this country badly needs a clear, uniform
policy that creates incentives for safe, cost-effective management
of this waste.''
   ``One year after needles on our beaches were front-page news,
the bulk of this waste remains largely unregulated and
uncontrolled,'' Wyden said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
