<HEAD>Panel Wants Outside Counsel to Review Gingrich Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee wants to hire the
same outside counsel that investigated Speaker Jim Wright to look
into complaints against GOP Whip Newt Gingrich.
   The panel said Tuesday it had asked the House Administration
Committee to hire the Chicago law firm of Phelan, Pope &amp; John Ltd.
at a cost of $150,000.
   Wright resigned from the House last month after the ethics
committee charged him with 69 violations of House rules.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., accused Gingrich in an April
complaint of violating campaign finance laws, House limits on
outside income and a House rule preventing acceptance of gifts from
those with a direct interest in legislation.
   Gingrich, the second-ranking House GOP leader, called
Alexander's charges ``baseless,'' and said ``any serious review of
the allegations would indicate how politically motivated they
were.''
   Alexander's complaint focused on the COS Limited Partnership,
which consisted of 21 investors who contributed $5,000 each to
promote ``Window of Opportunity,'' a book written by the Georgia
Republican, his wife and a third author.
   Gingrich was not an investor, but his wife was paid for running
the partnership, formed in 1984.
