<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett-Drugs     07-26 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Drugs,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Policy Takes Aim at Crack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William J. Bennett says his national
drug program will focus on the battle against crack.
   ``It's crack that is responsible for the disorder in many of our
cities,'' Bennett said Tuesday, describing the strategy his Office
of National Drug Control must unveil by Sept. 5.
   ``It's crack which is endangering the lives of so many innocent
civilians because of the tendency for violence. It's crack which is
appearing with terrible frequency as the drug sought out by
pregnant addicts.''
   Crack is a cheap and highly addictive form of cocaine that is
smoked.
   While programs focusing on other illegal drugs also are
important, the campaign against crack takes precedence because it
presents ``the clearest, most immediate danger to the largest
number of people,'' Bennett said.
   Bennett also told reporters that states that fail to impose
strict anti-drug policies may risk losing federal funds.
   ``We will expect states to do certain things if they want
federal funds,'' he said. ``We will expect educational institutions
to finally do certain things if they want education funds.''
   He did not give any details.
   A draft of the drug strategy, which Congress has required be
completed by Sept. 5, is being reviewed by the various agencies
affected, including the National Security Council, Bennett said.
   President Bush, who is to announce the program, will have the
final say.
   ``It is his strategy,'' Bennett said.
   Also Tuesday, Bush announced that he will nominate U.S. Marshals
Service Director Stanley E. Morris as deputy director of Bennett's
office in charge of drug supply reduction.
   The long-awaited announcement, following by a week the
nomination of the other top deputy _ Herbert Kleber _ rounds out
the top appointees in the office. The associate director in charge
of state and local affairs, Reggie Walton, was confirmed six weeks
ago.
</TEXT>
