<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0351EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CapitalGains     07-26 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plan Favors Rich Less Than Ways and Means-Backed Plan: Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional economists say the capital-gains
tax cut favored by a majority of the House Ways and Means Committee
is tilted more toward high-income Americans than the measure backed
by President Bush.
   Eighty cents of every dollar of benefit in the capital-gains cut
that has become the major issue in the committee would go to those
with incomes above $100,000 a year, according to figures prepared
by the Joint Committee on Taxation.
   Bush's proposal would earmark slightly less _ 79.7 cents of
every dollar _ for the over-$100,000 group. But it would give 2.5
percent of the total tax relief to those with incomes under $30,000
a year, compared with 1.8 percent under the bill being debated in
Ways and Means.
   Either plan would cut taxes for about 7.9 million couples and
individuals who would be expected to have profits from the sale of
stocks and other assets in 1990. Capital gains are taxed as
ordinary income, at rates of 15 percent, 28 percent or 33 percent,
depending on total income.
   Bush's proposal, which would result in a top capital-gains rate
of 15 percent, would produce a tax cut of $30,820 for the average
investor with over $200,000 of total income. The other proposal,
which would have a top 20 percent rate for two years and then a 28
percent rate, would be worth $24,906 a year to the average $200,000
investor.
   Bush and other supporters of a capital-gains cut say it would
boost the economy by encouraging saving and reducing U.S. business
costs of investment.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, told reporters Tuesday that any capital-gains cut to
temporarily raise revenue would be gimmickry that would complicate
the future deficit picture.
</TEXT>
