<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SatelliteFight     07-26 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satellite Fight,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Files Suit Against Comsat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut company alleges in a $1.5
billion antitrust suit that a congressionally created corporation
is fixing prices and blocking competition for international
satellite communications services.
   Pan American Satellite of Greenwich, Conn., alleges that
Communications Satellite Corp., or Comsat, is blocking ``cheaper
and better satellite communications services in order to line its
own pockets and protect an outmoded monopoly.''
   Comsat sells U.S. companies access to Intelsat, the 117-nation
consortium of satellite telecommunications users.
   PAS Chairman Rene Anselmo said Comsat had ``illegally
monopolized the market by price fixing and conspiring to block
competition. We want to bust open their monopoly.''
   The suit, filed Tuesday in the U.S. District Court for the
Southern District of New York, seeks $500 million in actual damages
_ which would be trebled under U.S. law _ and a permanent
injunction enjoining Comsat from engaging in alleged illegal
activities.
   PAS is the first privately owned international satellite
communications company. It launched its PAS-1 satellite in June
1988 at a cost of about $100 million and began service in September
to Latin America and Europe.
   But PAS alleges that Comsat has tried to put it out of business
by supporting a boycott of separate satellite systems,
misrepresenting facts to PAS customers, using predatory pricing
tactics and conspiring with foreign telecommunications companies to
block PAS business opportunities.
   Comsat spokesman Bob Hunter said the PAS suit ``has absolutely
no merit,'' describing it as another in a ``series of actions taken
by Pan American Satellite to find every opportunity to lodge
complaints and in fact attempt to impede and or harass Comsat in
its own mission.''
   Congress created Comsat in the Communications Satellite Act of
1962. Until 1971, Comsat oversaw Intelsat's growth. Comsat owns 26
percent of Intelsat and accounts for more than 50 percent of all
Intelsat traffic, PAS said.
   Comsat is a private, publicly traded company that leases
Intelsat circuits to companies such as American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co., MCI, US Sprint and television networks.
</TEXT>
