is living with the guy,'' Fitzwater quipped. ``I don't think he's
going anywhere unnoticed.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Commercial Tritium Sales Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department is suspending commercial
shipments of tritium from the Oak Ridge National Laboratory in
Tennessee because European customers have complained of short
weights.
   The department said Tuesday that measurement and loading
operations are being reviewed.
   Tritium, a radioactive gas, is a major component of many nuclear
weapons, but it also has commercial, research and medical uses.
Tritium is used in luminous signs, such as aircraft exit signs, and
for runway markers in remote areas such as Alaska.
   The department's production of tritium is shut down because of
safety and management problems with the nuclear reactors used to
produce it at the Savannah River Site in South Carolina.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Mayors: Congress Needs to Put Money Where Mouth Is</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional efforts to force communities
into cleanups they can't afford won't work and are a cheap
substitute for a real environmental policy, a representative of the
National League of Cities said.
   ``You cannot build ... treatment plants with a thousand points
of light,'' John Bullard said Tuesday before a joint session of the
Environment and Public Works subcommittees on environmental
protection and on superfund, ocean and water protection.
   Bullard, mayor of New Bedford, Mass., represented the National
League of Cities before the subcommittees, which are considering a
variety of clean water legislation.
   Bullard said the federal government must be able to ``walk this
fine line'' between ``punishment and partnership'' if it is to be
serious about environmental issues.
   An ``irresistible force'' of public demand for a clean
environment is running up against an ``immovable object'' of scarce
financial resources that threatens ``an impending explosion that
could consume some cities,'' he said.
