<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Attendants     07-26 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Attendants,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor Credits Courage of Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survivor of United Flight 232 praised
the flight attendants for maintaining calm and helping passengers
escape from the wreckage of the DC-10 after it crashed.
   Helen Hayes of Denver said a flight attendant whose name she
doesn't know helped prevent panic. Ms. Hayes was sitting in the
ninth row in the jetliner's middle cabin section.
   ``Her voice was very soothing,'' Ms. Hayes, 27, said Tuesday
from her Sioux City hospital room. ``She prevented the passengers
from going into complete hysteria.''
   Seven of the eight flight attendants on the plane survived the
tumbling crash at the Sioux Gateway Airport last Wednesday. Of the
296 people aboard, 185 survived and 111 perished.
   United spokesmen said they would wait for investigators to
determine why such a high number of the cabin crew survived. United
spokesman Rob Doughty said flight attendants sit in jump seats
which are bolted to bulkheads in reinforced sections of the cabin.
   That's so they can help passengers get out of the airplane, he
said.
   Ms. Hayes said she could see the fear on the flight attendant's
face. She said flight attendants issued instructions on what
passengers should do right up to the time the crippled jumbo jet
hit the ground.
   ``It must have been very difficult for them to do that,'' she
said.
   Ms. Hayes said passengers were calm but tense before the crash.
   ``People were very quiet, you could feel the fear in the air,''
she said. ``People were very tense.''
</TEXT>
