<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0440EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba     07-26 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Rejects U.S. Charges That It's Soft on Drug Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMAGUEY, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has a better record than the United
States of punishing narcotics smugglers, the country's deputy
foreign minister said in response to U.S. charges that his
government is soft on drugs.
   The diplomat, Ricardo Alarcon, told a news conference Tuesday
that while U.S. officials accused of narcotics trafficking go
unpunished, Cuba has acted decisively against officials guilty of
the same crimes.
   Two weeks ago, Cuban authorities executed Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa and
three colleagues after a court-martial found them guilty of drug
smuggling and other charges.
   Alarcon said U.S. authorities refused to act on information
several years ago suggesting that high-level American officials
were involved in cocaine trafficking from Central America to
Florida. He said former National Security aide Oliver North was
among those involved.
   U.S. officials have said those allegations have little
credibility partly because they were based largely on comments made
years ago by convicted drug smugglers.
   American skeptcism of Cuba's commitment to fighting the drug
trade was reaffirmed Tuesday during a House hearing in Washington.
   Melvyn Levitsky, assistant secretary of state for international
narcotics matters, said there was a sharp increase in drug
shipments through Cuban territory in the first six months of this
year.
   ``Some evidence suggests that Cuba simultaneously facilitates
the flow of drugs in selected cases while prosecuting other cases
to conviction,'' Levitsky told the House Foreign Affairs Committee
narcotics task force.
   Alarcon said Cuba will not ``tolerate the least flexbility, the
slightest concession toward this vice nor toward any person related
to this vice.''
   He also said that ``tons and tons'' of marijuana packages have
washed ashore in Cuba over the years, indicating that American
traffickers were responsible.
   Given the magnitude of the overall drug problem, Alarcon said
both countries could benefit from a cooperative effort in combating
drug trafficking.
   Alarcon spoke to reporters on the eve of tonight's speech by
President Fidel Castro marking the 36th anniversary of his first
armed attack against the military dictatorship he ousted in 1959.
   Hours after Alarcon spoke, an official of the Department of
Revolutionary Orientation, Jorge Gomez Barata, protested Bush
administration plans to beam television broadcasts to Cuba.
   He said Cuba has the technology to jam the broadcasts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
