<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-26 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen Wednesday,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index ended lower after
morning gains.
   The dollar closed at 141.43 yen, down 0.92 yen from the previous
day's 142.35-yen finish. It opened at 141.50 yen and moved between
141.33 yen and 141.58 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 23.07
points, or 0.07 percent, ending the day at 34,515.83. The index had
gained 445.57 points Tuesday, reaching a record high of 34,538.90,
and gained another 159.69 points Wednesday morning before turning
down.
   Dealers said stock buying by investment trust companies pushed
the index up in the morning, then investors began selling to take
profits after gains for five consecutive trading days.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's movement followed trends in
New York and European markets, falling because of expectations that
the second quarter U.S. gross national product figure, to be
announced Thursday, would show little economic growth, traders said.
   Such an indication usually discourages foreign investors from
buying dollars because of the possibility it might lead to interest
rate cuts.
   Securities firms and investment trust companies bought dollars
for U.S. bonds to be issued in early August, said one dealer with a
commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Other traders said investors still were reluctant to buy the yen
due to Japan's political uncertainties.
</TEXT>
