<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     07-26 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourteen Indian Soldiers Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sri Lanka-India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen Indian peacekeeping soldiers
were killed and three injured when Tamil rebels detonated
remote-controlled explosives in northeastern Sri Lanka, military
officials said today.
   The Indian soldiers were travelling in a truck when the
explosion occured Tuesday at Mullipothnai, about 160 miles
northeast of Colombo, the Sri Lankan officials said.
   Indian diplomats said they had no immediate information on the
report.
   The Sri Lankan military officials said 17 Indian soldiers were
in the truck when explosives, buried in the road, were detonated.
   The officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
blamed the attack on the dominant Tamil rebel group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   Tamil rebels started a violent campaign in 1983 to carve out a
separate homeland, claiming their ethnic minority was being
discriminated against by the Sinhalese majority.
   Tamils form 18 percent of the island's 16 million people, while
Sinhalese make up 75 percent and dominate the government and
military.
   Neighboring India sent a peacekeeping force to Sri Lanka nearly
two years ago to disarm Tamil guerrillas and oversee a peace
accord. But the Tamil Tigers refused to surrender their weapons.
   India got involved in the conflict because it is the dominant
power in the region and because of the sympathies of its own 60
million Tamils.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has demanded that the India
withdraw its troops by the end of July, but Indian says a premature
pullout would lead to even more violence. About 15,000 people,
including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have been killed in the past six
years of ethnic violence.
   Work in almost all state and commercial banks and some
government and private offices in Colombo came to a standstill
today as workers heeded a call by the Workers Action Front for a
three-day protest against the Indian presence.
   The front, a shadowy group whose orders are issued through wall
posters and leaflets, organized the transport strike that crippled
most of the country from mid-June to mid-July.
   Sri Lankan military officers say the Workers Action Front is
linked to a Sinhalese extremist group, the People's Liberation
Front, which accuses the government of making too many concessions
to Tamils and not being firm enough in getting rid of the Indian
soldiers.
   The government blames Sinhalese extremists for 4,000 political
killings in the past two years, including 3,000 since Premadasa
took office as president in January. Most of the victims were
Sinhalese government officials or supporters.
   Fourteen people, including three soldiers and two policemen,
were killed by Sinhalese extremists Tuesday and early Wednesday in
the Sinhalese heartland of southern and central Sri Lanka,
officials said.
</TEXT>
