<SECOND>PM-Hastings, 1st ld-writethru, a0459,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Denies Wiretap Leak, Offer of Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf to CORRECT salary to $89,500</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Judge Alcee Hastings, fighting
impeachment charges before a Senate panel, already has convinced
one panel member that wiretap charges are too weak to warrant
removing him from the bench.
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., surprised his fellow panel members
Tuesday when he said that even if the wiretap evidence were viewed
in the most damaging way, it would be too weak to warrant removing
Hastings from the U.S. District Court bench in Florida.
   Hastings testified before the panel Tuesday that he never leaked
wiretap information to the mayor of Dade County, Fla., and was not
offered money to fix a case.
   ``I did not tell Mayor (Steve) Clark anything about anything,
anytime on earth,'' Hastings said, appearing as a witness before
the 12-member panel hearing evidence in the case. ``I take great
stock in my ability to keep a secret.''
   The wiretap charges contend that Hastings compromised three FBI
investigations by leaking wiretap information over which he had
jurisdiction.
   Hastings, 52, also is accused of plotting with Washington
attorney William Borders to obtain a $150,000 payoff.
   The panel is hearing evidence to report to the full Senate,
which will decide whether to remove Hastings, who is paid $89,500 a
year.
   Gorton told fellow lawmakers his conclusion did not apply to the
other articles of impeachment against Hastings approved by the
House a year ago. No other lawmakers joined in his statement.
   ``Sen. Gorton, as he said, was speaking for himself,'' Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., told reporters, adding that he preferred to
wait until all the evidence was presented to decide.
   Hastings is expected to return to the witness chair later to
testify on the bribery allegations.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., however, asked the judge Tuesday if
money to fix a case had ever been offered by Borders, once an
influential figure in Washington who was convicted of bribery
conspiracy in 1983 and now is refusing to answer questions before
the panel.
   ``None whatsoever,'' Hastings replied.
   Hastings told the panel that when he was confronted by two Miami
reporters concerning rumors that he had disclosed the wiretap
information ``I was absolutely livid in the way this information
was coming to me.''
   ``It was rife in the courthouse and it was bouncing all over the
place,'' Hastings said. ``It is hard for me to control my rage as I
speak now.''
   He acknowledged under questioning from lawmakers that he did not
cooperate at first with the Justice Department's investigation of
the wiretap leak.
   He said that was because he felt officials treated him unfairly
in connection with the bribery conspiracy case and that he thought
they were likely to do so again.
</TEXT>
