<FIRST>r a PM-DealerConvicted     07-26 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dealer Convicted,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brooklyn Jury Finds `Uzi' Edwards Guilty of Murder, Drug Racketeering</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jonny in 9th graf cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jamaican drug dealer nicknamed ``Uzi'' who
helped introduce crack into the city was convicted of killing six
people and injuring more than a dozen others to further his empire.
   Delroy ``Uzi'' Edwards, a 30-year-old illegal alien from
Jamaica, glowered at the jury in federal court in Brooklyn Tuesday
as the foreman announced guilty verdicts to all 42 charges against
him.
   The panel expressed concern for their safety before delivering
their verdict. U.S. District Judge Raymond J. Dearie ordered
marshals to escort jurors from the courthouse and assured them
their names would not be revealed.
   Edwards was convicted of participating in four murders in
Brooklyn and one each in Washington, D.C., and Baltimore to get rid
of rival drug dealers and maintain discipline in his own ranks.
   He also was found guilty of 17 assaults, one maiming, kidnapping
and weapons charges and running a continuing criminal enterprise.
   The murder victims included four of Edwards' employees, a rival
drug dealer and an innocent bystander. They occurred during a
12-month period ending in December 1987.
   ``I assume he's going to appeal. Other than that I have no
comment,'' said Edwards' court-appointed lawyer, David Gordon. He
faces several life sentences on the convictions.
   Edwards also faces a state murder charge for a July 4, 1987,
slaying in a Brooklyn discotheque. Edwards, who has been in jail
since he was arrested on the murder charge in March 1988, was
returned to his cell at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in
Manhattan.
   During the six-week trial, Assistant U.S. Attorney Jonny J.
Frank described the brutal methods of the 50-member gang of
Jamaicans headed by Edwards that sold marijuana, crack and cocaine
in New York and later extended its operations to Washington,
Philadelphia and Baltimore.
   In an indictment handed up last December and in the
prosecution's presentation to the jury, the government told of a
drug operation that brought in up to $100,000 a day.
   Innocent bystanders were not immune to the rage of a man known
on the street as ``Uzi'' because he frequently carried one of the
small machine guns under his trench coat.
   Some of Edwards' victims were ``people who happened to be at the
wrong place at the wrong time,'' Frank said.
   Those who testified included Edward's second-in-command, a
30-year-old murderer and drug dealer named Kenneth Manning,
described to the jury how he participated in the grotesque
Edwards-ordered murder of an errant co-worker, ``Egghead,'' who was
beaten with bats and then doused with boiling water.
   Prosecutors said Edwards made ``mountains of money'' after
introducing crack, the powerful cocaine-based drug, in a poor
Brooklyn neighborhood in 1985.
   He owned luxury cars, real estate, fancy clothes and once paid
$150,000 in $10 and $20 bills to purchase a home in Amityville,
they said.
</TEXT>
