<FIRST>r i PM-India-Rain     07-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Rain,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty-Seven Feared Dead in Landslide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landslide triggered by torrential rains
buried a small village in the western state of Maharashtra and all
37 inhabitants were feared dead, police said today.
   The landslide, which occurred Monday in Bhaji village, was set
off by a fierce storm that has been blamed for at least 455 deaths
this week.
   The casualties are believed to be the highest during the monsoon
in recent years, authorities said. The Press Trust of India news
agency estimated the damage to crops and livestock in the millions
of dollars.
   Bhaji is about 165 miles southeast of the state capital, Bombay.
   Large boulders and tons of mud crashed down on houses built on
the hill during the storm, said a police official in Pune, the
closest town to Bhaji.
   ``It is highly unlikely that survivors will be found,'' said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Soldiers were working to remove the debris but little progress
has been made because the boulders were very heavy, he said.
   At least 315 people have died in Maharashtra during three days
of incessant rain that set off landslides and flash floods and
uprooted trees and houses, authorities said.
   Elsewhere in India, at least 140 people died in the storm that
originated in the Bay of Bengal and traveled across the country to
the western coast.
</TEXT>
