<FIRST>r a PM-MaritalSodomy     07-26 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marital Sodomy,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Liberties Union Eyeing Case for Privacy Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers considering a challenge to Georgia's
156-year-old anti-sodomy law said a man's prison sentence for
having sex with his wife shows the statute could be abused in
bitter divorce fights.
   James Moseley, a 34-year-old carpenter, was convicted of one
sodomy charge after admitting on the witness stand that he engaged
in oral sex with his common-law wife of four years, Bette Roberts.
   Sodomy is a felony in Georgia, even if the parties are
consenting husband and wife.
   Moseley was charged with two counts of rape, two counts of
aggravated oral sodomy and two counts of aggravated anal sodomy
stemming from two February 1988 encounters with Ms. Roberts.
   In May 1988, a jury acquitted Moseley of five of the six
charges, but convicted him of one sodomy charge because of his
admission on the stand. Moseley was sentenced to five years in
prison. The couple is divorced.
   The American Civil Liberties Union is considering asking the
state Court of Appeals to accept a late appeal on Moseley's behalf
or filing a habeas corpus action directly challenging his
incarceration, said Judd Herndon, an ACLU attorney.
   ``Heterosexuals today do not perceive themselves to be at risk
(under the sodomy law). ... They felt themselves immune. Mr.
Moseley has rudely found out that husbands and wives are not
immune,'' Herndon said.
   ``The Georgia sodomy law now becomes a weapon that can be used
by feuding spouses in a divorce action, and that ought to scare
every husband and wife in this state.''
   There are sodomy laws in 25 states, and seven of those apply the
law only to relations between homosexuals, according to the
National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
   Steven Lister, Moseley's lawyer at the trial, said he had no
idea Moseley's confession would be used against him.
   Superior Court Judge William H. Ison told the jurors that they
had the option of finding Moseley guilty of the lesser crime of
simple sodomy.
   State Rep. Charles Thomas, chairman of the Georgia House
Judiciary Committee, said he doubts lawmakers will attempt to
change the sodomy law in 1990 unless the courts tell them to do so.
   Georgia Attorney General Michael Bowers said Tuesday his office
isn't involved in the case yet and declined to say what stand he
would take on an appeal.
   He also noted that the state argued in an earlier case involving
homosexuals that the sodomy law could not be applied to consensual
acts within a heterosexual marriage.
   In the earlier case, Michael Hardwick of Atlanta was arrested
for engaging in oral sex with another man.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 2-1 in 1985 that
the law violated Hardwick's right to privacy. On appeal, the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled 5-4 in 1986 that the Constitution does not
protect homosexual relations between consenting adults, even in the
privacy of their homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
