<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-26 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Fall From Record High; Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index declined today
from its record high, and the dollar fell against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 34,515.83, down
23.07 points, or 0.07 percent, from the record high of 34,538.90 it
reached Tuesday with a gain of 445.57 points.
   ``The index was higher in morning trading as investors were
reassured by the yen's strength against the dollar,'' Nomura
Securities analyst Yoshiro Inoue said.
   But in the afternoon, investors were selling to take profits
after five days of gains, he said. He added that uncertainties over
U.S. second quarter gross national product figures to be released
Thursday contributed to the index's decline.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 1
billion shares, unchanged from the previous day.
   Housing-related issues gained after a news report that the Labor
Ministry would reduce income taxes related to rents, Inoue said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 141.43 yen, down 0.92
yen from the previous day's 142.35-yen finish. It opened at 141.50
yen and moved between 141.33 yen and 141.58 yen.
   Minori Takeuchi, a Chemical Bank dealer, said, ``Although many
investors were inclined to sell the dollar, they bought it back
whenever the rate went down near the 141-yen line.''
   Ms. Takeuchi said the market was awaiting the U.S. GNP figures
as an important indicator od whether the United States would relax
its monetary policy. Lower U.S. interest rates make the dollar less
attractive to foreign investors.
