<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Southeast; Cold Front Over Rockies, Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered thunderstorms today lingered in the lower Mississippi
Valley and southeast Texas, and fog covered much of the Northeast.
   On Tuesday, storm winds blew down trees and power lines in
southern Atlantic Coast states.
   In several northern Georgia communities, wind felled trees,
including two that landed on an automobile in Marietta, north of
Atlanta. The thunderstorms brought large hail to the area.
   Winds also toppled trees and power lines in Asheville, N.C.
   A small tornado moved through Beaumont, Texas, on Tuesday, but
it did little damage. One large building lost its tin roof.
   A cold front moving across the northern Plains and central
Rockies dropped temperatures to as low as 50 degrees early today
and brought thunderstorms to Wyoming and North Dakota.
   Fog developed this morning over much of the Atlantic Coast
states, the upper Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from northern Illinois
into northern Indiana, central West Virginia and over Maryland and
southern New Jersey.
   The high temperature in the nation Tuesday was 116 degrees at
Bullhead City, Ariz., and Lake Havasu City, Ariz.
   Today's foreceast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
from eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast region into Florida, as
well as from the southern and central Appalachians across the upper
Ohio Valley into northern New England. Showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast this afternoon and evening across the southern
Rockies into the southern Plateau.
   Predicted highs: 60s and 70s along parts of the Pacific Coast;
70s in the southern Rockies; 80s along the western half of the Gulf
Coast and in the Pacific Northwest, as well as from the middle
Mississippi Valley across the central Plains and Oklahoma to
western Texas and eastern parts of Colorado; above 100 degrees in
the desert Southwest, inland valleys of central and southern
California and southern Idaho; and 90s for much of the rest of the
nation.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 50 degrees
at Laramie, Wyo., to 95 at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 partly cloudy; Boston 77 foggy; Buffalo 74
foggy; Charleston, S.C., 73 fair; Cincinnati 74 fair; Cleveland 75
hazy; Detroit 70 partly cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 74 foggy;
Philadelphia 76 hazy; Pittsburgh 72 foggy; Portland, Maine, 73
cloudy; Washington 78 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 78 fair; Chicago 76 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
73 partly cloudy; Denver 67 fair; Des Moines 70 fair; Indianapolis
73 fair; Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 76 partly
cloudy; Nashville 77 fair; New Orleans 73 fair; St. Louis 75 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 61 showers; Anchorage 60 fair; Las Vegas 93
fair; Los Angeles 64 foggy; Phoenix 92 fair; Salt Lake City 75
fair; San Diego 66 fair; San Francisco 57 cloudy; Seattle 69 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 73 fair; Toronto 72 foggy.
