<FIRST>r a PM-Klan-Suit     07-26 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Klan-Suit,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Klan Leader Says Race Relations Course Won't Change His Attitude</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Ku Klux Klan leader who agreed to
attend a race relations course to settle a lawsuit over a clash
with civil rights marchers says the classroom sessions won't change
his attitude toward blacks.
   ``I will sit through that course, but I will leave with the same
opinion I walk in there with,'' Roger Handley said Tuesday.
   Handley, former grand dragon of the Knights of the Ku Klux Klan,
was one of 10 people named in a federal lawsuit stemming from a
1979 clash between robed Klansmen and black civil rights marchers
in Decatur.
   Under a settlement filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, the
defendants agreed to pay $11,500 in damages to the marchers,
perform community service and refrain from harassing blacks or
joining any Klan or white supremacist group for up to five years.
   The Klansmen also agreed to take a race relations course taught
by civil rights leaders. The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference, said he would help lead
the two one-hour sessions, probably next year in Birmingham.
   Handley told the Birmingham Post-Herald the settlement ``was
just a way of getting out of the lawsuit.''
   ``We could have been in court for six weeks, and with attorneys'
fees, we'd be getting into thousands of dollars just to defend
me,'' he said.
   ``But I haven't changed my opinions whatsoever. I know
race-mixing is wrong,'' he said, adding, ``I don't believe God
meant for any two races to live in one nation.''
   Lowery said he was hopeful the course would ease racial tensions.
   ``This workshop will be an opportunity for these people who are
acting out of racial prejudice to understand themselves a little
more, and for us to understand their motives and what misled them,
and we hope they can see the need to accept the oneness of the
human family,'' Lowery said from SCLC headquarters in Atlanta.
   Handley, however, said the class could serve another purpose.
   ``I've always felt like the more you know about an enemy, the
better off you are. It's possible I may get some very valuable
information that I'll use later on,'' he said.
   Handley said he would abide by the part of the settlement
requiring him to refrain from joining any white supremacist group,
including the Klan, for two years.
   The civil lawsuit was filed after investigators from the
Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery uncovered evidence that
prompted the Justice Department to reopen its investigation of the
May 26, 1979, incident in Decatur.
   The blacks, led by Lowery, were protesting the conviction the
year before of a 19-year-old mentally retarded black man for raping
three white women. Two Klansmen and two blacks were wounded by
gunfire in the ensuing struggle.
   Handley and nine other Klan members were indicted in 1984 on
civil rights charges. All either pleaded guilty or were convicted.
   Earlier this year, Handley and six others drew federal sentences
ranging from two months to two years for their roles in the
violence. One of the 10 has died.
   Handley, a 44-year-old disabled sheet metal worker, spent four
months in jail earlier this year. But he said he committed no crime
and pleaded guilty on the advice of his attorney.
   The civil case was to have gone to trial next week. The
settlement still must receive court approval.
</TEXT>
