<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council President Says Witnesses Should Be Under Oath in Mayor Inquiry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council president said he wants to
put witnesses under oath to get to the truth about murky financial
dealings that have been linked to Mayor Tom Bradley.
   John Ferraro also said Tuesday that the council should have the
power to issue subpoenas and hire special counsel, an apparent sign
of impatience with other investigations of the mayor's affairs.
   City auditors, meanwhile, revealed more details about
alterations to the city's financial records, saying certain details
in bids for city deposits submitted by a savings and loan had been
blotted out with typewriter correction fluid.
   Bradley denied any knowledge about the alterations and dismissed
speculation that he might resign.
   ``To anyone who has any such thoughts, I'll be around here four
years from now, as mayor of this city,'' Bradley told repvestments. ``Nor
have I in any way tried to cover up.''
   But Rittenberg was unable to satisfy council members about the
alterations during his second day of testimony.
   He said two staff members have accused each other of ``whiting
out'' the reference to the mayor on the Far East form. Those two
staff members were expected to be called to testify later this week.
   ``This whole thing reeks,'' Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky told the
treasurer.
   Bradley said he would not comment on the matter until City
Attorney James Hahn has completed an investigation.
   ``Nobody wishes that that thing would be over faster than I
do,'' Bradley said.
   But Ferraro, the council president, complained about the pace of
the attorney's probe. ``Jim Hahn talks rather slowly and I think
the investigation is moving rather slowly, too,'' he said.
   The committee also heard reports of other altered documents.
   Typewriter correction fluid often was used to blot out interest
rate details on bids submitted by Gibraltar Savings and Loan for
city deposits, said John Pearson, an auditor for the City
Administrative Office. Bradley personally held a bond that earned a
favorable interest rate from Gibraltar.
   In one case, Pearson said, a Gibraltar bid of 7.6 percent was
blotted out and a revised bid of 7.5 percent was entered. In
another, the bid dropped from 7.8 percent to 7.4 percent.
   The difference of a few tenths of a percent represents tens of
thousands of dollars in interest payments to the city, Pearson said.
   Gibraltar, an ailing Beverly Hills thrift, was seized by the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which declared the institution
unsound on March 31.
   A statement issued by the thrift Tuesday said an internal review
showed Gibraltar received no special benefit from its transactions
with the city.
   ``We will continue to cooperate fully with city investigators
and will readily comment further when the investigation is
complete,'' Gibraltar's statement concluded.
 
