<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     07-26 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Property Value Plunge Blamed on China Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today announced a winning bid
for a key downtown property that was far below original
expectations, the latest gauge of how China's bloody crackdown has
shaken this territory.
   Great Eagle Co. bid $346 million for the 95,000-square-foot lot,
the last major tract of downtown land expected to be sold by the
government before 1997, when Britain returns Hong Kong to China.
   Hong Kong government property sales are carefully scrutinized
because of the importance the real estate market plays in the
colony's economy and the disproportionate significance property
groups have on the stock exchange.
   The property had been expected to fetch perhaps as much as $641
million before Chinese troops on June 3-4 crushed the pro-democracy
movement, killing hundreds of unarmed civilians.
   But China's suppression has increased fears about the colony's
future under Chinese rule and, since the crackdown, estimates on
the winning bid had been around $385 million or slightly higher.
   Bob Pope, acting director of the government's Buildings and
Lands Department, said he was ``satisfied'' with the winning bid in
view of recent events in China, even though it was below his April
estimate of $513 million.
   ``I regard it as a vote of confidence in the future,'' he said
of the winning bid, noting that the entire project involves an
investment of about $641 million. Great Eagle is expected to build
two office towers on the site.
   ``The sort of returns that are expected probably equate to a
drop in the market somewhat, but not as great as indicated in the
press,'' he said.
   The stock market fell sharply on Friday when news began to leak
about the bids for the lot. It closed today at 2489.03, a modest
drop from Tuesday's 2517.02 closing.
</TEXT>
