<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0749EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxBill 1stLd-Writethru a0457 07-26 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Writers Disagree on Catastrophic Illness Financing</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf, The most, to CORRECT percentage who pay surtax
to 40 sted 60 percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers disagree about whether the
hard-fought changes they voted in the financing of catastrophic
illness insurance for older Americans will stop the complaints of
those who have to pay.
   As a rule, couples with incomes below $25,000 and singles with
incomes under $15,000 would pay slightly more than under current
law. Except for those with highest incomes, most others would pay
less.
   The most important change is cutting by half the surtax paid by
about 40 percent of those 65 and older.
   ``It's a major gain for middle-income seniors'' who would pay a
lower surtax under the amendments approved Tuesday by the House
Ways and Means Committee, said Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich.
   But people with incomes under about $20,000 a year will have to
pay a higher flat monthly premium, said Rep. Brian Donnelly, D-Mich.
   ``That's regressive,'' he said, adding that he will continue
efforts to repeal the program.
   The committee's amendment, approved in a closed-door session by
a 19-17 vote, would allow older Americans a one-time chance to turn
down catastrophic coverage _ but only if they also give up Medicare
Part B, which covers doctors' bills.
   Because of that condition, Donnelly said, the program ``is about
as voluntary as a prison sentence.''
   The panel reversed itself and agreed to retain the law that
permits individuals to deduct 10 percent of interest on credit
cards, education loans and car loans next year. To help pay for
continuing a special tax benefit for banks and corporate
executives, the committee had voted earlier to end the writeoff
after this year, when a 20 percent deduction is permitted.
   Resolving the catastrophic issue left the committee with one
major issue: whether to reduce the tax on capital gains, which
applies to profits from sales of stocks and other property.
   President Bush wants a reduction to stimulate the economy,
saying it would raise revenues. Democratic leaders, including
Speaker Thomas Foley and committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski of
Illinois, oppose a cut because the bulk of the benefit would go to
high-income Americans. Democrats also insist a cut would lose money
after a year or two.
   A majority of the committee _ 13 Republicans and six Democrats _
backs a capital-gains cut, but Rostenkowski has delayed a vote
while he attempts to change some minds.
   On the catastrophic illness issue, the committee voted to:
   _Cut the surtax in half. Current law requires anyone eligible
for Medicare to pay a surtax of 15 percent of federal income tax
over $150, but no one with less income pays the surtax. About 60
percent pay some surtax, but fewer than 6 percent pay the maximum,
which this year is $800.
   Under the committee action, the surtax would be cut to 7.5
percent this year and 12.5 percent next year. It would rise to 14
percent by 1993.
   _Raise the flat monthly premium that all but the poorest
retirees pay for catastrophic coverage. Current law sets that
premium at $4 in 1989, $4.90 next year, and $10.20 by 1993. That is
in addition to the monthly premium, now $27.90, paid for Part B
Medicare coverage. The charge is scheduled to rise to $29 next year
and to $33.40 by 1993.
   The committee voted to raise the total monthly premium to $38.40
in 1990, with additional increases of 50 cents in 1991 and 10 cents
in each of the following two years.
   _Increase the prescription deductible, the annual amount of
out-of-pocket expenses for drugs that a beneficiary must pay before
catastrophic reimbursement begins, to $650 in 1991 and $950 in
1992. Those figures are $200 and $300, respectively, above current
law. Most of the drug coverage does not begin until 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
