<FIRST>r i PM-France-ElasticJumps 1stLd-Writethru a0517 07-26 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Elastic Jumps, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Bans Elastic Jumping Fad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 5th pvs, ``This is...'' to CORRECT that statement
issued late last week, sted today. Pickup 6th, ``There was...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is now illegal in France to tie an elastic band
to your feet and jump off into the void.
   The practice had become a minor fad, with the courageous or
reckless flinging themselves off, for example, the Eiffel Tower and
bouncing headfirst several times in midair.
   The government issued its temporary ban last week after a third
death this year resulting from the fad.
   Emmanuel Bottin, a 27-year-old Frenchman, was killed July 18
when the elastic band attaching him to a bridge in the Alps snapped
on the third bounce, dropping him into the rocks 100 feet below.
   ``This is a new and dangerous physical activity,'' the French
Interior and Sports Ministries said in a joint statement late last
week. ``Such an activity cannot continue without serious guarantees
for the safety of the participants being required of organizers.''
   There was no indication how long it would take to draw up
regulations under which the sport could resume.
</TEXT>
