<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Fires     07-26 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Fires,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lightning Causes New Forest Fires in Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning has ignited new forest fires
in central Canada, and 23,000 people were kept from returning home
in three provinces.
   ``We're not making any plans to move anybody back,'' Ryan Kustra
of the Manitoba Department of Natural Resources said Tuesday night.
``Until the situation is stablized and safe, we're not going to
move them back and then move them out again.''
   The fires, the region's worst in memory, have destroyed more
than 3.7 million acres of forest in northern Manitoba, Saskatchewan
and Ontario.
   However, no injuries or deaths have been reported.
   Light rain cooled some fires Tuesday, but lightning caused
others. More showers were expected today.
   In northeastern Saskatchewan, rain dampened two fires
threatening the community of Sandy Bay. But spokesmen for the
provincial forest fire management center said the fires still were
burning.
   ``It's too large to be brought under control in one day,'' said
duty officer Darryl Rowland. ``We'd need a lot more rain to put it
out.''
   At least 200 firefighters are battling the area's blazes. One
crew cut through more than a mile of brush with axes as it tried to
halt approaching flames.
   Fred Bear of Sandy Bay has been cooking for a 10-man crew
fighting fire in the area for the last week. Flames came within 60
yards of their camp.
   ``The smoke was so thick that we had to wrap wet towels around
our faces to breathe,'' he said Tuesday.
   Since Thursday, more than 23,000 people had to leave homes in
remote northern communities as flames advanced. They are staying in
hotels, schools, churches and privates homes.
   About 225 fires were burning in Manitoba, 150 in Ontario, and
about 165 in Saskatchewan, officials said. Most have been caused by
lightning.
   Roads in the fire areas are virtually shut down.
   Manitoba Premier Gary Filmon has said firefighting efforts there
and the massive evacuation will cost more than $30 million.
   In Ottawa on Tuesday, Prime Minister Brian Mulroney promised
``every conceivable support'' from the federal government.
   In northern Ontario, rescuers on Tuesday airlifted out 44 people
stranded in the community of Kasabonika. The area was blanketed in
smoke from five forest fires.
   Almost 600 people _ mostly elderly people with breathing
problems and mothers and children _ have fled northwestern Ontario
in the last week.
</TEXT>
