<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Student     07-26 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Student,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Goes to North Korea to Escort Back Radical Student</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest flew to North
Korea today to escort a radical student from the South back across
the border. The government in Seoul threatened to arrest them both.
   Government prosecutors said the nation's intelligence agency
also would launch an investigation of dissident Catholics.
   South Korea bans unauthorized trips to communist North Korea
such as the one made by the 20-year-old student, Im Su-kyong.
   The government has also declared the border crossing would
violate the cease-fire accord that ended the Korean War and said
both the student and priest will be arrested after entering South
Korea.
   The Association of Priests for Justice, a Catholic dissident
group, said Moon Gyu-hyon, a Philippines-based priest, flew to
North Korea's capital, Pyongyang, via Tokyo and Beijing. The
association sponsored the trip.
   Moon was recently assigned to the Philippines after he finished
studies at New York's Maryknoll Seminary.
   ``The church has the duty to protect its lamb,'' said a
statement from the Seoul-based group.
   It said the group believed Ms. Im had made the trip ``in a move
representing the patriotic sentiments of young students for
unification.''
   ``She is a Catholic. It is our duty to support her,'' said the
statement.
   While in North Korea, Ms. Im attended an international youth
festival July 1-8.
   The Catholic group's statement said Moon holds a South Korean
passport and a permanent U.S. residence permit. It said he was
expected to return with Ms. Im through the border village of
Panmunjom on Thursday.
   That day marks the anniversary of the cease-fire that ended the
1950-53 Korean War between the North and South. The crossing would
carry symbolic value for radicals and dissidents who are demanding
Korean reunification.
   The Korean Central News Agency, North Korea's official news
service, said today that Ms. Im had arrived in the town of Kaesong
near Panmunjom. The report, monitored in Tokyo, said she was
traveling as part of a group of 30 anti-nuclear peace marchers who
favor reunification. It quoted her as telling a rally in Kaesong
that the peninsula should be united.
   Radical students and dissidents in South Korea said rallies
would be held to welcome her home, but attempts to hold protests in
recent weeks have been thwarted by police. National Police Director
Kim Woo-hyun said authorities will block any attempts by protesters
to reach Panmunjom to greet Ms. Im.
   The Joong-ang Daily News said 20,000 riot police would be placed
on alert for demonstrations in Seoul.
   Government prosecutors said the Agency for National Security
Planning, the intelligence agency, would investigate 16 Catholic
priests who belong to the standing committee of the Association of
Priests for Justice.
   The prosecutors said the priests would be investigated in
connection with laws that prohibit unauthorized visits to the north.
</TEXT>
