<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0921EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Floods 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0493,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Swamp Southern Region; 36 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with more casualties, higher rainfall,
damages. Pickup 7th pvs, ``Most of ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains drenched South Korea's
southern coast, spawning floods and mudslides that killed at least
36 people and forced thousands from their homes, officials said
today.
   Another 50 people were reported missing in the flooding, which
disrupted air, land and sea travel, the National Disaster Center
said.
   South Korean newspapers, gathering their own statistics,
reported at least 93 people killed or missing and more than 55,000
people driven from their homes.
   By this evening, up to 17.2 inches of rain had fallen in a
two-day period, the center said. Center officials said 34,500
people were homeless because of flooding.
   The disaster center said 7,880 homes and buildings were
inundated or destroyed and estimated losses from damaged crops,
highways and other public facilities at $15 million.
   Most of the homeless were taken to schools, churches and other
makeshift shelters and the government rushed in blankets, food and
other relief supplies, the officials said.
   Hardest hit was South Cholla, which received an average of 13
inches of rain on Monday and Tuesday, the officials said. Thirty
people were killed and 29 others were reported missing in the area.
   Most of the victims were killed in landslides or drowned in
rain-swollen creeks or rivers, they said.
   An emergency evacuation order was issued for about 30,000 people
because of the rising waters of the Youngsan River, they said.
   Weathermen in Kwangju, the capital city of South Cholla, said
the Youngsan's level passed its danger point of 31 feet early
today, the first time it reached that level since the are weather
bureau opened 60 years ago.
   Military helicopters rushed to rescue about 500 people isolated
by the bloated river, officials said.
   Rescuers continued to try to evacuate several hundred people
marooned in the towns of Changsung and Pulkyo, which were virtually
submerged.
</TEXT>
