<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0921EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     07-26 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Running Serial Murder Trial Nears Finale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four-year-old ``Night Stalker'' serial
killing trial of Richard Ramirez is nearing its finale as the fate
of the 29-year-old drifter is submitted to jurors who will weigh 13
murder charges.
   In the final hours of closing arguments, a prosecutor called for
Ramirez to be convicted of gruesome crimes he called ``consummate
acts of cowardice.''
   A defense attorney urged jurors to bring in verdicts of
innocent, claiming there was reasonable doubt that Ramirez really
was the devil-worshipping ``Night Stalker'' who murdered, raped and
robbed his victims while forcing some to ``swear to Satan.''
   Ramirez once shouted ``Hail Satan'' in court and displayed a
pentagram _ the inverted star symbol associated with devil worship
_ drawn on his palm.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan planned to instruct jurors in
the law today, then submit the case for deliberations.
   The tall, shaggy-haired Ramirez, of El Paso, Texas, is charged
with 13 murders and 30 related felonies during a series of slayings
in the summer of 1985. Witnesses have identified him as the
intruder who entered homes through unlocked windows and doors.
   ``These were murders of men in their sleep, rapes and sodomy of
women after their husbands were dead,'' declared Deputy District
Attorney P. Philip Halpin. In the final moments of his reply to
defense arguments Tuesday, the prosecutor reminded jurors of
physical evidence found at several murder scenes that linked
Ramirez to the killings. Among the items were pentagrams.
   ``Some of these cases are carbon copies of each other,'' said
Halpin.
   ``You have all the evidence in the world to reach the logical
and reasonable conclusion that the defendant is guilty as
charged,'' he concluded.
   Earlier, defense attorney Ray Clark suggested there was
reasonable doubt about Ramirez' guilt, that witnesses wrongly
identified him as the ``Night Stalker.''
   ``I'm asking you to go in, take a look at all the evidence,
discuss it among yourselves and come back with 43 not-guilty
verdicts,'' he told the jury.
   He acknowledged that Ramirez confessed he was the ``Night
Stalker'' but insisted he did it because he thought such
``bravado'' would impress other prisoners.
   ``Jail is a dangerous place to be,'' Clark said, ``and in the
pecking order the murderers get the most respect.''
   Halpin, in his reply, stressed that Ramirez has no contact with
other prisoners.
   ``If murderers are treated better (in jail) it doesn't matter,''
he said, ``because he's kept segregated. He's off in a room alone
for obvious reasons.''
   Two witnesses have said Ramirez told them: ``I am the Night
Stalker.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
