<DOCNO> AP890726-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0922EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-26 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ships Sail into Besieged Christian Ports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cargo ships sailed into Christian ports
today to deliver food to the besieged Christian enclave, drawing
only light fire from Syrian gunners. A newspaper said an informal
truce was in effect.
   A police spokesman, said two of the vessels dropped anchor at
Beirut port in the city's Christian sector and three arrived in the
port of Jounieh, in the Christian heartland.
   The spokesman refused to give any information about the ships.
   He said Syrian gunners, deployed in Moslem west Beirut, fired
``only six howitzer shells'' at the Christian-controlled coastline
as the ships steamed slowly into dock.
   He said no casualties were reported and noted it was ``very
unusual of the Syrians not to fire heavily'' at ships heading for
ports in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   The daily newspaper An-Nahar said an ``undeclared truce'' had
taken effect in the 19-week confrontation between Gen. Michel
Aoun's Christian forces and Moslem militias allied with Syrian
troops. The report could not be confirmed.
   The Syrian land and sea blockade imposed March 8 has left the
Christian community desperately short of fuel, food and other
supplies. It was imposed after Aoun blockaded illegal militia-run
ports south of Beirut.
   A spokesman for Aoun's headquarters who refused to be named
confirmed that ``several vessels'' anchored at Christian ports
overnight and said the Syrians ``fired a only few rounds... I don't
know why their barrage was not as intense as it usually is.''
   Also today, Syrian and Christian forces skirmished with
automatic rifles across Beirut's dividing Green Line, wounding nine
people.
   That raised the overall toll to 453 killed and 1,869 wounded in
the current round of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   An-Nahar said a three-member Arab League committee had won a
temporary truce after ``discreet contacts'' with the warring sides.
   The paper said the ``combatants agreed to give the committee
another chance to bring about a peaceful end to the conflict.'' It
did not elaborate.
   An-Nahar noted, however, that in the absence of any official
truce announcement ``it is not known how long the cease-fire would
last.''
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, King Hassan II of Morocco and
Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid were asked at an Arab League
summit in May to settle the Lebanese conflict by November.
   The Kuwaiti daily newspaper Al-Qabas, in a front-page report,
said the Arab committee has decided to freeze its mediation due to
Syria's refusal to accept Aoun as a negotiating partner.
   The paper quoted Syrian President Hafez Assad as telling the
Saudi, Moroccan and Algerian foreign ministers during a recent
meeting in Damascus: ``If our Lebanese allies accept Aoun as a
negotiator on behalf of the other party, we will not accept him.
This is a final and irreversible decision.''
   ``Accordingly, the three-member commitee has decided to freeze
its activities for a short period of time, pending a solution to
this snag,'' the report added.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, declared a ``war of liberation''
against Syria's 40,000 troops, who were deployed in predominantly
Moslem sections of Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate.
   The Christians contend the Syrian troops betrayed their mandate
by fighting on the Moslem side in the civil war.
</TEXT>
