<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0519 07-26 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks to Seek Treatment at White Hospitals in Defiance Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes type on 2nd graf. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``Vlok contended...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks will seek medical care
at eight whites-only hospitals next week as part of a defiance
campaign protesting discrimination and segregated national
elections, anti-apartheid leaders announced today.
   The activists detailed the first phase of the campaign a day
after Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok threatened to crack down
on ``revolutionaries and radicals'' who were organizing the
protests.
   Vlok contended that the civil disobedience campaign, as well as
terrorist attacks, had been ordered by the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla movement in an effort to disrupt the
Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. Parliament has chambers for
whites, Asians and people of mixed-race, but the black majority is
excluded.
   A coalition of anti-apartheid groups, in statements issued at a
news conference, accused Vlok of trying to foster paranoia among
white voters and said the defiance campaign would be non-violent.
   ``It is our right to defy the criminal and illegal apartheid
regulations, which are denying our people the right to health care,
education, housing,'' one statement said. ``The government claims
to be dismantling apartheid. Our experience tells us otherwise.''
   Saki Macozome, an official of the South African Council of
Churches, said non-whites who required medical care would seek
treatment starting Aug. 2 at four white hospitals in Transvaal
Province and four in Natal Province.
   ``We will consider all hospitals to be open to all people from
Aug. 2 onwards,'' said a statement endorsed by the church council
and several leading anti-apartheid groups. These included the Black
Sash civil rights organization and the Congress of South African
Trade Union, the country's largest black labor federation.
   The groups gave no details about other planned actions during
the defiance campaign, but they confirmed that segregated
recreational facilities would be targeted. Activists denied Vlok's
allegation that the campaign would include fire-bomb attacks on the
homes of parliamentary candidates.
   Health Minister Willie van Niekerk said the authorities would
not allow health care to be disrupted by protesters.
   ``Any patient suffering from an acute illness will not be turned
away before receiving the necessary treatment, regardless of their
population group,'' van Niekerk said, adding that such patients
would be charged standard fees.
   People not requiring urgent care ``will be requested to leave
the premises in an orderly fashion,'' he said.
   Vlok, in a speech Tuesday, said disruptions of the election
campaign must be stopped ``at all costs.''
   However, the anti-apartheid groups said a crackdown on peaceful
protests could trigger a backlash.
   ``While the white leaders are campaigning to be elected, they
are once again planning to place the black leadership behind
bars,'' the statement said. ``Such actions by the state are
precisely what would precipitate the kind of uncontrolled violence
which Vlok is accusing us of planning.''
</TEXT>
