<FIRST>r a PM-People-RingoStarr     07-26 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Ringo Starr,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ringo's Album Blocked; Former Beatle Wins 30-Day Court Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Beatle Ringo Starr, on his first U.S. tour
in more than a decade, has succeeded in blocking the release of an
album that he's displeased with.
   The album, due to be released this week, was put on hold Tuesday
for 30 days by a Superior Court judge while lawyers for the rock
star and a Memphis producer try to settle the issue.
   Judge Ralph Hicks continued a temporary order Starr had obtained
Monday, after he said he didn't like his drum performances and
wanted to redub them before the album's release.
   Starr also balked at a demand by CRS Records of College Park and
producer Chips Moman of Memphis, Tenn., that he pay them $146,239
to prevent release of the recordings, which Starr made in February
and April 1987. Moman had rejected Starr's offer of $100,000.
   Starr's lawyers accused Moman of trying to release the album on
an ``unheard-of label'' to take advantage of the former Beatle's
concert tour, which began earlier this month.
   Attorney Jane Stevens said CRS Records, which Moman formed with
a partner in April, could not handle the album ``in a manner
befitting an artist of (Starr's) stature.''
   Moman acknowledged that the label is new and operates out of his
lawyer's offices. But he said he wants to put the album out before
Starr has a chance to put out a live recording from his tour and
``kill any chances I got of getting anything off this product.''
   He also said he was frustrated by repeated efforts to reach the
singer and by Starr's refusal to use any song from the album during
his tour.
   Starr contended in his lawsuit that the original recordings'
quality was not up to his standards because Moman brought alcoholic
beverages to the recording sessions.
</TEXT>
