<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i HongKong-BoatPeople     07-26 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>Hong Kong-Boat People,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong to Investigate Harassment of Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government acknowledged today that
Vietnamese asylum-seekers have complained of rough treatment by
police guarding their detention center and promised a thorough
investigation.
   The police assaults, first brought to light by the U.N. agency
for refugees, allegedly occurred during a weekend disturbance at
the Sek Kong detention center, where more than 7,000 Vietnamese are
kept in tents.
   They are among the 50,000 Vietnamese languishing in this British
colony after fleeing their Communist hommeland by boat.
   Authorities claim the violence began when about 200 Vietnamese
hurled stones Sunday night at guards who were trying to prevent
detainees from slipping through holes cut in the barbed wire
fencing around the camp. The unrest flared again several hours
later.
   Police originally said only four Vietnamese requested treatment
for injuries after the incident, including three who said they were
hurt accidentally. Police also said the death of a Vietnamese man
that night was not due to natural causes but provided no further
details.
   A police spokesman said today that the police have not received
any formal complaints since the unrest.
   However, Secretary for Security Geoffrey Barnes said in a
statement today, ``There have been complaints from detainees of
unduly rough handling by the police. All allegations against the
government staff concerned will be fully and swiftly investigated.''
   The statement did not say how many complaints had been received,
although the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees office
has said a ``considerable number'' of Vietnamese were injured.
   Robert Van Leeuwen, the head of the U.N. agency in Hong Kong,
told government-funded radio that similar incidents on a smaller
scale have occurred in the past at other centers where Vietnamese
are kept.
   ``Perhaps a more general look at the management of certain
centers would be in order,'' said Van Leeuwen, who was expected to
submit a report to Hong Kong authorities on complaints of police
behavior.
   The Vietnamese at Sek Kong are among the boat people who must
prove they fled political persecution or face repatriation.
   Local media have reported growing tension in the detention
centers amid signs that Britain and Vietnam are near agreement on a
program of forcefully repatriating boat people who do not qualify
as refugees.
</TEXT>
