<DOCNO> AP890726-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Rubell     07-26 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Rubell,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studio 54 Owner Steve Rubell Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entrepreneur Steve Rubell, the Studio 54
co-owner who presided over New York nightlife when disco was at its
peak, died early today at age 45.
   Rubell died in a Manhattan hospital of complications from
hepatitis and septic shock, said his publicist, Dan Klores.
   Rubell and partner Ian Schrager became the crown princes of
Manhattan nightlife when they operated Studio 54 in the late 1970s,
luring Andy Warhol, Bianca Jagger, Liz Taylor, Liza Minnelli and a
slew of celebrities to their exclusive club.
   Rubell worked the door of the club after its April 26, 1977,
opening, deciding who would and would not be admitted. During those
heady days, he failed to recognize John Kennedy Jr. and Warren
Beatty, sending both away.
   Rubell and Schrager's reign was cut short by a 1979 conviction
for tax evasion. In January 1980, they were sentenced to 3{ years
in prison. By turning in several other club owners, they reduced
their sentences and were released from an Alabama prison a year
later.
   They sold Studio 54 soon afterward and channeled their efforts
into the hotel business. Within four years of their prison release,
Rubell and Schrager were operating Morgans hotel in Manhattan and
running another nightclub, the Palladium.
   Once again, Rubell became a fixture in the club scene. Opening
night at the Palladium attracted singer Boy George, actor Matt
Dillon and other celebrities.
   The partners also continued their hotel work, renovating and
reopening the Royalton hotel in midtown Manhattan. They also were
renovating a hotel off Times Square and had purchased a third on
the East Side.
   Rubell is survived by his father, Philip, and mother, Ann; his
brother, Donald, and sister-in-law, Mera; and a niece and nephew. A
private funeral service will be held Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0084 </DOCNO>
