<DOCNO> AP890726-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     07-26 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Rulers Said to Have Released Nearly 4,000 Criminals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military rulers have released
nearly 4,000 convicted criminals under a recent government amnesty,
the state newspaper reported today.
   Under an amnesty announced July 20, death sentences were
commuted to life imprisonment, life sentences were reduced to 10
years, and other punishments were cut by two-thirds. The order said
criminal cases still being heard are to be closed.
   The amnesty applies only to those who committed offenses before
Sept. 18 1988, the day the military moved to crush a nationwise
pro-democracy uprising. It does not apply to cases of high treason
or breaches of martial law stipulations imposed since then.
   Martial law is aimed at preventing an upsurge of popular
discontent against authoritarian rule similar to that seen last
year. Gatherings of more than five people are forbidden, and
freedom of speech is greatly curtailed.
   On July 18, the eve of a planned opposition rally, the military
tightened martial law and threatened death sentences for offenders.
   In five days since the amnesty was announced, the Working
People's Daily, the English-language edition of the only legal
newspaper in Burma, said 3,944 prisoners had been released.
   A total of 155 people on death row at the time of the
announcement had been given reprieves, the paper said.
   The amnesty was announced the same day the military put under
house arrest the country's two leading opposition figures, Aung San
Suu Kyi and Tin Oo of the National League for Democracy. It accused
them of ``attempting to destroy the military and create anarchy in
the country.''
   A British Embassy spokesman in Bangkok said today that Michael
Aris, the British husband of Ms. Suu Kyi, is under effective house
arrest with her.
   Burma's foreign minister, Ohn Kyaw, denied that Aris was under
detention but said he was not permitted to see British Embassy
officials under the terms of his wife's house arrest.
   ``He (Aris) is under house arrest as far as we are concerned.
His liberty is being curtailed. Maybe he is only under half house
arrest but that is like being only slightly pregnant,'' he said. He
spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with British custom.
   The spokesman said the Foreign Office had summoned the Burmese
ambassador in London and ``protested strongly'' about the treatment
of Aris.
   ``How can they forbid a British subject with a valid visa for
Burma to see someone from the embassy in Rangoon. He is a British
subject and he has every right to go to the embassy,'' the
spokesman said.
   The Foreign Office said Britain's charge d'affaires had been
prevented from seeing Aris, an Oxford University professor and
expert on Tibet, since he arrived at Rangoon airport Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
