<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lonetree-Kunstler     07-26 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lonetree-Kunstler,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lonetree Accuses Lawyers Of Using Case For Publicity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Marine ever convicted of espionage
has accused his former lawyers, including civil rights attorney
William Kunstler, of keeping him in the dark about government
offers to plea bargain.
   In an appeal asking for a new trial or a reduction in Sgt.
Clayton J. Lonetree's 25-year sentence, new attorneys for the St.
Paul native have accused Kunstler and co-counsel William Stuhff of
ignoring plea-bargain overtures. They contend the attorneys hoped
to continue the case as a forum for publicity to embarrass the
military.
   The appeal was filed with the U.S. Navy-Marine Corps Court of
Military Review one week ago but has not been publicized until now,
the Star-Tribune reported today.
   Lonetree, who was a guard at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, was
convicted in 1987 of providing floor plans of the embassy to the
Soviet Union in a sex-for-secrets deal. He was sentenced to 30
years, later reduced to 25 years.
   Lonetree fired Kunstler and Stuhff after his conviction.
   ``If it helps the client, they can say anything they want about
the lawyers,'' Kunstler said Tuesday. ``I almost wish they were
right.'' Kunstler said he cannot recall any government offers that
were not communicated to Lonetree.
   The appeal claims Lonetree was not told by Kunstler or Stuhff
that, early in the case, the government would have agreed to a
five-to-10-year sentence in return for cooperation.
   The appeal, filed by Washington lawyers Lee Calligaro and Daniel
Johnson, also said a military attorney representing Lonetree was
rebuffed by Kunstler and Stuhff when he sought to pursue
plea-bargaining negotiations before trial.
   Stuhff said the appeal's characterization of his efforts on
Lonetree's behalf are ``completely dishonest.'' He said plea
bargaining was aggressively pursued, the government never offered
to settle for as little as five years, and Lonetree was informed of
all offers.
</TEXT>
