<FIRST>r a PM-DrugKingpin     07-26 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Kingpin,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Picked for Trial of Reputed Cocaine Kingpin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed cocaine kingpin whose forced
extradition from Honduras last year sparked rioting in that country
is going on trial this week amid unusually tight security.
   Juan Ramon Matta Ballesteros, 44, is accused of heading a
network that in seven months moved more than a ton of cocaine
valued at $70 million into the United States.
   According to his indictment, officials confiscated 114 pounds of
cocaine and $1.9 million in cash in one raid on the operation. He
was charged in April 1988 with conspiracy, possession of cocaine
with intent to distribute and running a continuing criminal
enterprise.
   Attorneys selected a jury Tuesday in U.S. District Court. People
entering the courtroom had to pass through a metal detector added
for the case.
   Opening arguments were to begin Thursday before Judge Pamela A.
Rymer.
   Matta was arrested aboard a U.S.-bound plane in April 1988 after
he was whisked out of Honduras and taken to the Dominican Republic
by Honduran officials.
   The arrest touched off anti-U.S. rioting in Honduras. The
country's constitution forbids the extradition of Honduran citizens.
   U.S. marshals said an arrest warrant was issued for Matta after
he escaped from Florida's Eglin Federal Prison Camp in 1971. He had
been held there on charges of entering the United States with a
false passport.
   Matta refused to enter a plea at his arraignment, saying his
arrest violated his constitutional rights of due process. Martin
Stolar, his attorney, claimed Matta was tortured while in custody.
   Gurule said a medical examination confirmed that reasonable
force was used to subdue Matta, who resisted arrest. That force
included a hood placed over his head, secured with a cord around
his neck.
</TEXT>
