<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   07-26 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: penny earned.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 20
   The Press-Enterprise, Riverside County, Calif., on the trade
deficit:
   Any way they're read, the trade statistics for the month of May
are not good news.
   The nation seems to be exporting its manufactures about as fast
as it can. In April, American exports amounted to $30.76 billion,
the most ever. And in May, they were off a bare 1 percent; call it
a wash.
   Going as fast as it can, the nation still lost ground like mad.
April's trade deficit of $8.29 billion may sound like a lot on its
face, but in fact it was the best month of the young year. In May,
it's now reported, the deficit puffed up to $10.24 billion.
   Imports were up on every front, but where consumers usually get
the blame, the fingerprints of American businessmen are all over
this deficit. Imports of capital goods, as opposed to consumer
goods, led the parade. ...
   It's one thing, the (experts') reasoning goes, to have consumers
splurging on VCRs, CDs and video cameras. There is a reasonable
expectation that binges like these have to end sooner or later.
   It's another thing to have businesses importing supplies and
equipment. That probably means that these materials are not being
made in this country; at least, not any more.
   That dovetails uncomfortably with the fact that a lot of popular
consumer electronic items no longer are made in America. That all
represents a competitive failure _ and nothing says that has to be
a temporary condition.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 21
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on the tobacco industry and honoraria:
   The Tobacco Institute led all contributors of honoraria (special
interest speaking fees) to members of Congress last year. It
coughed up $123,400 to 85 representatives and eight senators.
   In addition, RJR@Nabisco, Philip Morris and the Smokeless
Tobacco Council bestowed upon fine congressmen an additional
$138,000.
   These are representatives of the same government that tells us
smoking is the chief avoidable cause of death _ the same government
supposedly worried about the thousands who want to kick the habit,
but can't.
   It's a betrayal of public health.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 22
   The Providence (R.I.) Journal-Bulletin on raising taxes:
   The House Ways and Means Committee, which every year gets the
first chance to tell Americans how heavily they will be taxed the
year after, is having a hard time keeping its eyes on the target.
   It is true that taxpayers might applaud the committee if it does
not pass a tax bill at all _ but the members do have a job, and
they should do it.
   Yet, rather than addressing such issues as capital gains tax
cuts and reductions in the levy on the retired elderly for
catastrophic health insurance, the panel has voted $16 billion to
fund a child-care bill yet to be enacted.
   The tax panel has already spent a lot of time finding taxes and
fees to increase _ that is, slicing the sausage thinly in order not
to alarm President Bush who, during the presidential campaign,
pledged to hold the line.
   Until the Democrats on Capitol Hill face up to the election
returns, talk of comity in Congress will remain largely rhetorical,
disguising policy differences that eventually will explode if the
voters' message is spurned.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 23
   The Joplin (Mo.) Globe on the cause of the Alaska oil spill:
   A 110-page report to the National Transportation Safety
Commission by Alaska concludes that poor management by Exxon
Shipping Co. was responsible for the nation's worst oil spill when
the Exxon Valdez went aground March 24 in Alaska's Prince William
Sound.
   In fact, said the man who headed the state's inquiry, management
lapses and failures were so numerous ``that it is a wonder the
Exxon Valdez was the first tanker grounded.''
   That condemnation should come as no surprise. It was apparent in
the first hours after the tanker struck the reef and began losing
11 million gallons of oil that no one really had any idea of what
to do. Vital equipment reportedly was out of service. Emergency
plans for dealing with a spill of such magnitude were either
nonexistent or fantasy. ...
   Oil spills simply must not be considered a risk of doing
business. Congress must ensure that the oil companies have in place
the methods and means for handling future calamities as well as for
preventing them, and Exxon Shipping Co. and Alyeska Pipeline
Service Co. must be required to pay dearly for their failures.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 19
   The Record, Hackensack, N.J., on the Oregon lottery:
   Starting in September, Oregon will sell betting sheets. People
can try their luck at picking the winning teams each week in the
NFL. State officials say they expect their take to be $4 million to
$9 million annually, which would then go to support athletic
programs at the state's universities and colleges.
   But before Oregon starts counting its source of revenue, it
would be wise to take another look at its odds for success. Smart
money says the NFL will file a lawsuit ... (which) is likely to
involve years of costly delays.
   Then there is the matter of bookies. For one thing, they pay a
higher return than the state, and they never ask bettors to report
their winnings to the Internal Revenue Service. The football
lottery may be something less than a smash hit with the public.
   Some bettors will like the convenience of one stop shopping that
allows them to pick up butter, eggs, and the Seattle Seahawks at
plus three points at the local supermarket. But is this really the
best way to fund college sports? Not by a long shot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
