<FIRST>r a PM-ArsenicPoisonings     07-26 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arsenic Poisonings,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Into Arsenic Poisonings Expands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of alleged arsenic
poisonings by a woman charged with killing her former husband and a
boyfriend has expanded to eight cases.
   Detectives have added the deaths of three acquaintances to the
probe of Blanche Taylor Moore, 56, police Lt. Steve Lynch revealed
Tuesday.
   The retired grocery clerk is charged with murder in the 1973
death of her first husband, James Taylor, and in the 1986 death of
her boyfriend, Raymond Reid. She is charged with assault in the
arsenic poisoning of her present husband, the Rev. Dwight Moore,
54, who is under treatment.
   Mrs. Moore, who is scheduled for arraignment Aug. 28, says she
is innocent.
   Investigators previously disclosed they were looking into the
1966 death of Mrs. Moore's father, Parker Kiser, and that of a
longtime co-worker, Mabel Parsons, who died in 1988 at age 61.
   Added to the list of deaths under investigation were those of
Joseph Mitchell, Ina Vinson and John Reiber, all Burlington
residents described by Lynch as acquaintances of Mrs. Moore.
   Refusing to provide details, Lynch said his department was
conducting a preliminary inquiry into the death of Mitchell, a
grocery store butcher whose death in July 1985 was attributed to
arterial hypertension and lack of blood to the brain stem.
   Mitchell's wife, Anne, said that prior to her husband's death,
his hands and feet were numb and surgery to restore the feeling was
unsuccessful. Numbness is a symptom of arsenic poisoning.
   Ms. Vinson, 74, a retired Southern Bell worker, died Aug. 24,
1977, at her home of heart failure, according to her death
certificate.
   Reiber, 77, was a retired hosiery mill worker and a member of
the church at which Mrs. Moore's husband preached. Reiber died Feb.
12, 1988, in his home. His death certificate cites heart failure
and says his condition became acute one to two weeks before his
death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
