<DOCNO> AP890726-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalDerailment 1stLd-Writethru a0514 07-26 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Derailment, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Thousand Evacuees Remain as Chemical Tanker Still Burns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd to UPDATE with fire still burning
this mornign.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chemical fire in a derailed tanker car
burned into a fifth day today after firefighters failed to snuff
it, and an estimated 1,000 residents were forced to spend another
night away from home.
   Officials decided to let the fire burn itself out after attempts
on Tuesday to smother it with sodium bicarbonate powder were
unsuccessful, said a Tittabawassee Township Fire Department
dispatcher, who refused to give his name.
   Authorities met again this morning to discuss whether there is
any way to get the fire out quicker. They have said they cannot
predict how long it will burn because they don't know how much
chemical the car contained.
   The car has been burning since a train owned by CSX
Transportation Inc. derailed around midday Saturday about 90 miles
northwest of Detroit.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, four cars of another CSX train derailed in
Chatham, Ontario, about 80 miles east of Detroit, police said.
Authorities evacuated about 400 residents from a 1-square-mile area
as they unloaded butane and propane gas from the tankers, none of
which were ruptured.
   In Freeland, at least 3,000 people were forced to evacuate
initially, but most of them were allowed to return Monday when the
evacuation zone around the accident site was reduced from 15 square
miles to 4 square miles.
   The area wouldn't be decreased further until the chemical
chlorosilene in the car burned off and two other derailed cars
containing toxic plastic ingredients are removed, CSX spokesman R.
Lindsay Leckie said.
   The other cars remained near the burning car, but neither was
leaking or burning, Leckie said.
   Hydrochloric acid fumes from the burning chlorosilene were
dissipating in the air, CSX officials said.
   Officials have reported no serious injuries from the accident,
but many residents have experienced eye and skin irritation.
   Four people were released from St. Luke's Hospital in nearby
Saginaw following treatment Monday for eye and skin irritation and
nausea, hospital spokeswoman Sally Meter said.
   Alex J. Sagady, environmental health expert with the American
Lung Association of Michigan, said elderly people and those with
asthma or other respiratory problems had the greatest risk of
problems from the fumes.
   ``It was like spraying Raid in your face,'' said Tina Hartung,
recalling the sensation as she was hustled from her home 10 minutes
after the derailment. ``You could smell it. You could taste it.''
   One of the train's derailed cars jumped the tracks twice in
April, had brake problems and recently left service for repairs,
Jim Burnett of the National Safety Transportation Board said.
   ``This car has had two previous derailments on the CSX railroad.
I don't know what its accident experience may have been on other
railroads,'' Burnett said of the car, which is owned by the
Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe rail line.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
