<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-SpeedLimit     07-26 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speed Limit,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurance Group Says 65 MPH Limit Killed 550 Motorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 65-mile-per-hour speed limit adopted for
some rural interstate highways caused 550 additional deaths last
year, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety said today.
   In a report to Congress, the institute said highways with the
higher limit had a 30 percent increase in fatalities _ twice the
increase recorded by the institute and the Transportation
Department for 1987.
   Brian O'Neill, president of the research institute, which is
financed by insurance companies, said states that kept the maximum
speed limit at 55 mph had no significant increase in road deaths.
   The speed has been increased to 65 on rural interstate highways
in 38 states. Maximum speed elsewhere has remained 55 mph for 15
years.
   O'Neill said the conclusion that fatalities had increased 30
percent on roads where the speed limit had been increased was based
on an institute analysis of Transportation Department highway
fatality records. The department has not released its own
interpretation of the data.
   ``It's a much greater increase in deaths than would have been
expected if speed limits hadn't been changed,'' O'Neill told a
Science, Space and Technology Committee transportation subcommittee.
</TEXT>
