<HEAD>Americans Arrested for Allegedly Smuggling Marijuana into Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday they have arrested two
Americans on charges of using U.S. military mail to smuggle into
Japan two pistols, 125 cartridges and 9.9 pounds of marijuana
valued at $158,000.
   Police also have arrested another American and three Japanese
for allegedly buying the drugs and pistols, smuggled from the
Philippines, authorities said.
   Air Force Sgt. Robert N. Barber, 27, and Edwin M. Griffin Jr.,
34, a former serviceman, bought the drugs and pistols while in
training or on private visits in the Philippines.
   Barber then mailed the items to his base, Kadena Air Base in
Okinawa, through a U.S. military base in the Philippines, according
to a police official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Japanese police investigators first arrested Joji Heshiki, 40, a
Japanese restaurant manager in Naha, Okinawa, for allegedly
possessing marijuana and used information from Heshiki to arrest
two other Japanese and the third American, identified as U.S. Air
Force Senior Airman Wayne K. Wickliffe, the official said.
   Wickliffe also is assigned to Kadena, the official said, but
declined to disclose the hometowns of the three Americans.
   U.S. military spokesman Marine Master Sgt. Jake Rodrigues said
he could not confirm the report immediately because of the late
hour Wednesday night.
   The maximum penalty for smuggling marijuana into Japan is seven
years in prison and that for violation of the weapons control law
is 10 years in prison.
