<HEAD>Human Bones Found Near `SOS' Letters on Japanese Mountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have found human bones near a large ``SOS''
spelled out with white birch branches on a mountain in northern
Japan, officials said Wednesday.
   Two people have been reported missing since 1984 in climbs on
7,514-foot Mount Asahidake, said Sgt. Koichi Kasahara, a spokesman
for police on Japan's northernmost island of Hokkaido.
   He said he wouldn't dismiss the possibility a climber in
distress set out the ``SOS'' and died before any help arrived.
   He said the SOS was seen Monday by the crew of a police
helicopter searching for another missing climber. Rescuers said the
SOS arrangement looked old, with some of the birch buried in dirt
or grass, he added.
   The subject of Monday's search _ a climber from Tokyo _ was
rescued by the helicopter about 2 miles from the distress sign,
halfway up the mountain. But he told his rescuers he knew nothing
of the English SOS letters, each measuring about 16 feet long and
10 feet wide.
   On Tuesday, Kasahara said, the helicopter returned to Asahidake
in central Hokkaido and set down four searchers who found human
bones and a knapsack, containing a tape recorder, a towel, soap and
other articles, near the SOS.
   Kasahara said police were examining the bones and belongings to
determine the victim's identity. None of the articles carried any
names or initials, he added.
