<FIRST>u a PM-Nissan-UAW 1stLd-Writethru a0489 07-26 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-UAW, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan, UAW Step Up Campaigns on Eve of Union Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comments today. Picks up 6th
graf, `The company...' Voting starts 2 p.m. EDT. Version moved on financial
wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers and Nissan made
last-minute appeals to 2,400 workers, and both sides prdicted
victory today in balloting to decide if their plant will become the
first union shop owned solely by a Japanese automaker.
   The UAW aired radio commercials Tuesday echoing its theme that
the fast work pace at Nissan has increased injuries.
   ``The significance to us has to do with the problems that Nissan
employees have. They're suffering a very brutal line speed and high
injury rate,'' union spokesman Maxey Irwin said.
   The company has disputed this, although it drew a $5,000 fine
from Tennessee authorities _ now under appeal _ for refusing to
show its injury log to a group of workers.
   Nissan, meanwhile, reportedly warned workers on closed-circuit
videos that UAW representation could mean a loss of benefits for
production line workers.
   At a news conference today arranged by Nissan, anti-union
employees predicted the UAW would be defeated.
   ``I think it's going to go fairly heavily for the plant against
the union _ maybe 75 percent,'' Ken Roden, a 28-year-old worker in
the trim and chassis department.
   UAW organizer Jim Weaver had the opposite view.
   ``I think it really looks great. The momentum's building. And
people were coming out of the plant all excited this morning,''
Weaver said.
   The company has declined to talk publicly about the campaign.
``We don't want to conduct this election in the media,'' President
Jerry Benefield said earlier this month.
   Benefield addressed about half of the plant's work force
Tuesday. Pro-union workers said the speech was interrupted with
chants of ``Union! Union!'' They added that some employees gave
Benefield a standing ovation.
   The speech was closed to reporters, and Nissan officials
declined to comment on it.
   Workers at Nissan Motor Manufacturing Co. U.S.A.'s
auto-and-truck plant south of Nashville were to begin voting today
in an election that's crucial for the UAW.
   Reflecting an overall decline in union strength, UAW membership
has fallen from more than 1.5 million in the late 1970s to about 1
million today. Hopes of stopping the decline rest largely with the
growing number of plants operated by Japanese automakers.
   The union has organized workers in three joint ventures _ a
Mazda-Ford plant in Flat Rock, Mich., run by Mazda Motor Corp.; the
New United Motor Manufacturing Inc. factory in Fremont, Calif., a
venture of General Motors Corp. and Toyota Motor Corp.; and the
Diamond-Star Motors Corp. plant in Bloomington, Ill., a venture of
Chrysler and Mitsubishi Motors Corp.
   But workers at Toyota's Georgetown, Ky., plant, at Honda Motor
Corp.'s Marysville, Ohio, facility and at Nissan's Smyrna plant
aren't unionized.
   An effort to organize the Honda plant failed badly three years
ago, and labor observers say another defeat could cripple UAW hopes.
   Voting at Smyrna is scheduled to end early Thursday.
   Union spokesman Irwin played down the vote's importance.
   ``Within the UAW, it's not a question of if Nissan or the other
Japanese assembly plants ... will be organized,'' Irwin said
Tuesday. ``It is simply a question of when they will be organized.''
   Nissan's messages to workers reportedly blamed the union for
layoffs at General Motors and promised tough negotiations if the
UAW wins.
   The Nashville Banner reported today that it obtained an audio
copy of a company tape in which a voice says that a UAW victory
would mean the company would have to negotiate with the union, not
the workers.
   ``Who wins in negotiations is usually decided by who is in the
strongest position. So at Nissan you start out knowing the company
will not be easy in bargaining,'' the tape said.
   The tape also said employees should be concerned about strikes
and that a strike could hurt them more than it could Nissan.
Television reports of strike violence and unsuccessful strikes are
included in the videotape, the newspaper reported.
   Union spokesman Frank Joyce said the tape was an inaccurate
attempt to intimidate Nissan workers.
   ``The idea that somehow Nissan is currently in a bargaining
relationship on an individual basis with workers is pretty absurd.
Nissan employees do not set their own wages, benefits or working
conditions,'' Joyce said. ``If they want to declare in advance that
they will be hard to bargain with, we're used to that.''
</TEXT>
