<HEAD>Norwegian DC-10 Survivor Fights Fear, Flies Back to Oslo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian student who survived the DC-10
crash in Sioux City, Iowa, had vowed to take a boat home but
changed her mind and arrived by plane Wednesday.
   ``The flight home cured some of my fear, but there's still some
left,'' Gitte Skaanes told the Norwegian news agency NTB upon her
arrival from New York. She said she might even become a flight
attendant.
   Miss Skaanes spent a year in Cheyenne, Wyo. as an exchange
student. She suffered only a bump on the head July 19 when the
United Airlines DC-10 crashed while trying to make an emergency
landing in Sioux City.
   Of the 296 passengers, 185 survived. Miss Skaanes turned 18 the
day after the crash and called her survival a birthday gift.
   For several days after the accident, Miss Skaanes said she would
take a boat home rather than board another plane.
   She eventually decided that flying home beside her father, Jarle
Skaanes, was the only way to overcome her fear.
   After talking with reporters at Fornebu Airport, Miss Skaanes
boarded another plane for the short flight from Oslo to her
hometown of Trondheim, NTB said.
