<FIRST>r i AM-Romania 1stLd-Writethru a0579 07-26 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0579,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romanian Leader Says Living Standard Rose in Last Decade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Ceausescu throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania's president, indirectly denying
widespread reports of economic hardship, said in an interview
published Wednesday that living standards in his country rose
greatly in the last decade.
   President Nicolae Ceausescu told the rightist daily newspaper
ABC that living standards and state investment increased at the
same time that Romania managed to pay off its foreign debt. Romania
first announced in April that the debt _ at $11 billion in 1981 _
had been eliminated.
   ``In this manner the repayment of the foreign debt not only did
not affect our projects but economic development and the standard
of living increased,'' said Ceausescu.
   Romania used to be known as the breadbasket of central Europe
before World War II, but agricultural production decreased by the
1950s after the communist leadership decided to invest
predominantly in heavy industry.
   Shortages increased with Ceausescu's decision in the 1970s to
funnel most of Romania's foreign currency earnings into debt
payments. As a result, agricultural and manufactured goods needed
at home frequently were exported. Investment went into now-outmoded
industries, and Western experts generally agree that industrial and
agricultural production figures are below pre-World War II levels.
   Western journalists who traveled to Bucharest this month for a
meeting of the Warsaw Pact nations reported that most staple
commodities were rationed.
   Answering nine questions accepted from a list presented by the
newspaper, Ceausescu said Romania's industrial output had increased
135 times since 1945 and agricultural production has increased
tenfold.
   The subject of Ceausescu's succession was not included in the
list of acceptable questions. Ceausescu, 71, came to power in 1965.
   He said sanctions imposed by the European Parliament _ the
12-nation Common Market's legislature _ for alleged human rights
violations didn't represent general opinion in Western Europe, and
``business goes on.''
   The newspaper said the Romanian leader asked those comments be
off the record, but it published them anyway.
   Ceausescu said there is no restriction on emigration but the
government discourages Romanians from leaving. His comment
contrasted with claims of harassment by those who have applied to
leave and documented cases of border shootings of others trying to
flee.
   ``We believe people should not leave the country of their birth,
that they should remain and work to create a better future,'' he
said.
   Each year, 11,000 ethnic Germans born in Romania are allowed to
emigrate to West Germany in exchanged for hard-currency payments by
Bonn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
