<DOCNO> AP890726-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1259EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Books Bjt   07-26 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Books, Bjt,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Raids Political Books, But Pornography Stays</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the cover is a half-naked woman, blood
trickling from her mouth.
   Inside are 110 pages of small type and pen-and-ink sketches of
men with cigarettes clenched in their teeth and women with tears
streaming down their faces and dresses sliding off their shoulders.
   It must be the writing that makes ``The Demon Couple'' sell:
   ``A tall shadow comes through the door. She wants to cry out,
she wants to struggle, but everything is so sudden. The shadow sits
on the edge of the bed ... and undoes her buttons.''
   It is the kind of sexually explicit, sensationalist story that
officials and editorial writers have condemned as ``spiritual
drugs'' as they conduct a national magazine and book banning and
burning campaign to root out alleged Western liberal influences.
   But ``The Demon Couple'' and similar short-stories, all
unthinkable in the more puritan atmosphere of a decade ago, remain
on the market, their lurid covers framing many private bookstalls.
Hard-core pornography is available too, only slightly less boldly
displayed.
   The China Daily said Tuesday that authorities had seized 236,000
pornographic books and magazines nationwide this year, but
booksellers say most of what seized is political: books with somber
titles such as ``America As a Riddle'' by journalist Liu Binyan and
``A 10-Year History of the Cultural Revolution.''
   Booksellers keep these hidden under their tables.
   When Yan, former head of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences'
Political Science Institute, published his book several years ago,
it gained popularity among students for its insights into past
factional fighting. But Yan spoke out in support of student
pro-democracy protesters this spring, and fled the country to
escape arrest. Now, he is referred to in the official media as
``the wanted Yan Jiaqi.''
   Liu was in the United States during the protests, but he
condemned the crackdown, putting himself in the ranks of the
ostracized.
   He has become so taboo that an editor at a publishing company
who put out a book about him was arrested, and copies of the book
were ordered burned.
   The State Press and Publications Administration said last week
it had made a list of 60 banned books, but did not identify them.
These can only be deduced from what the Culture Ministry has seized
from private stalls and what has disappeared from the shelves of
state-run stores.
   They include biographies of ousted Communist Party General
Secretary Zhao Ziyang, and several histories of modern China.
   It is almost impossible to buy the narrative from the popular
television program ``River Elegy,'' which stirred up controversy
when it was shown last year for disparaging such Chinese cultural
totems as the Great Wall.
   Aging revolutionary veterans reportedly were incensed, but Hu
Qili, the top party official in charge of the arts, said at the
time: ``Leading cadres may comment on literary and art works but
their remarks should not be regarded as mandatory. At no time
should such questions be handled by launching a political
movement.''
   The veterans have won the day, however. Hu was purged in June
along with party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, and one of the
authors of ``River Elegy,'' Su Xiaokang, is reported arrested. The
People's Daily recently devoted one-third of its front page to a
bitter attack on the show. Stations are barred from airing its
sequel, and Su's other writings are banned.
   The China Daily said Monday that authorities in southwest
China's Sichuan province shut down the provincial Academy of Social
Sciences' publishing company, accusing it of printing an book that
``curses the Communist Party, party leaders and workers'
movements.'' The book was not named.
   Tales of illicit love and crime, meanwhile, sell briskly to
Chinese seeking escape from their drab workaday lives.
   The plots vie in sensationalism. Women are seduced by evil
gamblers, drugged and raped by city slickers, forced into
prostitution by factory bosses. Many commit suicide. Young men
slide into lives of crime and end up as murderers.
   The Communist Party is promoting alternate summer reading:
senior leader Deng Xiaoping's statements on quelling the student
protests, and compilations of newspaper editorials arguing that
socialism is China's only hope. At least three special books on the
protests have been issued or announced so far.
   But store clerks say the chief purchasers are work units,
ordering by the dozen for political study classes.
   The masses of readers seem to prefer stories of the kind the
party has dubbed ``spiritual opium.''
   ``The stories are bizarre and they draw you in,'' said a young
woman reader. ``They are not real-life, but if you come home from
work and are tired, you sit down and read one and you can't put it
down.''
   What about Deng's speech? ``Meiyisi'' _ ``It's boring.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
