<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Soviet     07-26 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soviet,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Warplanes Thunder Over Soviet Defense Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEUCHARS, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov
on Wednesday watched a thunderous display by Britain's most
advanced jet fighters during a visit that he said reflected the
easing of East-West tensions.
   ``We are learning more about each other,'' said Yazov, the first
Soviet defense minister to visit a NATO country since the end of
World War II.
   ``If we are more open, we are hoping that peace will be provided
and strengthened,'' the general said after watching the display at
Leuchars, a Royal Air Force base.
   He grinned as a Harrier fighter-bomber showed off its special
capabilities by flying backward.
   Yazov, on the second day of a four-day official visit, later
visited the British aircraft carrier HMS Invincible off the
Scottish coast.
   At an impromptu news conference in Leuchars, Yazov said that
during a meeting Tuesday with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, the
discussion focused on the dangers of modern weapons.
   Britain's outgoing defense secretary, George Younger,
accompanied Yazov. Younger resigned this week to resume a business
career but is staying on until Friday to serve as a host to the
Soviets.
   Yazov flew aboard a Royal Air Force plane from London and was
greeted at Leuchars by a kilt-wearing bagpiper.
   With the sun trying to break through dark clouds, Yazov
inspected the newest model of the Tornado jet fighter, the F-3. It
is an all-weather aircraft to be used to intercept unidentified
aircraft entering British airspace.
   About 40 of the long-range planes, built by a British, German
and Italian consortium, will be stationed at Leuchars this year to
replace older Phantom F-4s.
   Yazov also saw the attack version of the Tornado loaded with
bombs and missiles. Four of these planes burst over the horizon to
simulate an attack on a runway.
   During a deafening display by a Tornado F-3 and a Harrier, Yazov
and his aides passed up the earmuffs provided for them, even when
the Harrier hovered directly in front of them.
   ``It was strange to have the Soviet defense minister standing
next to me,'' Group Capt. A.J.C. Bagnall, the base's commanding
officer, said later. ``It was only sad that we only had two hours
to show him how we do business.''
</TEXT>
