<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Lucas 2ndLd-Writethru a0547 07-26 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0547,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucas Wins Support from Specter</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts graf 4, President Bush, with president prepared to make
phone calls.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas gained ground today in his
campaign for confirmation as the nation's chief civil rights
enforcer, winning support from Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who had
been viewed as a key undecided vote.
   ``I do not support William Lucas because he is black but I do
believe his background will give him special insights into the
civil rights laws,'' Specter told the Senate one day after a
meeting with the candidate.
   Specter, until now seen by Lucas critics as perhaps the only
Judiciary Committee Republican who might oppose confirmation, said
he was convinced the nominee is ``conversant with the civil rights
laws'' and would be able to draw expertise from ``a battery of
attorneys available to him.''
   President Bush is prepared to make personal telephone calls to
drum up votes for Lucas, White House spokesman B. Jay Cooper said
today. ``The president ... has not made any phone calls, but he
may,'' if his involvement is seen as important, Cooper said.
   The Judiciary Committee could vote as early as Thursday on
whether to recommend Lucas' confirmation to the full Senate. The
panel is believed to be sharply split with a few undecided
lawmakers holding the balance.
   The issue has become a political tug-of-war between the Bush
administration and a number of civil rights groups which oppose
Lucas, even though he is black, on grounds he lacks experience.
   Specter told the Senate it ``has become a great American sport
to use nominees as target practice in Washington, D.C..''
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., declared that ``the
media and the liberal establishment have stabbed Bill Lucas in the
back'' and that ``frankly, it's a disgrace.''
   ``Bill Lucas is a profile in courage _ what we are seeing with
the Bill Lucas nomination is a profile in liberal politics,'' Dole
said.
   Lucas, in written responses Tuesday to questions from Judiciary
Committee members, stressed his commitment to civil rights but said
there has not been enough time to assess recent Supreme Court
rulings on the issue.
   ``I agree with the president and the attorney general that it is
still too early to assess the practical impact of these rulings,''
Lucas said.
   Lucas' answers on Tuesday followed his refusal at a committee
hearing last week to criticize recent Supreme Court decisions that
have come under fire from civil rights groups.
   However, Lucas said, ``I will not tolerate the misuse of any law
or court decision to deny rights guaranteed by this nation's civil
rights laws.''
   Lucas' promise to fight misuse of court decisions came in answer
to Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., who is believed to be leaning in
favor of confirmation. The senator cited two recent civil rights
decisions by the Supreme Court, City of Richmond vs. J.A. Croson
and Patterson vs. McLean.
   The first case overturned automatic municipal contract
set-asides for minority-owned firms without some finding of
previous discrimination, and the second forbade the use of an 1866
civil rights law to sue over alleged racial harassment on the job.
   ``I believe these cases have erred in upsetting the proper
balance between private actions and government enforcement
actions,'' DeConcini said in asking what Lucas would do to enforce
civil rights law.
   ``The attorney general and I recognize that some people may in
fact use the recent Supreme Court decisions in an attempt to
discriminate or to challenge legitimate affirmative action and
set-aside programs,'' Lucas said.
   ``It is my commitment to investigate and prosecute those
individuals or entities and to prevent such efforts to roll back
the hard-earned gains of the civil rights movement,'' he said.
   Lucas said he would ``lead the charge in obtaining appropriate
relief'' for anyone who suffers discrimination as a result of the
rulings.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, asked whether Lucas believed
affirmative action laws have aided blacks and whether he thought
such policies could result in tokenism or reverse discrimination.
   ``I feel a special obligation to enforce laws which have
benefited me,'' Lucas said.
   ``Where you have a persistent pattern of discrimination, I think
that it is entirely appropriate to order that minorities be hired
and promoted,'' he said. He added that he also approved of
voluntary affirmative action efforts by employers ``to overcome a
manifest imbalance in a traditionally segregated job category.''
   ``On the other hand, I think there is a danger that some
programs, under the label of affirmative action, can in certain
cases be implemented in a way that amounts to improper quota
hiring,'' he said.
</TEXT>
