<DOCNO> AP890726-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     07-26 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Intends to Find Uno Successor Quickly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governing party leaders set a mid-August deadline
for swearing in a successor to resigning Prime Minister Sousuke
Uno, news reports said Wednesday.
   The deadline indicates they want to move quickly after recent
party setbacks.
   An opposition Socialist official said, however, that his party
will fight any attempts to convene Parliament too soon to name a
new prime minister.
   The news reports, based on comments by Liberal Democratic party
elders and government officials, said the party hopes to elect its
next president Aug. 8 and have the Parliament swear him in as prime
minister before mid-August holidays.
   Uno, who has been in office less than two months, said Monday he
will resign to take responsibility for his party's heavy losses in
Sunday's elections for half the seats in Parliament's upper house.
Uno's party lost 33 seats, mostly to the Socialists, the leading
opposition party.
   Uno himself has been plagued by charges he paid geishas for sex.
   It took more than a month after former Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita announced his resignation April 25 for the party to
settle on Uno as a replacement. Takeshita announced that Uno would
be his successor on May 27, and Uno took office June 2.
   At the time, party leaders struggled to find someone untainted
by the scandal that brought down Takeshita. He resigned to take
responsibility in the face of reports the Recruit Co. publishing
conglomerate tried to buy influence with large political donations
and cut-rate stocks. Kyodo News Service, quoting an unidentified
top government official, said Wednesday that Uno's successor will
be sworn in Aug. 15.
   However, several other reports said the Liberal Democrats have
decided to convene a special five-day session of Parliament on Aug.
7. The mass-circulation newspaper Yomiuri Shimbun said an election
among party lawmakers will be held while Parliament is in session
and a new prime minister will be sworn in before the session ends.
   A Liberal Democratic official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the party's lower house Steering Committee met for
about an hour Wednesday to set a date for the session. But the
official added that the matter was still being negotiated with
opposition leaders.
   A Socialist Party official, who also spoke on condition of
anonymity, said his party will fight proposals to hold the session
soon. He said it needs more time to work on a bill to abolish an
unpopular new 3 percent sales tax. He did not say exactly how long.
   The tax, forced through Parliament last year by the Liberal
Democrats, was a key issue in Sunday's elections that deprived the
governing party of a majority in the upper house for the first time
in the party's 34-year history. By law, Parliament must convene
within 30 days after an election and appoint the prime minister. It
is expected to approve the Liberal Democrats' choice because of the
governing party's large majority in the more powerful lower house.
   The party's Election Management Committee was to meet Thursday
to decide the method and timing of elections to name the next party
president.
   A party reform committee recommended Wednesday that Uno's
successor be picked by a ballot of party lawmakers instead of by
back-room negotiations, the party official said.
   Uno was virtually hand-picked by Takeshita, and many people
criticized the secretive process.
   A top contender to replace Uno, governing party Secretary
General Ryutaro Hashimoto, said Wednesday that as the party's No. 2
executive, he shares the blame for the election defeat.
   ``We have experienced defeat for the first time, and it was
while I was in charge, so I am responsible,'' Hashimoto said. He
made no reference to resigning, however.
   Hashimoto, 51, is the youngest secretary general in the party's
history.
</TEXT>
