<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-26 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diego Henao has inspected hundreds of
cars, but nothing prepared him for what he found under the hood of
a new Toyota Corolla.
   Coiled around the battery was a 5-foot-long boa constrictor.
   ``Diego drove the car over from the lot, popped the hood to
check the fluid levels and there was this snake,'' said Mark Vlash,
assistant parts manager at Toyota of Stamford. ``He almost had a
heart attack.''
   It turned out the boa, whose name is Samantha, had escaped from
a cage at Jack McGraw's home a month earlier. Alerted by a radio
report about the discovery of the snake, McGraw came to take his
pet home Tuesday, to the relief of many at Toyota of Stamford.
   But parts manager Joe Munro took a shine to the snake during its
brief stay. He fixed up a box for it, with with leaves and and old
radiator hose to imitate a fellow reptile, and even sent workers
out for mice to feed Samantha.
   ``It really is a cute little thing,'' Muro said. ``He must have
been handled a lot because he is so at home being held.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When fashion photographer Arthur Elgort
came to town with two models and a crew of 10, the New Yorkers
found their clothes made them stick out of the rodeo crowd like
cacti in Manhattan.
   The visitors, who planned to use the 93rd annual Cheyenne
Frontier Days celebration as a backdrop for a fashion shoot,
quickly ditched their L.L. Bean shoes and Brooks Brothers shirts
for jeans and other cowboy duds.
   ``Everyone in our group must have spent $300 in Western
Outfitters today _ and that's the joke of it all _ it will even go
over well in New York,'' Elgort said recently.
   But no matter what they wore, models Cindy Crawford and Charlene
Short weren't able to disappear into the crowd.
   ``I had huge hair and a sexy top on,'' explained the 23-year-old
Crawford. ``The cowboys were screaming and shouting.''
   The photographer hopes the Wild West theme will be as big a hit
in European fashion magazines as his models were with the cowboys.
   ``To them,'' he said of the Europeans, ``Wyoming is more of
America than going to New York.''
</TEXT>
