<FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-Pirates     07-26 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-Pirates,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Thais Arrested in Rape, Robbery of Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested two Thai
fishermen who confessed to robbing a group of Vietnamese boat
people and raping the women aboard, a police officer said Wednesday.
   The Vietnamese boat, apparantly heading from Vietnam to
Indonesia, was attacked June 7 in the Gulf of Thailand, said Lt.
Col. Prakob Benjapong of the Thai Maritime Police. He said 32 of 35
people aboard are still missing.
   Fishermen Sompong Nakmas, 33, and Thanom Pathumsuwan, 19, were
arrested Tuesday after confessing to the attack, Prakob said.
   Attacks on boat people, who sometimes flee with gold or other
valuables, have become increasingly violent in the past year and
have left scores _ if not hundreds _ dead.
   Western officials believe most attacks are carried out by
``pirates of opportunity'' _ fishermen who chance upon the
Vietnamese boats.
   The two latest fishermen under arrest were identified by three
Vietnamese women who are the only known survivors of the attack,
Prakob said. The women came ashore in the southern Thai province of
Pattani on June 25, he said.
   They told authorities the two fishermen had threatened the men
in the Vietnamese boat with knives and iron bars before taking 11
women aboard their own boat. The women said the men raped them
while keeping them prisoner, Prakob reported.
   The fishermen later freed three women, but the whereabouts of
the eight others and the 24 Vietnamese men are unknown, he said.
   Prakob said the fishermen told him they allowed the men to go
free with their boat and later let the eight other women swim
ashore.
   The police officer said authorities are seeking up to nine other
fishermen in the attack.
   It was the fifth time since June 22 that police have arrested
Thai fishermen for pirate attacks involving murder, rape or robbery
of Vietnamese boat people, he said.
   Last month, police said four other Thai fishermen were arrested
and confessed to killing 130 Vietnamese refugees April 16 off the
Malaysian coast.
   Prakob said Friday that police arrested three Thai fishermen who
confessed to killing 56 Vietnamese boat people in an attack March
26.
   More than 1.5 million Vietnamese have left their homeland since
the communist takeover in April 1975.
</TEXT>
