<FIRST>u i AM-Zaire-Belgium 1stLd-Writethru a0592 07-26 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zaire-Belgium, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zaire, Belgium Patch Up Debt Quarrel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with signing ceremony, CORRECTS that Belgium
canceled $285 million sted $500 million of Zaire's debt. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Belgium and Zaire
signed an agreement Wednesday to normalize relations and forget a
bitter 18-month dispute over the Central African nation's debt to
its former colonizer.
   As part of the agreement, Belgium canceled about $285 million in
debts owed by Zaire, delegation sources said.
   It also agreed to a 14-year period during which interest
payments on $370 million in outstanding Zairean commercial debts
will be made to a fund for development projects in Zaire.
   The agreement was reached late Tuesday between Prime Minister
Wilfried Martens of Belgium and President Mobutu Sese Seko of
Zaire, who attended the signing ceremony at the royal palace.
   They applauded as Zairean Foreign Minister Nguza Karl-I-Bond and
his Belgian counterpart, Mark Eyskens, signed the accord.
   The signing ceremony originally was scheduled for Tuesday but
was postponed following last-minute difficulties over details of
the accord.
   Officials said the main obstacle was Belgian insistence on
mentioning the International Monetary Fund as the umbrella
organization for carrying out the agreement.
   The Zaire delegation refused to accept reference to the fund on
grounds the agreement ``was strictly a bilateral matter between
Zaire and Belgium,'' delegation sources reported.
   The two delegations met Tuesday night at a dinner put on by
Morocco's King Hassan II, who helped resolve the dispute.
   A communique issued after the signing ceremony said the two
governments had ``put an end to the crisis in their relations ...
and removed all obstacles to their continued good relations on the
basis of legality.''
   The communique said both governments expressed their gratitude
to the king for his ``invaluable aid.''
   Belgium and Zaire, which used to be the Belgian Congo, have been
at odds since December 1987, when Mobutu rejected Brussels' offers
to ease the debt burden and denounced the treaty of friendship
between the two countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
