<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Czechoslovakia     07-26 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Czechoslovakia,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Activist Calls for Reforms in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reformers from Poland, Hungary and the
Soviet Union may combine forces in trying to nudge Czechoslovakia
toward democratic change, according to a Solidarity leader who met
with dissidents in Prague.
   Without change in Czechoslovakia, reform movements elsewhere are
``crippled, deprived on one leg,'' said Zbigniew Bujak, Warsaw
region Solidarity leader.
   ``That's why the answer to the question how can we help
Czechoslovakia enter the road of reforms is very important to us,''
Bujak said in an interview published Tuesday in the opposition's
Gazeta Wyborcza daily newspaper.
   Communist leaders in Poland and Hungary have moved toward
increased political plurality. In contrast, Czechoslovakia's
leadership has refused to hold talks with opposition groups and
consistently has condemned activists.
   Bujak was one of five Solidarity members in Czechoslovakia for
meetings with dissidents and with Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, the
leader of the Roman Catholic Church in Czechoslovakia, Cardinal
Frantisek Tomasek.
   Leading the delegation was Parliament deputy Adam Michnik, a
longtime Solidarity activist who this month met with advocates of
reform in the Soviet Union's Congress of People's Deputies.
   Bujak said Polish activists would like to participate in the
Czechoslovak opposition's observance next month of the 21st
anniversary of the 1968 Soviet-led invasion. He said Czechoslovak
dissidents also may be invited to visit Poland later in the year.
   The 1968 invasion ended the reformist policies of Alexander
Dubcek, which resembled some of the changes now being implemented
in the Soviet Union. Three members of the Solidarity delegation met
Monday with Dubcek in Bratislava.
   The visit was criticized in Warsaw by the Communist Party daily
Trybuna Ludu as potentially harmful to ``good and friendly''
Polish-Czechoslovak relations.
</TEXT>
