<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     07-26 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Alleges Rhodesians Burned Bodies of Black Nationalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading black magazine says the former
white Rhodesian government secretly burned the bodies of black
nationalist guerrillas in an incinerator that it likened to the
ovens of Nazi Germany.
   The August issue of the independent Parade magazine said the
incinerator is hidden in thickly wooded grounds at Chikurubi
maximum-security prison, near Harare, where scores of guerrillas
were executed.
   It said the now-idle incinerator was used to dispose of bodies
of an unspecified number of guerrillas executed during the
seven-year war that forced independence and brought the black
majority-ruled nation of Zimbabwe into existence in April 1980.
   Former Rhodesian Prime Minister Ian Smith, the last white ruler
of this ex-British colony, denied there were covert executions and
said his government burned only papers in incinerators.
   The magazine, which claims a readership of more than 1 million
in this southern African nation of 9 million people, said the
incinerator was Rhodesia's equivalent to the ovens the Nazis used
in World War II.
   Parade described the incinerator as the size of a small house
with a 10-yard chimney extending through the roof. According to a
stamp embossed into its heavy iron casing, the incinerator was
called ``Macro-Burn'' by its makers in Johannesburg, the magazine
said.
   ``It must be one of the most efficient crematoriums in southern
Africa,'' said Political Affairs Minister Eddison Zvobgo, who is
campaigning for it to be declared a national memorial.
   ``We think the incinerator should become a national monument
like those in Germany today,'' he said.
   The incinerator is equipped with fan-assisted oil-fired burners
and at one end features a high-walled ``sluice yard'' where
truckloads of corpses allegedly were dumped, said Zvobgo, who was
Zimbabwe's first justice minister.
   He said that in 1980, President Robert Mugabe's new government
found no accurate records of guerrilla executions and believes most
were destroyed by outgoing Rhodesian authorities.
   Between 1976 and 1979, Zvobgo said, an unknown number of
guerrillas were tried summarily by military courts and were
executed with no legal recourse to appeal the death sentence.
   The war had reached a stage when the level of killings made it
impractical to bury or keep records of the dead, Zvogbo charged.
   About 30,000 Zimbabweans, mostly black civilians, died in the
war.
   Smith told a news conference that guerrillas were tried and
executed under anti-terrorism laws.
   The retired politician, who ruled from 1965 until independence,
said he believes the report was timed to distract attention from
the government's political woes.
   It is the latest in a series of attacks against the nation's
remaining 100,000 whites, he charged.
   ``I do recall we had incinerators for burning papers and I
believe we had a big clean up of a mountain (of papers) which
required burning when the change of government took place,'' said
Smith.
   Recently, the government has been criticized for corruption and
policies that have led to record unemployment, commodity shortages
and rising inflation.
</TEXT>
