<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1433EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Europarliament     07-26 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europarliament,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President Wants More Power for European Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baron Enrique Crespo, the new
president of the European Parliament, called Wednesday for more
power for the 518-seat assembly.
   ``If we aspire toward a united Europe, someone must administer
this union, and someone must monitor those who administer the
union,'' he said.
   He acknowledged that national governments of the 12 European
Economic Community member states view the demands for greater power
with ``suspicion and distrust.'' But, he said, national parliaments
of the EEC nations ``must see us as partners in the democratic
monitoring of institutions.''
   The European Parliament, the only one of the EEC's institutions
to be democratically elected, is frequently dismissed as no more
than a debating chamber.
   Specifically addressing this point, the 45-year old Spanish
lawyer said the parliament should make its ``debates more serious
and to the point, always and in all circumstances.''
   He was alluding to the body's propensity to adopt resolutions
and reports on human rights abuses or natural catastrophes on the
other side of the globe.
   Crespo said the parliament's ``prime concern must be the
immediate problems which directly affect European citizens.''
   For the time being it can amend or reject the EEC's budget,
which only becomes operational once the parliament's president has
signed it.
   It also can dismiss all 17 members of the EEC's Executive
Commission, which drafts community laws, and can prevent or delay
legislation from going into force by sending drafts back to the
commission.
   The parliament must also be consulted on certain measures aimed
at creating a single market by the end of 1992.
   It can veto or delay some EEC treaties with other countries, and
new applications for Common Market membership must gain at least
260 votes in the parliament to be accepted.
   However, the parliament cannot initiate legislation, and in
economic and monetary affairs its opinion does not have to be taken
into account _ a situation Crespon criticized.
   ``We are entitled to demand parliament's full participation'' in
the work of the Intergovernmental Conference on Economic and
Monetary Union, he said, referring to a plan to create full
monetary union among the 12 member states.
   Parliament should also be involved in the ``drawing up of the
new texts which are to regulate Community economic and monetary
union in the future,'' he said.
   Also on Wednesday, British legislator John Tomlinson accused the
French government of ``bribery'' in giving each parliamentarian an
expensive, leather-bound personal organizer, a color TV set, a fax
machine and a paging system.
   France, Belgium and Luxembourg have been fighting for years over
where the parliament should be located.
   It now holds its monthly week-long plenary sessions in
Strasbourg, has its committee meetings a five-hour train ride away
in Brussels, Belgium, and has its administrative headquarters in
Luxembourg, midway between the two.
   ``In my vocabulary there is only one word for this: bribery,''
said Tomlinson, a socialist, implying the gifts were an attempt to
swing sentiment in favor of the Strasbourg location.
   He introduced a motion calling on the EEC governments to fix a
permanent Brussels base for the assembly.
</TEXT>
