<FIRST>r w AM-JailedMother     07-26 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jailed Mother,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bill to Free Jailed Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel on Wednesday approved
legislation to limit civil contempt-of-court jailings in the
District of Columbia, but one senator said he may try to make the
bill apply only to the woman whose case prompted it.
   The Governmental Affairs Committee voted 13-0 to set a 12-month
cap on civil contempt-of-court jailings in child custody cases in
the district.
   However, Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., said he may introduce an
amendment on the Senate floor to limit the bill to the case of Dr.
Elizabeth Morgan.
   ``I don't want to limit the power of a judge, and that is what
this is all about,'' Rudman said. ``This would never have come
before the Congress if Dr. Morgan had not been in jail.''
   Morgan, a plastic surgeon, was jailed in August 1987 by a local
judge who said she would remain confined until she produced her
daughter Hilary for court-ordered visits with Dr. Eric Foretich,
her ex-husband and the girl's father. Morgan has alleged that
Foretich has sexually abused the girl, but he has denied it.
   The child custody dispute has become a rallying point for
women's rights groups and organizations concerned with child abuse
who have come to Morgan's defense, while Foretich has won the
support of various men's groups.
   Rudman said he was reluctant to interfere with the district's
court system and expressed concern that capping all child custody
contempt-of-court jailings could eventually allow persons guilty of
child abuse to go free.
   However, Rudman said he would drop his plans for the amendment
if he felt it would prevent the bill from being passed before
Congress goes into recess on Aug. 5.
   Should the bill pass the Senate, it will have to go before a
House-Senate panel to work out differences between a version that
passed the House last month and the more narrowly drawn Senate
measure.
   The House bill would set a 12-month cap on all civil contempt
jailings, but the Senate version, introduced by Utah Republican
Orrin Hatch, would establish the limit only for civil contempt
child custody jailings.
</TEXT>
