<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1440EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FlagBurning     07-26 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Push Anti-Flag Burning Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on Wednesday blocked a
Republican-proposed constitutional amendment to ban flag burning as
they pursued passage of a regular statute they say can do the same
thing without altering the Bill of Rights.
   The chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, Jack Brooks,
D-Texas, ruled out of order an attempt by Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., to bring before the committee the amendment backed by
President Bush.
   Supporters of the amendment contend that changing the
Constitution is the only way to overcome last month's ruling by the
Supreme Court that flag-burning was a protected form of free
expression.
   Democratic leaders, including Brooks and House Speaker Thomas S.
Foley, D-Wash., are pursuing a regular statute designed to meet the
court's objections.
   Their strategy is aimed at avoiding damage to constitutional
rights and demonstrating that Democrats abhor flag burning. The
symbolism of the flag was used by Bush in last year's presidential
campaign against the Democratic nominee, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis.
   Brooks scheduled another meeting of the panel for Thursday to
take action on his proposed bill to outlaw desecration of the flag,
including burning, with penalties of up to a year in jail plus a
fine. The bill could come before the full House next week.
   ``It is my firm believe that a statute punishing flag burning...
can be drafted in a way that is consistent with the Supreme Court's
decision,'' said Brooks. A statute could be approved much more
quickly than an amendment, which requires ratification by the
states, he said.
   However, Sensenbrenner pointed out that even some opponents of
amending the Constitution don't believe a regular statute can undo
what the court decided.
   ``This is nonsense, and a ridiculous way to solve the problem
and a cop-out on our legislative responsibilities,'' he said. The
issue won't ``go away,'' he said, and blocking the constitutitonal
amendment ``is going to come back soon enough to haunt those who
made the decision.''
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the committee's
constitutional rights subcommittee, said he was convinced from mail
he was receiving that the public was becoming less enthralled with
the idea of a constitutional amendment.
   ``I believe we must act in the way that causes least violence to
the First Amendment, least damage to the Bill of Rights that for
200 years has made us the envy of the world,'' he said.
   The assertion by Democratic leaders that public support for an
amendment was beginning to lag in recent days was challenged as
``self-deception'' on Wednesday in the Senate by Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   ``The simple truth is that the vast majority of the American
people want a constitutional amendment,'' Dole said, citing 400
letters and petition he has received on the issue.
   The Senate has scheduled action in October on both a statute and
a constitutional amendment on flag burning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   07-26 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0539,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Reported Ready to Accept Peace Plan, With Conditions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with State Dept. denying existence
of the memo but commenting on PLO conditions. Pickup 8th, ``Shamir's right...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO is ready to accept Israel's plan for
elections in the occupied lands if the government agrees to certain
conditions, including the principle of trading land for peace,
legislators said today.
   The new PLO position is a considerable softening of the
organization's earlier policy of rejecting the peace plan unless
Israel first withdraws its forces from the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   Lawmaker Avraham Burg of the left-leaning Labor Party said
Israel learned of the PLO's latest views from a U.S. government
document outlining the organization's reaction to Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's election plan.
   The document was relayed to Israel by Soviet envoy Gennady
Terrasov, who met an aide to Vice Premier Shimon Peres this week in
Paris, said an Israeli official who insisted on anonymity.
   In Washington, Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department
spokeswoman, denied there is such a document. But she said:
``Obviously we have been working with all sides to support the
election concept and to initiate a dialogue between Israelis and
Palestinians... We are pressing for movement in this regard.''
   Another Labor legislator, Aryeh Eliav, said the PLO's positions
were also relayed by two aides to PLO chief Yasser Arafat during a
conference in Vienna this month.
   ``At this conference, I definitely heard from the PLO
representatives that they are ready for elections if Israel will
say in one way or the other that at the end of the process, Israel
is ready to trade territories for peace,'' Eliav told The
Associated Press. ``They said this very clearly.''
   The PLO demands also include allowing Arab residents in
Israeli-annexed east Jerusalem to vote in the elections.
   Ms. Tutwiler said, ``The PLO has told us privately, as it has
said publicly, that it supports the election concept as part of a
comprehensive peace plan. However, the PLO has put a number of
conditions on its support for elections which would prejudge the
outcome of a negotiated solution.''
   She said the conditions include an independent Palestinian state
as a guaranteed outcome and that such conditions ``are not
acceptable to us. This is a key issue which we continue to discuss
in our dialogue with the PLO.''
   Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes the land-for-peace
formula and allowing Arabs in east Jerusalem to vote. The
left-leaning Labor Party accepts those conditions.
   Israel's peace initiative calls for electing Palestinians in the
occupied territories to negotiate with Israel on an interim
self-rule plan, with talks to be held later on the final status of
the territories.
   On Tuesday, a pro-PLO Palestinian lawyer, Jamil Tarifi, said he
had met with Shamir to discuss the plan. Shamir has denied meeting
with pro-PLO Palestinians.
   Leftist legislator Yossi Sarid said Tarifi was a PLO member.
Tarifi refused to say if he was a PLO member.
   Tarifi said he told Shamir to deal with the PLO.
   ``The PLO will accept it (the plan), or it will not be
acceptable to the Palestinian people,'' he said he told Shamir.
   Shamir maintains the government has no contacts with the PLO,
but a leading Labor Party official said today Israel already was
negotiating indirectly with it.
   ``The fact that there are negotiations on this subject with the
PLO is clear and it has one aim, to get a green light from the PLO
for elections in the territories,'' Yossi Beilin, an aide to Labor
Party leader Shimon Peres, said on Israel army radio.
   He said the contacts were through the United States, Egypt and
Romania.
   According to Israeli sources, the PLO already has proposed
forming a delegation of 10 residents from the territories and two
Palestinian-Americans to meet with Israeli officials to discuss the
elections proposal.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the team
would eventually emerge as candidates in the elections and be
assured victory because of PLO backing.
   According to the sources and newspaper reports, other conditions
set by the PLO included:
   _Army withdrawal to predetermined positions on election day.
   _Allowing international observers to watch the voting. The
Jerusalem Post said a new element was PLO agreement to an
Egyptian-American ``coordinating team'' fulfilling this role
instead of U.N. supervision.
   _Israeli assurance that Palestinian candidates would have
freedom of speech and immunity from prosecution.
   _Acceptance by Israel of U.N. Security Council resolutions 242
and 338, which call on Israel to give up occupied land, and
Israel's recognition of the political rights of the Palestinian
people.
</TEXT>
