<FIRST>u a PM-ParaplegicClimber     07-26 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraplegic Climber,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraplegic Climber Expected To Reach Summit By Mid-Afternoon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Should stand for PMs. Climbers expected to reach summit about
5 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tired and buffeted by
strong winds, paraplegic mountain climber Mark Wellman was on the
verge today of conquering El Capitan.
   Wellman and his climbing partner, Mike Corbett, began their
final ascent at 7:30 a.m. after spending the night tied into
sleeping bags on Chickenhead Ledge about 300 from the summit of the
sheer granite mountain.
   By 9:30 a.m., the two had scaled 125 feet, said park spokeswoman
Lisa Dapprich. Wellman, whose legs are paralyzed, and his longtime
friend Corbett expected to pull themselves over the top by
mid-afternoon today, the eighth day of their climb, said Dapprich.
   In radio conversation with the men this morning, Dapprich said
Wellman remarked, ``We're looking forward to getting on top and
getting a hot meal.''
   Dapprich said she asked the climbers Tuesday how they were
feeling and Wellman said, `We're feeling OK, just tired and sore.'''
   Wellman, who pulled himself up six inches at a time on ropes
placed by Corbett, tried to become the first paraplegic to make the
climb.
   The biggest problem the climbers faced was the wind, which they
noted had been gusting from 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. every day, sometimes
blowing them 10 feet out from the cliff face.
   ``After five or six days, you get summit fever _ all you can
think of is the top,'' said Corbett in a radio conversation with a
park ranger Tuesday. ``I think when we get to the top, it will feel
like I received a gold medal.''
   Wellman said his powerful hands were swollen but that he was not
injured during his quest. He estimated it would take 7,000 pullups
to reach the summit.
   Wellman was left paralyzed from the waist down when he fell 50
feet during a climb of the 13,700-foot Gables Peak south of
Yosemite in 1982. He was in the hospital for seven months but has
since been active, staying in shape with sports such as kayaking
and directing the park's program for disabled visitors.
   Corbett had a record 41 ascents of El Capitan before the climb
with Wellman, a world record for climbing the 3,200-foot face of
the rock outcropping.
   He said he was unable to go to sleep Monday night after hearing
that members of his estranged family in Houston would arrive in
Yosemite sometime this weekend.
   The family heard about the climb and recognized Corbett, who
last talked to them in 1981. His younger brother said in a
television interview Tuesday that he considers his brother ``a
hero.''
   ``I named both of my sons after him - that should give an idea
of how I feel about him,'' Tony Corbett, of Houston, told NBC news.
   Corbett told his girlfriend that he left his family in Houston
after a ``really traumatic'' divorce by his parents.
</TEXT>
