<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Military-Drugs     07-26 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military-Drugs,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Cuts Drug Use, Moves Into Domestic Drug Interdiction Arena</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military has sharply cut drug use in its
own ranks and made significant progress in aiding drug interdiction
efforts in the United States, a Pentagon official said Wednesday.
   Assistant Defense Secretary Stephen M. Duncan said drug use
among U.S. military personnel has dropped from 27 percent in 1980
to 4.8 percent last year, largely due to drug testing.
   Duncan, the department's coordinator for drug enforcement policy
and support, also said the Pentagon is helping National Guard units
across the country to detect and monitor drug activities and using
its own resources for domestic interdiction efforts.
   But Duncan skirted questions at a news conference about the
military's possible future role in fighting cocaine at its South
American origins.
   ``We've had no guidance from the president yet,'' Duncan said.
When pressed, he added: ``We're not going to do anything without
the knowledge and support of the host government.''
   A National Security Council report on drugs reportedly
recommends an increased role for the U.S. armed forces in drug
interdiction in South America.
   President Bush, in pre-election speeches, pledged to fight
domestic cocaine use by taking action in Peru and Bolivia, where
the majority of the world's coca grows in the Andes mountains.
   But Peru's Maoist guerrillas presented a ``security threat'' to
American workers, the State Department said, and the programs have
been all but stopped since February. The tough coca plants continue
to produce four harvests a year, most of which ends up as processed
cocaine on U.S. streets.
   An administration source recently described direct U.S. military
involvement in drug interdiction in South America as ``effectively
a dead issue'' because none of the drug-producing nations would
``invite'' American troops.
   A comprehensive plan expected to include the military's overall
role in fighting drugs is due in September from the office of drug
policy coordinator William Bennett.
   Under a recent law, the Defense Department is the lead agency
for detecting and monitoring all air and sea drug activities. The
actual interdiction is done by other agencies, primarily the
Customs Service and the Coast Guard.
   Duncan noted the Pentagon's assistance to the National Guard for
drug interdiction, saying 52 plans submitted by the governors of
states and territories had received approval for part of a $40
million parcel earmarked for such programs.
   The guardsmen have been working mostly along the Southern border
with civilian law enforcement agencies to detect and monitor drug
smugglers. But states from Maine to Missouri as well as Puerto Rico
and the Virgin Islands have set up acceptable drug programs.
   ``This is the first time the Guard has been used in this way,''
Duncan said.
   Duncan also said the armed forces supplied 28,000 flight hours,
2,000 ship days and $300 million in equipment loans for its new
role in drug interdiction.
   ``I believe we've made significant progress,'' he said. ``I
think the American people need to understand, while there's a lot
we can do, we're not a law enforcement agency.''
   The General Accounting Office in June issued a report
criticizing the Pentagon's air effort, with its harshest comments
about the aerostat ballons intended to detect incoming planes. The
report said the ballons have trouble distinguishing the low,
slow-flying planes used by drug traffickers from ``surface
clutter.''
   Duncan said the Pentagon would ask Congress to increase its drug
budget from $308 million to $317.6 million for drug interdiction
assistance and from $112 million to 117.5 million for demand
reduction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
