<FIRST>r w AM-Mosbacher-Antitrust     07-26 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher-Antitrust,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Defends Antitrust Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher on
Wednesday defended the Bush administration against congressional
criticism that consumers could be hurt by the administration's
efforts to modify antitrust laws.
   Mosbacher said the administration would ``very soon'' present
Congress with its recommendations for ways to change the antitrust
laws to allow American companies to compete globally in the field
of high-technology products.
   The administration is considering a major relaxation of
antitrust laws that would allow companies to jointly produce
high-technology products, such as high-definition television sets.
   This would expand on an action taken by Congress in 1984 when it
changed the antitrust laws to allow companies to engage in joint
research efforts.
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks, D-Texas, told
Mosbacher that he had reservations about the need to further weaken
the antitrust statutes by allowing joint production as well as
joint research.
   Brooks said this was a ``more difficult question because it
raises issues about concerted behavior in the marketplace, not the
laboratory.''
   Rep. Lawrence J. Smith, D-Fla., called the proposal for an
antitrust exemption for manufacturing a ``much more radical
approach'' than the research exemption and he predicted that it
would encounter substantial congressional esistance.
   Smith said such an approach could allow American companies to
form giant monopolies that would boost prices to the detriment of
consumers.
   But Mosbacher said these arguments missed the point that
American companies were being forced to compete globally in the
development of new technology with foreign businesses that faced
for fewer antitrust restrictions.
   ``The entire industrial world is now in competition. We will
either adjust to that reality or we will not survive as a great
power,'' he told the committee.
   Mosbacher said that the administration was still considering
exactly what types of antitrust changes to propose to Congress.
   ``I think we will be pulling our act together very soon,'' he
said.
   In response to a question, Mosbacher said he did not think it
was proper to exclude foreign-owned companies from participating in
joint ventures in the United States.
   He said any antitrust exclusions should also be applied across
the board, rather than limited to just smaller firms, as some in
Congress have proposed.
   Mosbacher said it was crucial to America's future prosperity to
allow more joint ventures as a way of allowing companies to spread
the risks and costs of developing complex new technologies.
   ``Legislation aimed at reducing antitrust uncertainty could
allow American firms to move confidently into new technological
fields, thereby enhancing U.S. competitiveness,'' he said.
   Mosbacher said the administration's proposal would not be a
``backdoor attempt to undermine the antitrust laws and the
competitive, free enterprise economy they seek to protect.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PhoenixHeart     07-26 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phoenix Heart,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developer of Artificial Heart Needs Money for Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dentist who designed an experimental
artificial heart that was used in a human without federal approval
says he's improved his air-driven Phoenix Heart but needs money for
further development and testing.
   Kevin Cheng believes his latest versions are superior to
anything else in use.
   But he is unable to finance costly animal testing to prove his
devices work, which could bring federal approval for experimental
use in humans, or to develop a fully implantable and internally
driven heart.
   Cheng said he needs at least $300,000 for animal testing and may
have to try to find foreign backers for testing overseas,
mentioning Japan and the Republic of China.
   Cheng, who has sought federal and private grants without
success, says his last best hope for testing in the United States
rests with the University of Arizona in Tucson. But while he has
supporters there, federal support is unlikely for another
air-driven heart pump because it involves old technology.
   Such devices, including current Jarvik hearts, are powered by
external machines that pump air through tubes that pass through the
patient's chest wall. The patient is tethered and susceptible to
infections because of the tubes.
   Cheng, 46, achieved notoriety in March 1985 when an earlier
Phoenix Heart intended for calf testing was used at University
Medical Center, which is affiliated with the Tucson school, in an
emergency without the federal Food and Drug Administration's
authorization.
   The Phoenix Heart kept a patient whose body had rejected a donor
heart alive for 11 hours before a second transplant. The man died
of complications unrelated to the device.
   Dr. Jack G. Copeland, the UMC surgeon who arranged its use,
afterward acquired FDA-approved Jarvik-7s and pioneered their use
as bridges to keep patients alive until transplants are available.
Jarvik hearts, which were permanently implanted in five recipients
in the United States and Sweden, have since been used as transplant
bridges about 150 times in the United States.
   Between 1983 and 1987, Cheng implanted his devices in 10 calves
for as long as 10 days, but expenses forced their shutoff. Each
polyurethane heart costs $15,000.
   In the meantime, Cheng is at a standstill with virtually no
testing accomplished on his new designs, elliptical, polyurethane
Phoenix-7 and -8 models.
   He insists his design is superior to the Jarvik hearts, with
greater blood volume per stroke and slightly smaller size.
   The Phoenix Heart's three pumping membranes, versus the Jarvik's
one, will effectively remove all blood from the ventricle, ``and no
one else has done that yet,'' said Dr. Willem J. Kolff, one of the
nation's most respected artificial heart researchers.
   Kolff developed the first successful kidney dialysis machine and
is chief of the University of Utah's Division or Artificial Organs,
where the Jarvik heart was developed.
   Cheng's heart ``is novel, it's promising, it's unusual,'' Kolff
said. ``I see no reason why it should not work. It should be
tested.''
   If the Phoenix Heart were available and fully tested today,
``I'd say we could put it in instead of the Jarvik'' in bridge
situations, said Richard Smith, chief biomedical engineer at UMC.
But he said he thought it would be more useful for Cheng to work
toward a permanent, totally implantable heart with an internal
motor.
   Cheng's ultimate goal is a completely implantable
electro-hydraulic artificial heart, using currently available
technology, to provide patient mobility and a quality of life
lacking when tethered to an air-driven pump.
   Cheng, who worked at the Texas Heart Institute while in dental
school, said he wants to complete his 12-year-old project, which
has cost him $200,000, ``to save some human life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Strikes     07-26 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Strikes,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rail Workers Break Strike, but Commuters Still Hampered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of rail workers on Wednesday broke
Britain's sixth national rail strike in six weeks, British Rail
said, but most commuters still had to get to work without trains.
   The work stoppage halted service on much of the national rail
network. In addition, the 12th one-day walkout in 16 weeks by
London subway workers shut down the London Underground.
   The strikers are demanding higher wages.
   Thousands of commuters walked, cycled or jogged to work.
Transport Secretary Cecil Parkinson walked 1{ miles to Parliament.
   Two royal parks in London, Hyde Park and Regent's Park, served
as emergency parking lots.
   British Rail said Wednesday that 12,500 of the National Union of
Railwaymen's 75,000 employees showed up for work, but just 400 of
its normal 16,000 rail services operated.
   The union said British Rail's figures on strikebreakers were
inflated, but it did not offer estimates of its own.
   The first three trains into London carried just 15 passengers,
and rail union leader Jimmy Knapp mocked British Rail's attempts to
break the strike.
   ``It's a pitiful return for the amount of money, time and effort
they spent over the past week trying to persuade, cajole and
threaten people back into work,'' Knapp said.
   Commuter Douglas Wallace said he was the only person to board
the train at his local station at Hither Green, seven miles
southeast of London.
   ``I was the only passenger standing at the station, and when it
arrived, they said, `This is a train for you. Get on it,''' he said.
   The rail union paid for advertisements in several newspapers
Tuesday seeking to boost flagging support among its members.
   The Financial Times business daily quoted some rail workers as
saying they wanted to accept management's offer of an 8.8 percent
increase in basic pay. The union is seeking a 10 percent increase
in the basic wage of $188 a week.
   The 8.8 percent offer has been accepted by two other railway
unions.
   Subway workers are seeking a $103 weekly pay raise to operate
subway trains without conductors. Management has offered $48 a week
plus extra vacation time, but it is demanding increased production.
   About 9,400 dockworkers at London ports have been on strike
since July 10. Port officials say the strike is crumbling, with
only 37 of the 60 ports involved still idled.
   The dock strike began after Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative government abolished a jobs-for-life guarantee,
enacted in 1947, for dockers at the 60 ports.
   A major cause of the labor unrest has been Britain's annual
inflation rate of 8.3 percent, the highest in the 12-nation
European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
