<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Nazi     07-26 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Nazi,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Nazi War Criminal Discovered in Switzerland</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FRA5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WUPPERTAL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nazi war criminal known as the
``William Tell of Auschwitz'' for forcing prisoners to balance tin
cans on their heads before shooting them has been arrested in
Switzerland, officials said Wednesday.
   Gottfried Weise, 69, was arrested at a hospital in the Swiss
community of Thun, where he had sought treatment for a stroke, said
Horst Rosenbaum, Wuppertal's chief prosecutor. Weise had
disappeared from West Germany three months earlier.
   The head of the Thun regional hospital, Beat Straubhaar, said
Weise had been in the facility's care for two weeks under the name
of Sieber.
   The hospital chief said Weise disclosed that he was sought in
West Germany, and hospital authorities summoned police. Weise
indicated to hospital workers that he would voluntarily return to
West Germany without extradition, Straubhaar said.
   Weise was transferred to a prison hospital in Bern after his
arrest.
   He was convicted on Jan. 28, 1988, by a Wuppertal court of
killing at least five prisoners in 1944 while a guard at the
Auschwitz death camp in Poland.
   Weise had been allowed to remain at his home near Wuppertal
pending appeal to care for his sick wife. His disappearance was
discovered April 20 when police went to arrest him to begin serving
his sentence.
   Rosenbaum said it was a mystery how Weise was able to make his
way to Switzerland, as his passport had been confiscated.
   ``We suspect he stayed with Swiss or German friends in the area
of Thun,'' Rosenbaum said.
   During his trial, Weise became known as the ``William Tell of
Auschwitz.'' Witnesses testified that he forced an 8-year-old boy
and a 17-year-old girl to balance tin cans on their heads _
apparently making them believe that he would aim at the cans _ and
then fired shots at the two, killing them.
   He was convicted of their deaths and of killing two male
prisoners who tried to escape by hiding in a supply truck. Weise
also was convicted of killing an inmate for responding too slowly
to orders.
</TEXT>
