<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Elections     07-26 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Elections,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Call For Big Turnout In Vote Expected to Elect Rival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's main radical figures urged their
countrymen Wednesday to participate in this week's presidential
elections, even though their main rival, Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, is expected to win.
   Their declarations suggested they want to avoid a head-on
collision with Rafsanjani, who has emerged as the country's most
popular leader.
   State-run Tehran Radio quoted Ahmad Khomeini, the son of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, as saying that if his father were
alive, he would have been the first to cast a vote in Friday's
elections.
   ``God willing, on July 28, the dear people of Iran will throng
to the polls with steady stride,'' the broadcast quoted Khomeini as
saying.
   ``In doing so, they will gladden the hearts of our friends and
send our enemies to the dust of dismay,'' he said.
   Khomeini's son is considered the leader of Iranian radicals. His
group has been jockeying for power with pragmatists, led by
Rafsanjani, since the ayatollah died June 3.
   There had been speculation Khomeini would declare himself a
candidate for president against Rafsanjani, leading to an open
fight for power. However, radicals have shown more flexibility in
recent weeks in an apparent effort to avoid a direct challenge of
Rafsanjani.
   Hard-line Prime Minister Hussein Musavi, interviewed separately
by the radio, called for a ``massive turnout.''
   ``The government of the Islamic Republic considers voting in the
elections as a divine and national duty and will mobilize all its
capabilities for better holding of them,'' he said.
   Polls published by some newspapers predicted Rafsanjani will
take 86 percent of the votes.
   The same polls gave his only challenger, Abbas Sheibani, 11
percent while saying 3 percent of the Iranians questioned intend
not to vote.
   Iran's electorate was estimated at 25 million at last year's
parliamentary elections.
   Sheibani, 58, is a French-trained doctor and parliament deputy
without a national political base.
   The presidential elections were originally scheduled for Aug. 18
but were advanced to accelerate the transition of power after
Khomeini's death.
   A national referendum will be held with the presidential voting
on proposed constitutional amendments. The changes would increase
the president's powers, making him head of government and scrapping
the post of prime minister.
   The proposals are expected to win approval.
</TEXT>
