<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1601EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Gingrich     07-26 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>House GOP Whip Facing Questions About Payroll Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich, already
awaiting a possible ethics investigation into a book promotion
deal, is facing new questions about large temporary pay raises he
gave to aides, including some who briefly resigned to become
campaign workers.
   Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind., the ranking Republican on the House
ethics committee, said Wednesday the panel will look into
``anything we see,'' including the possibility of payroll
irregularities, if it approves a formal investigation of Gingrich.
   Gingrich said temporary, yearend raises are commonly used by
House members to reward hard-working staffers, and he said his
decision to award such raises is not influenced by whether an aide
takes time off from the staff to work in his campaign.
   A spot check of Gingrich's House colleagues from Georgia found
that four of nine gave aides large temporary raises last year, and
one, Rep. John Lewis of Atlanta, gave an aide a 27 percent pay
increase 15 days after he returned from a two-month campaign leave.
   The disclosure of Gingrich's practice, first made in an Atlanta
business publication, comes at an awkward time for the combative
House GOP whip who submitted the ethics complaint that led to
former Speaker Jim Wright's resignation.
   Myers said the committee could meet as early as next week, and
may be ready to decide then whether to begin a formal investigation
of Gingrich. sparked by a complaint about the book deal.
   ``If we vote for a preliminary inquiry, we would look at
everything,'' Myers said when asked if the panel would investigate
Gingrich's payroll. ``As in the Jim Wright case, we would look into
anything we see.''
   House payroll records show that Gingrich gave temporary raises
to 15 staffers last fall, including two aides who took leaves for
campaign work. He gave similar raises to 13 aides in both 1987 and
1986, including two in 1986 who took leaves to work in his
re-election campaign.
   Myers said he did know whether it was a widespread practice for
House members to give aides who worked on their campaigns a
temporary raise after they returned.
   ``If true it would be troubling,'' he said. ``It would violate
the spirit of the House. We do not want to use government funds to
fund our campaigns.''
   House personnel rules state that ``yearend raises should be made
only on a permanent basis and only when the services of the
individual warrant.'' Federal law and House rules also prohibit
members from rewarding staff members for campaign work.
   The two Gingrich aides who took leaves for the 1988 campaign
were press secretary Sheila Ward, and executive assistant Sarah
Grewe. During the one-month leaves, the campaign paid Ward $1,612
and Grewe $1,262. At the pay rates in effect when they took the
leaves, Ward would have earned $1,606 and Grewe $1,500 if they had
stayed on the congressional payroll.
   After returning to the congressional payroll in mid-November, a
temporary raise gave Ward $1,979 more than she would have made the
rest of the year at her old rate. Grewe earned an additional $1,986.
   In the final quarter of the year, Ward's total salary from both
the campaign and the congressional office was $6,804, or $1,984
more than she would have made if her October pay rate had been in
effect the rest of the year. Grewe's total salary for the quarter
of $6,348, also was about 41 percent, or $1,848, more than she
would have earned at the October rate.
   The other 13 permanent members of Gingrich's congressional staff
also received large temporary raises during the final quarter of
1988, boosting their overall pay by amounts ranging from 9 percent
to 44.9 percent, or from $400 to $3,392.
   The salaries of all 15 staffers were reduced on Jan. 1, 1989,
though their new levels still ranged between 4 percent and 33
percent higher than the salaries the previous October.
   During the 1986 campaign, the two aides who took leaves were
Catherine Brock, assistant state administrator, and Katherine
Watson, a legislative assistant. During the 10-week leaves, the
campaign paid Brock $3,588 and Watson $2,141. Had they stayed on
the congressional payroll at their pre-leave pay rate, Brock would
have earned $4,140 during the 10 weeks and Watson would have earned
$4,600.
   After returning to the congressional payroll in mid-November,
temporary raises gave Brock $2,820 more in salary for the remainder
of the year than she would have earned at the pre-leave pay rate,
and Watson $2,520 more.
   In 1986, Gingrich began dispensing the temporary raises to his
staff in August. For the rest of the year, the temporary raises
boosted the total pay of the 11 other permanent staffers by amounts
ranging from $1,280 to $5,000, or from 13 percent to 67 percent.
</TEXT>
