<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-26 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Troops and Civilians Uncover Hidden Explosives in Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan security forces Wednesday
discovered an 11-pound bomb hidden in a crowded Kabul vegetable
market, the government said.
   Twenty-four hours earlier, people at a state store discovered a
briefcase that also contained a cache of explosives, said Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani.
   The discoveries, which could not be confirmed independently,
were reported at a time of increased rocket attacks and a car
bombing that have killed more than 200 people in Kabul this month.
Nearly all victims were civilians.
   Moslem guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-backed government
have been firing long-range rockets from behind the hills that ring
the mile-high capital.
   Also Wednesday, Amani said, security forces discovered two
rockets positioned for attack on Kabul in the northwestern
foothills.
   ``Extremists, faced with serious defeat, to save face are
resorting to terrorist activity, and a lot of innocent civilians
are falling victim to the attacks,'' he said.
   He said the explosives in the market were left in a bag beside a
shop.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas claim responsibility for rocket
attacks but not for planting explosives or car bombs.
   Security forces conducting house-to-house searches discovered
``a large quantity of arms and ammunition,'' Amani said.
   In another incident, security forces arrested a man carrying
$12,000 in forged notes, he said. Amani said this is part of the
guerrillas' ``economic sabotage'' against the government.
   Outside Kabul, he said, government forces recently killed more
than 280 guerrillas, including Pakistani army officers and six
Saudi Arabians. The two countries admit aiding the guerrillas but
deny having fighters in Afghanistan.
   Amani said government troops are pushing the guerrillas into
retreat southeast of Jalalabad, toward the town of Torxam, near the
Pakistani border. In that fighting, soldiers killed 27 guerrillas
and captured two tanks, five mortars and a large quantity of arms
and ammunition, he said.
   Jalalabad has been the scene of the fiercest fighting since
Soviet troops backing the government withdrew February under a U.N.
agreement.
   Amani said another 74 guerrillas were killed in a July 23
operation against followers of guerrilla leader Gulbaddin
Hekmatayar in western Maidan Shahr, capital of Wardak province.
   Government troops repulsing an attack outside the city by
Hekmatayar's followers killed 180 guerrillas, Amani said.
   Both sides often exaggerate reports of fighting and casualties
that are impossible to verify.
</TEXT>
