<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Ambassadors     07-26 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Ambassadors,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Defends Diplomatic Choices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only one-third of President Bush's embassy
appointments are political, a White House official said Wednesday
in response to complaints that the administration is handing out
plum ambassadorial assignments as political payoffs.
   Bush's list of nominees contains the names of several people who
gave six-figure contributions to Republicans in the last election,
but White House spokesman B. Jay Cooper said they were chosen on
the basis of their qualifications.
   Cooper said Secretary of State James A. Baker III is using a
formula to ensure that 67 percent of the appointments are career
government officers and 33 percent are political appointees,
brought in by the president.
   He said there is currently a greater percentage of political
appointees because some now serving are carryovers from the Reagan
administration, when the ratio was 60 percent career officers to 40
percent political appointees.
   Some Bush appointments have raised a firestorm of criticism in
Senate Foreign Relations Committee hearings to confirm the
ambassadors.
   Sens. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., Albert Gore, D-Tenn., and other
Democrats have complained that the appointees lack sufficient
qualifications beyond their financial and political connections.
   At least six of the people Bush appointed to ambassadorships
gave $100,000 or more to the Republican National Committee. Their
names are listed in the RNC's so-called soft money files, which
means their donations are not subject to the $1,000 limit on
contributions to individual federal campaigns.
   Those six include Nicolas Salgo, the former ambassador to
Hungary whom Bush named to the rank of ambassador to negotiate
property issues in his job as director of the State Department's
Moscow Embassy building control office. He gave the RNC just over
$500,000 last year.
   The others who gave $100,000 are Joy Silverman, who has no job
history and was named as ambassador to Barbados and four other
Caribbean island nations; Florida real estate magnate Joseph
Zappala, named as ambassador to Spain; Louisiana oil company
executive John Giffen Weinmann as ambassador to Finland;
Mississippi developer Melvin Sembler as ambassador to Australia;
and Washington attorney Joseph B. Gildenhorn as ambassador to
Switzerland.
   Zappala narrowly won confirmation on Tuesday in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, with Sarbanes vowing to continue the
fight against him and others on the Senate floor. Zappala reported
to the committee that he gave $126,000 to Republican political
causes last year and $17,900 in the two years before that.
   Many other appointees named to ambassadorships or other
high-level administration posts were members of Bush's campaign
finance committee or gave contributions of $10,000 or more to the
RNC soft money fund.
   Cooper said Wednesday that all will make ``excellent
ambassadors'' and that each one was chosen on the basis of specific
qualifications they bring to their posts.
</TEXT>
