<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz     07-26 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rabbi Beaten at Auschwitz Plans to Press Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American rabbi who was beaten by Polish
workers while protesting the presence of a convent at Auschwitz
said Wednesday he will press charges against the attackers and
police who did nothing to stop them.
   Rabbi Avraham Weiss and six U.S. Jewish students were removed
from the camp in Poland and kicked and beaten by the construction
workers during a July 14 demonstration to protest the presence of
the Carmelite convent on the camp grounds.
   The international Jewish community considers Christian symbols
on the perimeter of the camp a desecration of the memory of those
who died at the Nazi concentration camp. An estimated 2.5 million
Jews were among the 4 million people killed at Auschwitz.
   ``The convent is offensive to the Jewish people. It is part of
the larger Vatican attempt to Christianize the Holocaust,'' Weiss,
of Riverdale, N.Y., said at a news conference.
   Weiss dismissed claims the convent was meant as a memorial to
Christians who died in the camp.
   ``Jews were murdered because they were Jews. Christians were
murdered because they were Polish political prisoners who happened
to be Christians,'' he said.
   Jewish groups are demanding the Carmelite nuns respect an
agreement to move. That agreement was reached by church officials
and representatives of international Jewish organizations in 1987
and originally called on the nuns to leave by February.
   They were to move to a convent that has yet to be built.
   Polish news reports have said work on the new convent will begin
next year.
   Weiss said he arrived in Israel after meeting New York Cardinal
John O'Connor, who promised to write an article supporting the
Jewish cause within the next 10 days.
   Weiss said he will be pressing charges through the Polish
representative in Israel against the Polish assailants and police
who he claimed stood by and did not intervene during the beatings.
   ``We have hired lawyers ... and we are going to be asking the
Polish representative to press charges against those citizens who
beat us. We know who they are. Their pictures were on front pages
of newspapers throughout the world,'' Weiss said.
   He added he wanted an investigation into what role the nuns
played in the incident. ``After all,'' he said, ``these
construction workers came from the convent.''
   Weiss also demanded that Israel take charge of Auschwitz as a
symbol of the Holocaust.
   ``Unless Israel is going to administer and oversee Auschwitz, it
would be impossible for Auschwitz to retain its unique message of
being ... that place where the Nazis tried to exterminate Jews.''
</TEXT>
