<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1609EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ProstituteMarch Bjt   07-26 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prostitute March, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some D.C. Ladies of the Night Rounded Up and Marched Toward Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The march was short, the apparel was shorter
and tempers in neighboring Virginia were shortest.
   It seems some enterprising Washington police officers tried
something new early Tuesday to rid the downtown area of prostitutes
_ by herding 24 ladies of the night across the Potomac River toward
suburban Arlington.
   This army, more of a platoon, really, marched not on its
stomach, but on spiked heels. Not to the beat of drums, but to the
muffled rustle of vinyl hot pants and leather miniskirts.
   Still, it was like a shot heard 'round the commonwealth, which,
notwithstanding the ``Welcome to Virginia'' sign on the far side of
the river, was mightily displeased by this latest export from the
city bearing the name of the state's favorite son.
   ``This is the fourth commodity the District (of Columbia)
exports to Virginia,'' snapped Rep. Stan Parris. ``We get all the
sludge, all the garbage, most of the prisoners and now their
prostitutes.''
   A fellow Virginia Republican, Sen. John Warner, took to the
Senate floor to denounce the forced march of the prostitutes as
``an indignity to the Commonwealth of Virginia.'' He demanded that
Mayor Marion Barry discipline those involved in ``this incredible,
almost unbelievable episode, in law enforcement.''
   ``This isn't for real, is it?'' said Arlington Police Chief
William K. Stover. ``I've been in this business for 33 years, and I
never heard of such a thing in my life. I don't know how in the
world you get the authority to parade a lot of prostitutes in front
of a police car. That's like herding cattle. I feel now like I
ought to shore up my boundaries.''
   Barry's office declined comment, and no official of the
Washington Metropolitan Police accepted responsibility for the
bizarre roundup and 1{-mile march. It began, at about 1:30 a.m.
Tuesday, just seven blocks from the White House, and ended less
than an hour later on the 14th Street Bridge, the main artery
spanning the Potomac between Virginia and downtown Washington.
   The women were gathered from sidewalks near the intersection of
14th and L streets, the hub of the red-light district, and ordered
to hoof down the left lane of 14th to the Virginia border. A police
scout car, with red and blue lights flashing, led the assemblage,
while another brought up the rear.
   ``They said they were taking us to Virginia, that we could work
over there,'' said a woman who identified herself only as Toni.
``They said we'd go to jail if we stopped.'' None of the women was
arrested.
   ``It was like a perverted Memorial Day parade,'' said a
dumbfounded Treasury Department officer who witnessed the march
from his post at the Bureau of Engraving and Printing.
   The marchers had just started up the approach to the bridge when
a Washington Post reporter and photographer happened on the scene.
According to the Post, two officers grabbed the photographer when
he starting taking pictures and ordered him to stop. ``You're going
to ruin what we're trying to do,'' the officer was quoted as saying.
   When the photographer continued taking pictures, the newspaper
said, the four officers involved in the procession piled into their
cars, made U-turns, and drove against one-way traffic back into
town, leaving the weary women sitting on the sidewalk, rubbing
their sore feet.
   The officers had declined to identify themselves, and one, when
asked who was in charge, replied ``Nobody's in charge,'' the Post
said.
   Three police districts intersect at 14th and L, and spokesmen
for two of them denied any involvement. The commander of the other
one, Deputy Chief Edward J. Spurlock, promised an investigation and
said ``It's definitely not something I would approve. It sounds
awful bizarre to me. I assure you that's not the kind of thing we
encourage.''
   ``I hope the police department doesn't take this as a joke,''
said Arthur B. Spitzer, legal director of the local American Civil
Liberties Union. ``There's no law that allows police officers to
deport people.''
   Others weren't so critical. ``We'd be thrilled if they'd drive
them to Omaha, and we'd contribute for gas,'' said Barbara
Rothenberg, vice chairman of the neighborhood's citizens advisory
council.
   The shorter excursion apparently had little effect. When the
march ended, the women shared cabs back into town and most returned
to the same sidewalks whence they began.
</TEXT>
