<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Sudan     07-26 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Sudan,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunger Looms Again at Village Where 8,000 Starved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A village in southern Sudan where 8,000
people starved to death last summer could see a repeat of the
disaster because of insufficient food stocks for its surging
population, a relief official said Wednesday.
   The Western official said relief donors are studying
possibilities for sending more food to Abyei, the village 500 miles
southwest of the Sudanese capital, Khartoum.
   The official, who spoke in a telephone interview from Khartoum,
declined to be identified by name or organization because of the
sensitivity of the relief issue with the Sudanese government.
   The United Nations estimates that 250,000 people died as a
result of starvation and civil war in the southern Sudan during
1988. The world body says 100,000 more could die this year unless
its huge relief operation to send 105,000 tons of food into the
south succeeds.
   About 70,000 tons of supplies will have been moved by the end of
July, relief officials say.
   The Western official said Abyei received 3,000 tons of food,
enough to get 26,000 inhabitants and refugees through the June to
November rainy season. During that time, heavy rains isolate many
areas.
   However, the official said in the past few weeks up to 20,000
more refugees have arrived in Abyei, and ``the food is no longer
enough to last them through the rainy season.''
   The official also said many refugees were streaming in daily to
nearby Aweil, where 4,000 other people starved last year. However,
he had no details on food supplies there.
   Sudan's civil war started in 1983. Christians and animists are
fighting for more autonomy from the Arab Moslem majority government
in the north. The rebels claim to control up to 95 percent of the
southern countryside.
   The fighting has forced up to 2 million southerners to flee
their homes and livelihoods, making them dependent on relief food.
About 23 million people live in all of Sudan.
</TEXT>
