<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-26 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Secretary General Satisfied With Namibian Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar expressed concern Wednesday about the possibility of
thousands of people being held in Angola by the South-West Africa
People's Organization.
   At a news conference on the last day of a summit by the
Organization of African Unity, Perez de Cuellar also said the U.N.
peacekeeping force is adequate to ensure free elections scheduled
in the former South African colony this fall.
   South Africa occupied the territory during World War I and began
to administer it in 1920 under a mandate from the League of
Nations. The league's successor, the United Nations, revoked the
mandate in 1966, called for an end to South African rule and
declared SWAPO the legitimate representative of the Namibian people.
   SWAPO still has bases in Angola, which borders on Namibia,
although its members are being repatriated to participate in the
pre-independence election campaign scheduled to lead to
parliamentary balloting in early November 1989.
   Perez de Cuellar said he discussed the matter of detainees with
SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma in Zambia last week.
   ``I think it is not only a concern of the South African
government, but the population would like to know the whereabouts
of 2,000 men,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   Legwaila Joseph Legwaila, Botswana's United Nations ambassador
and the secretary-general's special representative for Namibia,
noted that SWAPO released 201 detainees a few weeks ago and claims
those were all it held.
   He emphasized that there was no hard evidence to support claims
of thousands more in detention, ``but ... rumors are rife in
Namibia that there are still 2,000 to 2,500 detainees in Angola.''
</TEXT>
