<FIRST>r w AM-US-EuropeanTV     07-26 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-European TV,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Too Much American TV on European Sets? Congress Hears Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British media executive Robert Maxwell urged
Congress on Wednesday not to go to ``war'' with the European
Community over a proposal to limit how much U.S. programming may be
shown on European TV.
   Maxwell appeared before a House subcommittee that is considering
a possible U.S. response if the European Community limits American
programming to about 50 percent of what is shown on European TV. He
said Europe is determined to limit U.S. imports one way or the
other.
   But Hollywood representatives at Wednesday's hearing of the
House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications and
finance said they could not live with a quota system that threatens
to erode the $2.5 billion balance of trade surplus the U.S. film
and television industry has overseas.
   The European Community proposal is part of a plan to lower trade
barriers between the 12 European nations in 1992. The ``Television
Without Frontiers'' proposal calls for a ``majority proportion'' of
transmission time, ``where practical,'' to be reserved for works of
European origin with the 12 member nations.
   It would replace a patchwork of existing restrictions that range
from tough, mandatory quotas in France to none at all in Denmark
and Greece.
   Maxwell, who has extensive publishing and cable TV holdings in
Britain, France and elsewhere, told the subcommittee that rather
than making ``saber-rattling'' threats of trade retaliation, the
Bush administration and Hollywood producers should try to negotiate
a more favorable quota system with the 12-nation European Community.
   Otherwise, Hollywood will face even harsher restrictions if the
European countries are left to impose quotas individually, he said.
   He said the European proposal, because it wasn't mandatory, was
a compromise ``soft quota'' system that was considerably less
stringent than that being sought by France, Belgium and the
Netherlands. Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain will not accept
mandatory quotas, he said.
   He said he was here to open a ``dialogue'' with Hollywood
executives to try to reach an accord, but ``but that dialogue
cannot be no quotas.''
   He urged the subcommittee not to ``blindly support this (U.S.
film-TV) industry if it leads to war with Europe.''
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said he welcomed negotiations, but if talks fail, the
Hollywood community will ask Congress to ``help protect a national
asset.''
   ``When quotas come in the front door, consumer choice goes out
the back,'' Valenti said.
   American shows such as ``Dallas'' are very popular overseas, and
they are relatively inexpensive to buy. But Maxwell said just 5,000
hours out of 105,000 hours of movies and tapes shown on European TV
are produced in Europe, with the rest mainly coming from the United
States.
   That makes it an issue of money and jobs _ and preserving
Europe's ``cultural diversity,'' Maxwell said. ``European citizens
will not sit in their parlors watching their culture replaced by
images made in Hollywood, Mexico City or Tokyo.''
   But subcommittee Chairman Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., told
Maxwell there was strong bipartisan feeling in Congress that the
United States would do what it had to keep markets open overseas.
   He said the proposed quoto was ``strongly opposed by the
adminstration, which has criticized it as violative of
international trade agreements and aimed at reducing a $2.5 billion
trade surplus in one of the very few remaining sectors where the
United States enjoys a trade surplus.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChinesePigs     07-26 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Pigs,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Herd of `Prolific' Chinese Pigs Admitted to US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A herd of Chinese hogs has been officially
admitted into the United States for breeding experiments, the
Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   The 140 hogs were released after four months of quarantine and
testing at the department's animal import center on Fleming Key
near Key West, Fla., said James W. Glosser, administrator of the
department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service.
   The Chinese animals were described as ``unusually prolific'' and
that their twice-yearly litters average 16 to 20 newborn, with a
record of 33. That compares to an average of 10 to 12 young for
most U.S. breeds, he said.
   Three breeds with exotic names are involved: Meishan, Ming and
Feng-Jing. The animals were obtained through a contract between the
department's Agricultural Research Service and the Chinese National
Animal Breeding Stock Import and Export Corp.
   Under the agreement, the USDA research agency, the University of
Illinois, and Iowa State University are equally sharing costs of
the imported hogs and will share the animals for study.
   Glosser said the hogs will next reside at USDA's meat animal
research center, Clay Center, Neb.; the University of Illinois,
Urbana; and Iowa State University, Ames.
</TEXT>
