<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1650EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas     07-26 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucas Wins Undecided Senator Specter In Confirmation Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas won over a key undecided
lawmaker Tuesday in his drive to become the nation's chief civil
rights enforcer, putting him a step closer to gaining the blessing
of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   ``It's more important to have someone who understands Supreme
Court decisions from personal experience, knows it so to speak in
his gut, as opposed to someone who knows where to put all the
commas and semicolons,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., in
endorsing Lucas.
   His endorsement of the embattled nominee came the day before a
scheduled committee vote on whether to recommend the nomination.
Specter said support and opposition for Lucas were nearly equal
``at this precise moment.''
   Civil rights groups contend Lucas, 61, a former Wayne County,
Mich., sheriff and county executive who is black, lacks the
experience to serve as assistant attorney general for civil rights.
   The nomination is on the Judiciary Committee agenda for
Thursday, although any member of the panel could force a
postponement and Specter said a quick vote following last week's
hearings would be unusual.
   Specter had been considered the one committee Republican who
might oppose Lucas. His decision put the spotlight on Sen. Howell
Heflin, D-Ala., as a possible swing vote with power to send the
nomination to the Senate floor with the panel's blessing.
   Eight votes are needed for a favorable recommendation. It
appeared that Lucas could rely on all six of the committee's
Republicans plus Sen. Dennis DeConcini, although the Arizona
Democrat has never quite finalized his support.
   A number of lawmakers remained undeclared, but the nominee
appeared likely to face opposition from six other Democrats on the
committee with Heflin a lingering question mark.
   Even if Heflin voted against Lucas, the nomination could still
go to the floor without a recommendation or even with an
unfavorable one, although that could make it even harder for Lucas
to win confirmation in the Democratic-controlled Senate.
   President Bush, in an interview with Knight-Ridder on Tuesday
that was released Wednesday, dismissed most of the arguments
against Lucas as motivated by ``pure politics.''
   ``I am convinced that a lot of the opposition... came because he
made the mistake of changing to the Republican Party,'' Bush said,
referring to Lucas' switch before a 1986 run for Michigan governor.
``I strongly support him.''
   The position Lucas is seeking entails supervising 151 attorneys
and a much larger support staff that is charged with enforcing the
nation's civil rights laws through the courts. He would succeed
William Bradford Reynolds, who was at odds with civil rights groups
throughout much of the Reagan administration.
   The Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights Under Law, whose past
presidents include attorneys general, law school deans and leading
lawyers, recommended Wednesday that the Judiciary Committee reject
the Lucas nomination.
   ``On the basis of Mr. Lucas' lack of substantive legal
experience and his lack of understanding of both basic civil rights
law and civil rights decisions of the United States Supreme Court,
we cannot support Mr. Lucas,'' the group said in a letter to
committee chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del.
   Ralph Neas, executive director of the Leadership Conference on
Civil Right, said his group was disappointed by Specter's decision
``but we remain confident that the Senate will not confirm Mr.
Lucas.''
   David Runkel, an assistant to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh,
said he was ``confident and even more confident with Senator
Specter's announced support'' that Lucas will win a favorable
recommendation. ``We're hopeful there will be a vote tomorrow.''
   Following the appearance of Lucas before the Judiciary Committee
last week both Biden and Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said they were
disturbed by the nominee's answers to questions about civil rights
issues.
   He repeatedly sidestepped invitations from the lawmakers to be
critical of recent Supreme Court decisions that are under fire from
civil rights groups.
   Specter scoffed at this criticism, however, telling reporters
that Lucas was politically bound to agree with the positions
already expressed by Bush and Thornburgh.
   ``Had he deviated from what either of his bosses had said, he
could have been in a lot of hot water,'' Specter said. He said
Lucas' experiences as he rose from dishwasher to major public
official would help him do the civil rights job.
</TEXT>
