<FIRST>r w AM-LungDrug     07-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lung Drug,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Allows Wider Use of Experimental Drug for Premature Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Wednesday
authorized wider use of an experimental drug to treat and prevent a
respiratory disorder that is the leading cause of death and
disability among premature infants.
   Respiratory Distress Syndrome, also called hyaline membrane
disorder, afflicts as many as 50,000 of the 250,000 infants born
prematurely each year in the United States.
   About 5,000 of them die from the condition, which occurs when
immature lungs are not yet producing an inside coating that keeps
them from collapsing when the infant exhales, the FDA said. A son
born to then-President and Mrs. John F. Kennedy in 1963 died of the
disorder, the agency said.
   The drug, a synthetic surfactant, is licensed by Burroughs
Wellcome Co. of Research Triangle Park, N.C.
   It will be made available under an FDA category used for drugs
shown to be safe and effective for a serious or life-threatening
disease but not yet approved for commercial marketing.
   The FDA said the drug can be administered as a single dose
immediately after birth to help prevent death in high-risk
premature infants of 1.5 to 2.5 pounds, or as two doses to treat
infants of more than 1.5 pounds who have the syndrome.
   The drug has been associated with an increase in episodes of
apnea, a temporary cessation of breathing that is not fatal and is
correctable, the FDA said.
   The agency said Burroughs Wellcome will make the drug available
at no cost to U.S. hospitals and other health-care facilities that
can provide state-of-the-art care to high-risk mothers and infants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
