<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0627 07-26 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ships Deliver Food to Christians Amid Report of Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with new artillery barrages, casualty
toll; pickup 4th pvs, `A police...' Edits thereafter to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Syrian gunners unleashed
barrages of artillery and rockets on Beirut's residential districts
Wednesday, killing five people and shattering a two-day lull in
their 19-week-old confrontation.
   Police said 20 people were also wounded in the attacks, which
began shortly after nightfall.
   The thuds of exploding shells shook the city, and orange flashes
of exploding rockets illuminated the skies over Beirut, which was
in total darkness because of fuel oil shortages at power plants.
   Ambulances, their sirens wailing, raced through the city streets
and radio stations blared appeals to residents of the divided
capital to hurry to basements and bomb shelters.
   The radio stations later reported several fires burning out of
control in Beirut.
   Long-range artillery guns in the Christian heartland blasted
east Lebanon's Bekaa valley, targetting the Syrian army's supply
routes from Damascus. They also hit west Beirut and hills to the
southeast with 155mm howitzers and 130mm mortars.
   The Syrians blasted east Beirut and dozens of villages and towns
to the north and northeast, using mortar guns and Soviet-designed
BM-21 multi-barreled rocket launchers which spit out 40 projectiles
per minute.
   The sudden nighttime escalation capped day-long skirmishes with
automatic rifles across Beirut's dividing Green Line in which nine
other people were wounded. It shattered hopes of a temporary truce
until a political settlement could be worked out.
   The new casualties raised the toll to 458 killed and 1,889
wounded since the current round of fighting in the 14-year civil
war broke out March 8.
   Earlier Wednesday, five cargo ships carrying food supplies
docked at ports in the besieged Christian enclave north of the
capital, and reports said an undeclared truce was in force.
   A police spokesman said Syrian batteries fired only six
howitzers at daybreak as two vessels sailed slowly into Beirut Port
and three into Jounieh, 12 miles to the north.
   Previously, hundreds of shells and rockets would rain on the
coast when a vessel was seen. Syrian gunners have hit at least six
ships since March.
   The police spokesman said Lebanese army Gen. Michel Aoun's
gunners retaliated with four artillery rounds at Syrian batteries
on west Beirut beaches. He refused to disclose the ships' names,
flags or owners.
   They carried ``canned food supplies, including meat and
vegetables,'' the spokesman said.
   He said it was ``very unusual of the Syrians not to fire
heavily'' at the ships.
   Aoun's 20,000 mainly Christian soldiers and a 6,000-strong
coalition of right-wing Christian militias control a 28-mile
stretch of Lebanon's 130-mile Mediterranean coast.
   Syrian and allied Moslem forces have trapped 1 million
Christians in the enclave for four months. They enforced the siege
in retaliation for a blockade Aoun ordered on illegal ports run by
Moslem militias.
   The prestigious daily newspaper An-Nahar earlier reported an
``undeclared truce.'' It said an Arab League peace committee
mediated the cease-fire after ``discreet contacts'' with Aoun and
the Syrian leadership.
   The ``combatants agreed to give the tripartite committee another
chance to bring about a peaceful end to the conflict,'' An-Nahar
said, but added: ``It is not known how long the cease-fire would
last'' without an official declaration.
   The committee, comprising Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid,
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and King Hassan II of Morocco, has been
criticized severely for failing to make progress a month after it
was formed.
   Kuwait's Al-Qabas daily, in a front-page report said the
committee has decided to ``freeze its activities for a short period
of time'' while it considers Syria's refusal to negotiate with Aoun.
   ``The key hurdle blocking the work of the three-member
committee... is the recognition of Aoun as a negotiating partner,''
the newspaper said.
   It quoted Syrian President Hafez Assad as saying: ``If our
Lebanese allies accept Aoun as a negotiator on behalf of the other
party, we will not accept him. This is a final and irreversible
decision.''
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' to drive Syria's
40,000 troops out of Lebanon for violating their Arab League
peacekeeping mandate by siding with the Moslems.
</TEXT>
