<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GMPlant     07-26 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Plant,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,300 Idled GM Plant Workers Call It a Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nissan-UAW</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Buick, shimmering in a fresh
coat of white paint, rolled out of the 41-year-old General Motors
Corp. plant here Wednesday, marking the end of the line for 1,300
workers.
   Some workers are turning down a company buyout, holding out hope
that the plant might open again some day. But most were resigned to
the idea there would be no reprieve for the plant.
   ``We've done a lot of deep thinking about what we're going to do
with our lives,'' said supervisor Robert Biscotti. ``There has been
a grieving period, but after a while you realize: `What can you
do?'''
   GM is closing the plant because demand for the Buick Century and
Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera it produces isn't keeping up with the
company's capacity to build them.
   Dee Allen, a Detroit-based spokesman for the automaker, said
there is little chance the plant would be reopened.
   ``We haven't precluded the option of opening again, but we have
more than enough facilities without Framingham,'' he said.
   The plant has had two other layoffs, including about 1,200 this
spring, and some temporary closings during the last several years.
About 500 workers are staying on temporarily to help put the plant
in mothballs.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who worked to keep the plant
open, concedes there is little that can be done if people aren't
buying cars.
   The plant's manager, J. Russell McCarthy, drove the last car off
the line and into the loading yard.
   ``We've had good years where we've worked six days a week and
then days where we don't work at all,'' said Roland Cole, a 20-year
plant veteran and United Auto Workers member.
   ``It's been a home to a lot of us. We've been like brothers,''
says Joao DeCruz, a native of Portugal who plans to go on
unemployment.
   Dominic Miele, a 28-year plant veteran, was less philosophical:
``We've got a president who wants to give Poland $100 million when
we can't take care of our own at home.''
   Many of the senior employees have opted for early retirement.
Some have taken advantage of GM, state and federally funded
retraining programs or relocation.
   Others have accepted a company buyout that union officials say
they can't discourage because the prospects for getting rehired are
nil. GM offered one-time payments of $40,000 to workers with 10 or
more years service and $65,000 to those with 25 years on the job.
   Dukakis recalled Wednesday how he met with GM President Roger
Smith and other top company officials about sparing the plant after
the company announced the closing plans in February.
   ``All I can tell you is what he (Smith) said to me, and that was
that they didn't invest a quarter of a billion dollars to modernize
the plant so (GM could) walk away from it,'' Dukakis said.
   The company plans to bring down costs by building A-cars like
the Cutlass Ciera and Century only at its plants in Oklahoma City;
St. Therese, Quebec, and Ramos Aripze, Mexico.
   The plant, Framingham's largest employer, last year paid
$830,000 in local taxes, spent $19 million on local suppliers and
had a payroll of $59 million.
   The city of 65,000 is likely to suffer the blow better than many
factory towns because of its diverse economic base, which includes
computer manufacturing, stationery production and a 375-room hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
