<FIRST>u w AM-IRSProbe     07-26 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRS Probe,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Told Inspectors Should Not Be Compromised by Personal
Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress was told Wednesday that Internal
Revenue Service inspectors in charge of keeping employees honest
should be separated from the rest of the agency so they aren't
compromised by personal relationships.
   ``While nominally independent today, inspection is dependent on
other IRS functions to operate on a daily basis,'' said Frank
Rippetoe, former inspector in Los Angeles.
   ``This sometimes leads to attempts by IRS managers to influence
internal security activities,'' he told the House Government
Operations subcommittee on on commerce, consumer and monetary
affairs.
   IRS officials were to testify Thursday at the hearings into
accusations involving the agency. But in testimony released in
advance, Commissioner Fred Goldberg said steps are being taken to
minimize employee misconduct.
   IRS officials have said they would not comment on specific cases
because of privacy laws concerning tax returns.
   Initial witnesses on the second day of hearings were formerly
employed at the tax agency's Los Angeles office, where the
subcommittee's probe began.
   They told of an internal investigation of the former head of the
Criminal Investigative Division in Los Angeles which they believed
was compromised by personal relationships.
   ``The chief of CID was Ron Saranow and he did not encourage
cooperation by his agents unless it was to resolve a problem for
him,'' said Rippetoe. ``Mr. Saranow and several of his managers
cultivated a friendship with one of the inspection managers in
L.A., Debbie Jones, and led his agents to believe that she could be
approached to assist them if they had a problem with inspection.''
   Witnesses said that in the Los Angeles office Saranow had
considerable control over what was said about him.
   Former inspector Russ Davis said Saranow and Jones were commonly
believed to have a ``close, personal relationship.''
   As a result, when Saranow became the subject of an internal
probe, agents were reluctant to talk because they felt everything
they said would get back to Saranow, said Davis.
   The office in general was divided into the ``front office
favorites'' and the ``lunatic fringe,'' said Chuck McCalmont,
former group manager for the CID in Los Angeles.
   ``Agents were reluctant to report employee conduct violations to
the inspection service if it involved a manager or one of the front
office favorites,'' said McCalmont. ``The agents also felt if the
allegation involved a so-called lunatic fringe agent, inspection,
with the backing of our front office, went all out to prove the
allegation.''
   Though Saranow, who retired from the IRS without being charged
with misconduct, was interviewed by subcommittee investigators, he
was not scheduled to testify at the hearings which continue
Thursday.
   The investigators said Tuesday that Saranow would have exercised
his rights under the Fifth Amendment against self-incrimination if
he were called to the hearings.
   Ms. Jones remains in her position with internal security at the
Los Angeles office. She was not scheduled to testify. When The
Associated Press attempted to reach her by telephone at her office,
a public affairs spokeswoman for the IRS said she would call back
later.
   Also testifying Wednesday were three IRS auditors who said they
reported suspected misconduct by an inspection manager in Chicago
and found it detrimental to their careers.
   ``We were threatened, harassed and retaliated against by top
inspection executives,'' said George Ecola.
   The witnesses said the manager they blew the whistle on was
eventually suspended for 12 days for accepting illegal gratuities,
though his friends in the agency took up a collection to make up
for his lost salary. He has since resigned from the IRS.
   They said the complaint, however, caused one whistle-blower to
be removed from management, another demoted and the third
threatened with a downgrade.
</TEXT>
