<SECOND>AM-Obit-Biastre,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former von Bulow Butler Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Louis Biastre, the former butler to
Martha ``Sunny'' von Bulow who testified in the attempted murder
trial of Claus von Bulow, died of an apparent heart attack. He was
63.
   Frances Ann Biastre, a sister-in-law, said Tuesday she
discovered Biastre, who was taking heart medication, on the floor
near the kitchen sink, holding nitroglycerin pills in his hand.
   He was pronounced dead at the scene by Fire Department rescue
workers.
   Biastre retired in November after Clarendon Court, the von
Bulows' 8.3-acre estate in Newport, was sold to Glen and Patricia
Randall of Washington for $4.2 million.
   Biastre testified during von Bulow's first trial in 1982 that
Mrs. von Bulow was not a heavy drinker, discrediting the defense's
claim that she induced her own coma by drinking and taking drugs.
But he also said Claus von Bulow ordered all sweets from the house
because of his wife's hypoglycemia, or low sugar count.
   Mrs. von Bulow, 57, has been in a coma at Columbia Presbyterian
Hospital in New York for nine years. Claus von Bulow was convicted
of attempted murder in his first trial, but that conviction was
overturned and he was acquitted at the retrial.
   A lifelong resident of Newport, Biastre worked for the von
Bulows from 1973 to 1988.
   Claus von Bulow, 62, agreed in 1987 to divorce his wife and
relinquish all claims to her money in an out-of-court settlement of
a lawsuit filed by two of Mrs. von Bulow's three children.
   Biastre is survived by a brother, Albert A. Biastre, and several
nieces and nephews.
