<DOCNO> AP890726-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Fires     07-26 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Fires,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Forest Fires in Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered rain and cooler temperatures
helped bring some fires under control in central Canada on
Wednesday, but 27,000 people were kept from their homes in three
provinces.
   The rain also brought more lightning strikes and new blazes in
far northwestern regions.
   The fires, the region's worst in memory, have driven people from
remote communities in northern Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Ontario
and destroyed 3.7 million acres of forest. No injuries or deaths
have been reported.
   Cooler weather and light rain Wednesday followed temperatures in
the 90s, providing relief for crews and clearing the air of choking
smoke.
   ``The cooler temperatures seem to hold the fires closer to the
ground,'' said Bob Johnston of the Manitoba Natural Resources
Department. ``If we had another three or four days like this we'd
be looking pretty good, I think the panic would be over, but the
forecast is not for that.''
   Instead, warmer, dry weather was expected to return to the
province.
   The fires began several weeks ago and became a serious problem
last week. At last count, about 225 fires were burning in Manitoba,
150 in northern Ontario and about 165 in Saskatchewan. Most have
been caused by lightning.
   In all three provinces about 4.2 million acres of forest have
been destroyed this year, and 3 million acres in Manitoba alone.
   Manitoba Premier Gary Filmon has said the firefighting and
evacuation will cost the local government $30 million.
   The provincial government has declared a state of emergency.
   In Ottawa on Tuesday, Prime Minister Brian Mulroney promised
``every conceivable support'' from the federal government.
   On Wednesday, stranded vacationers and businessmen were driven
south accompanied by Royal Canadian Mounted Police escorts, but
local residents were forced to wait out the blazes in makeshift
dormitories.
   ``We want to be sure that when it is time to go home, it is time
to go home to stay,'' said Mark Tessier, an official of the
Emergency Measures Organization in Thompson.
   The population of the northern mining city has jumped from
15,000 to about 20,000 in the past week as evacuees streamed in
from outlying communities.
   Rainfall in the provinces varied. One region received up to 1.6
inches, while in others it merely drizzled or didn't rain at all.
   In many cases, a north wind helping to blow fires back over
burned out ground instead of pushing them over fresh timber.
   But the bad weather, which in some cases included lightning,
grounded exhausted pilots, who had been flying 12 water bombers
over affected areas on an almost non-stop basis. A few of the more
than 50 helicopters remained in the air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Khashoggi 1stLd-Writethru a0701 07-26 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khashoggi, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Judge Bars His Release On Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 11th, ``No one ..., to add details from
financial summary.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabian financier Adnan Khashoggi's
efforts to get out of jail and back to the style to which he is
accustomed were halted Wednesday when a federal appeals judge put a
stay on his release.
   A lower court had granted Khashoggi a $10 million bail package
Tuesday, his 54th birthday, but prosecutors appealed before he
could post bond.
   Khashoggi, who had been a fugitive until his arrest in
Switzerland on April 18, is charged with helping Ferdinand and
Imelda Marcos in the alleged plunder of the Philippines government
treasury. He has been in jail in New York since his July 19
extradition.
   Judge Lawrence W. Pierce of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals granted the stay pending a ruling on a prosecution appeal
of the bail package. He did not indicate when the ruling might be
made.
   The government's appeal cited Khashoggi's ``unverifiable''
wealth as a reason not to grant bail. Assistant U.S. Attorney
Charles LaBella attached to the appeal a 19-page summary of
Khashoggi's assets that Khashoggi presented to the court last week.
   Khashoggi, once one of the world's wealthiest men, valued his
assets at $141.8 million but said he had $88 million in
liabilities, bringing his estimated net worth to $53.85 million.
   He is said to have been the main financier and middleman of the
Iran-Contra affair, in which proceeds of illegal U.S. arms sales to
Iran went to rebels fighting the Nicaraguan government.
   Calls to Khashoggi's lawyer, Robert Morvillo, were not returned.
Morvillo said Tuesday evening he had raised enough money to meet
the bail.
   Khashoggi had been expected to move to an apartment he owns in
the luxury Olympic Tower building on Fifth Avenue.
   LaBella said Khashoggi should be required to give a detailed
financial disclosure under oath before bail is even considered.
   ``No one can say with certainty what Khashoggi's net worth is _
something that Khashoggi continues to conceal,'' he said.
   Khashoggi's financial summary named 73 companies based in a host
of countries, including Panama, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia,
Lichtenstein, Switzerland, the Cayman Islands, Hong Kong and the
Netherlands _ but it said only 12 were active. The others were
described as dormant, in liquidation or bankruptcy.
   In addition to the New York apartment, it listed a home in Saudi
Arabia and an estate at Malaga, Spain.
   His personal and business debts included an $81,000 credit card
bill and $378,033 in lawyers fees.
   Khashoggi said he had $643,746 in bank accounts in Switzerland,
France, Monte Carlo, Singapore and Canada _ but said the balance in
the Monte Carlo account was only 47 cents.
   A federal grand jury in New York indicted Khashoggi, the
Marcoses, five other people and the California Overseas Bank in Los
Angeles last October. The ousted president and his wife were
charged with stealing more than $100 million from the Philippine
treasury to buy real estate and art in New York.
   Khashoggi, who allegedly posed as the owner of some of the
assets as a cover, was indicted on charges of racketeering,
conspiracy, mail fraud and obstruction of justice. However, the
Swiss government extradited him on the last two charges only.
   He faces up to five years in jail and a $250,000 fine on each of
the two charges of mail fraud and obstruction of justice.
   Trial of Khashoggi and his co-defendants is scheduled for early
next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
