<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0732,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Promising End to Impasse over Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `A former...' to CORRECT that Tremblay sought
the injunction. ADDS two grafs at end with details on decision.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Quebec provincial appeals court Wednesday
upheld an injunction that prevents a 21-year-old woman from having
an abortion, and her attorney said she would appeal to the Supreme
Court.
   The ruling was the latest in a series of legal decisions that
has riveted attention on the issue and increased pressure on the
government for an abortion law.
   The Canadian Broadcasting Corp. interrupted its programming with
the announcement that the Quebec Court of Appeals voted 3-2 to
uphold the injunction barring Chantal Daigle from having an
abortion.
   A former boyfriend, Jean-Guy Tremblay, had sought the
injunction. ``We've won,'' Tremblay told reporters at the Montreal
courthouse where the decision was announced.
   The lawyer for Ms. Daigle, a secretary who is in her 21st week
of pregnancy, said she would appeal to the federal Supreme Court.
``Our client doesn't have seven months to wait,'' lawyer Daniel
Bedard said.
   Defying the Quebec appeals court by seeking an abortion in the
United States could bring a two-year prison sentence and a $42,000
fine.
   Canada has been without an abortion law since January 1988, when
the nation's Supreme Court said the cumbersome procedure required
for approval infringed on women's rights. That ruling and a
decision in a second case last January decriminalized abortion and
said the issue was for a woman and her doctor to decide.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney has said legislation will be
introduced this fall when Parliament returns from summer recess.
   ``The government will be responding in what I hope will be an
appropriate way,'' he said recently. ``There are events that have
brought it to the front burner more than has been the case. But I
think nobody would want us to be stampeded by this.''
   Three provincial court decisions issued this month have resulted
in public pressure for a law.
   An Ontario Supreme Court decision threw out an injunction
preventing Barbara Dodd, 22, from having an abortion, and she went
ahead with the procedure immediately.
   But last week Ms. Dodd appeared publicly with Greg Murphy, 23,
who had sought the injunction claiming a father's right, and
criticized abortion rights groups for encouraging her.
   Pro-choice activists who helped advise Ms. Dodd before her
abortion deny that she was encouraged to go ahead against her will.
   In Manitoba, a woman went ahead with an abortion after her
former boyfriend failed to obtain an injunction.
   The Quebec decision involving Ms. Daigle was based on the
province's Charter of Rights.
   ``The child that has been conceived but not born is a reality
that must be taken into account. He is not an inanimate object nor
the property of anyone, but a living human entity distinct from the
mother ... and has the right to life and protection from those who
conceived him,'' wrote Justice Yves Bernier, one of the three who
voted to reject Ms. Daigle's appeal.
   ``Pregnancy is not in itself an attack on a woman's physical
well-being or an interference in her body but a function which is a
fundamental part of her nature. The rule of nature is that
pregnancy must lead to birth,'' Bernier wrote.
   In one of the two dissenting opinions, Justice Christine
Tourigny, the only woman on the panel, said the Quebec Superior
Court erred in upholding the injunction because ``the general
provisions of Quebec law cannot be interpreted as restricting or
forbidding rights guaranteed by the Canadian Constitution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0188 </DOCNO>
