<FIRST>u a AM-TaxRevolt Bjt   07-26 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Revolt, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skyrocketing Tax Bills Spur Revolt Among Homeowners</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Property tax bills 50 to 200 percent higher than
last year's have provoked an angry outcry that on Wednesday sparked
a petition drive to overhaul the Cook County tax system.
   The petition launched by Patrick Quinn of the Coalition for
Political Honesty seeks a property tax reduction and a limit on the
amount taxes can be increased.
   ``I think people have had it up to here with a system that needs
reform,'' said Quinn. ``It's a soak-the-average-person system and
it's not fair.''
   If the group collects 155,000 signatures, a non-binding
referendum will be placed on Chicago's March 20 primary election
ballot. An additional 130,000 signatures would place it on the Cook
County ballot.
   ``If they raise it any more, I don't know what I'm gonna do,''
said Michael Galgano, a 74-year-old former construction worker who
owns his Northwest Side home. ``I don't have much left in my
savings.''
   Galgano, one of the first to sign the petition, said his bill
was less than $1,000 three years ago, $1,300 two years ago, and is
about $2,000 this year.
   On Monday, 350 angry protesters stormed one alderman's office
demanding property-tax relief.
   ``We're the ones who are most in danger of losing our homes,''
said protester Frank Greco, 72, who lives on a fixed income in a
hard-hit ward. ``We want to send the message that unless they roll
back taxes, people are going to fight forever.''
   The county must share property tax revenues with the school
board, city colleges, streets and sanitation, etc., but it has
demanded an increased share for this year. And county board
president George Dunne has said he needs another increase to expand
crowded jails and hospitals next year.
   The petition calls for a reduction of at least 5 percent in the
1990 property tax levy, a $1,000 homestead exemption and a ceiling
on taxes of no more than 2 percent of the home's market value.
Quinn said some are now paying up to almost 3 percent of their
home's assessed value.
   That percentage of assessed value varies among the county's 108
taxing districts. Officials said the county's share of that is
1.128 per cent of assessed value, up from 0.913 in 1987.
   The plan is based on measures approved by voters in California,
Massachusetts, Missouri and Michigan, Quinn said.
   ``Benjamin Franklin said death and taxes are inevitable, but he
didn't say it's inevitable to be taxed to death,'' said Quinn, a
former member of the county Board of Tax Appeals.
   Quinn contends county tax collecting is based on a 19th century
system that is unfair, confusing and not based on ability to pay.
   He blamed Dunne, saying the county government is inefficient and
padded with patronage jobs.
   Dunne said his hands are tied by an antiquated system he would
like to see reformed. He said he spends 76 cents of every dollar
for a criminal-justice system that demands more every year.
   ``I won't make a promise of reducing something unless I can see
where that can be done, and I don't see it right now,'' Dunne said.
   Jean Lee said her taxes had doubled since the last time she was
billed.
   ``I worked really hard to get the home we have, and now I've got
to give it up'' if rates keep rising, said Ms. Lee, 58, who lives
with her retired husband on the South Side and was among the first
to sign the petition.
   In 1988, Illinoisans paid $7.4 billion in property taxes, equal
to the amounts generated by state income and sales taxes, said
Douglas Whitley, president of the Taxpayers Federation of Illinois.
   ``The problem is the system itself,'' Whitley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
