<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Buffalo     07-26 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Buffalo,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say HUD Has Been Reimbursed $72,970</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development has been reimbursed $72,970 owed by the widow and
estate of a one-time broker for the agency's Buffalo, N.Y., office,
officials said Wednesday.
   The department last week collected a check for $24,831 from the
estate of Bernard S. Brady and another for $48,139 from
Manufacturer's and Trader's Trust where Brady had maintained a HUD
escrow account, the Buffalo HUD office said in a release.
   ``Case closed,'' said Joseph Lynch, manager of the Buffalo
office. ``Thanks to the cooperation of Mrs. Brady, Harold Fein (her
lawyer) and Robert Wilmers at M&amp;T, we have recouped HUD monies and
restored Bernie Brady's reputation.''
   The reimbursements came less than a month after The Associated
Press obtained an internal HUD audit which showed Brady had
withheld payments, overbilled HUD and paid himself advances while a
real estate broker and appraiser for the department.
   When Brady died of cancer in 1987, his widow, Maureen, wrote
$20,100 worth of checks on the account, which was in her husband's
name, according to the audit, obtained under the Freedom of
Information Act.
   From 1983 until his death, Brady had been under contract to act
as management broker and closing agent when HUD sold foreclosed
single-family houses _ 70 to 80 a year in Erie County, according to
the Buffalo office. Brady was supposed to forward money and
documents to HUD within 48 hours but his reports were frequently
delinquent, according to the release.
   Discrepancies in the escrow account were reported to HUD in
October 1987 by Fein, attorney for the estate, and Lynch
immediately requested an investigation. But the audit was not
completed until Jan. 19, 1989, which HUD attributed to ``delays
encountered by the competing priorities.''
   When contacted by the AP last month, Lynch and A. Paul Kane,
HUD's regional inspector general for audit, said HUD was still
having trouble collecting the money.
   Brady was one of many closing agents who apparently took
advantage of lax controls at HUD under Secretary Samuel Pierce. The
new secretary, Jack Kemp, has been tightening controls in the wake
of reports that some agents took millions of dollars for their own
use.
   But Lynch said he did not believe Brady had any criminal intent.
   ``He may have kept lousy records but I am convinced Brady was an
honest man,'' Lynch said.
</TEXT>
