<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GE-IowaCrash     07-26 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE-Iowa Crash,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Probing Engine Records at GE Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators Wednesday began
examining records at the General Electric Co. plant that made the
engines for United Flight 232, while GE awaited the arrival of the
jet's shattered tail engine.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigator Jack Young is
studying GE's manufacturing and maintenance records for the tail
engine. Its fan section apparently disintegrated about 45 minutes
into the July 19 flight from Denver to Chicago. The DC-10 crashed
at Sioux City, Iowa, killing 111 people.
   ``The engine was assembled back in 1972, so there are many
records to review,'' said Dwight Weber, spokesman at the plant in
suburban Cincinnati.
   The remains of the tail-mounted No. 2 engine are to be shipped
next week from the crash site to the Evendale plant for dismantling
and inspection under federal supervision, Weber said.
   The plant, which produces engines for commercial and military
jets, has the facilities for such an inspection, while Sioux City
does not, he said.
   ``It will be inspected thoroughly and, I'm sure, torn down and
inspected piece by piece,'' Weber said.
   Weber said he did not know when the engine would arrive, what
its condition is or how long the NTSB would need to complete the
inspection. NTSB's Washington office did not return a telephone
call Wednesday.
   The CF6-6 engine was tailor-made for DC-10 series 10 jets,
including the one that crashed last week. Weber said GE produced
the engine from 1971 to 1981, when McDonnell Douglas sold the last
DC-10 series 10 jets. GE now makes a successor engine _ the
CF6-80C2 _ for wide-body jets.
   The CF6-6 engine established a record of reliability during 17
million flight hours in commercial service, Weber said.
   In Boston, FAA spokeswoman Gail Lattrell said FAA records showed
that the CF6-6 has been involved in 14 accidents or incidents. The
FAA defines an accident as one that causes injury or at least
substantial damage to an engine. An incident involves lesser damage
to an engine, Ms. Lattrell said.
   She said she had no details of the 14 occurrences.
   Weber said the CF6-6 had never been involved in a major accident
before the Iowa crash. The FAA's Aeronautical Center in Oklahoma
City reported no record of any service problems with the No. 2
engine on United's Flight 232.
   Those accompanying Young to GE-Evendale included representatives
of the Federal Aviation Administration, GE, United Airlines,
McDonnell Douglas and the Airline Pilots Association and
International Association of Machinists unions, the NTSB said. The
group is one of eight teams set up by the NTSB to investigate
various aspects of the crash.
</TEXT>
