<FIRST>r w AM-DrugTesting     07-26 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Parts of Drug Testing Program at Education Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday approved portions of
a drug-testing program at the Department of Education but blocked
random testing for 88 data processors at the agency.
   U.S. District Court Judge Joyce Green said that although the
government claims the data processors have access to sensitive
data, the department ``has not concretely identified the nature of
this information nor the safeguards that would prevent its improper
dissemination.''
   She approved random drug testing for 13 employees with access to
top secret information and gave the go-ahead for drug testing of
nine motor vehicle operators as well as a guard for the secretary
of education.
   In ruling on a lawsuit brought by the American Federation of
Government Employees, Green also approved testing when there is
reasonable suspicion that any employee is using drugs. She rejected
the labor union's request for a restriction that prior to such
testing, a supervisor must have individualized suspicion that an
employee is impaired while on duty.
