<HEAD>Casino Bus Overturns on Parkway; Dozens Injured, 10 Seriously ^Eds:
Inserts 2 grafs after the 6th, ``It appears ..., to add background on gambler
traffic, past accidents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLOWAY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus filled with gamblers bound
for Atlantic City overturned Wednesday on a highway, injuring
nearly 40 people, 10 of them seriously, officials said.
   Passersby stopped along the Garden State Parkway to help
passengers, many of them elderly, off the bus through emergency
exits. By the time state police arrived, two people remained on the
bus screaming for help.
   Twenty ambulances and paramedic units carried 38 people,
including the bus driver, to four hospitals, medical officials said.
   ``A majority of people have minor cuts and bruises and back
pains,'' said Dr. James Bagnell, director of emergency services for
Atlantic City Medical Center. He said most of the serious injuries
were broken bones.
   The driver, not immediately identified, complained of a
mechanical problem with the bus.
   ``It appears the brakes locked up and in an attempt to gain
control, she tipped the bus,'' said Trooper David Smith. Smith said
investigators were trying to determine how fast the bus was
traveling.
   Much of Atlantic City's casino business depends on buses that
arrive hourly, bringing gamblers for several hours or a day in the
casinos.
   On Nov. 29, a bus to Atlantic City carrying elderly people, most
from New York City, flipped onto its side, injuring 49 people. In
August, a bus taking gamblers home from Atlantic City struck a New
Jersey Transit bus, injuring 21 people.
   There were 14 people at the Atlantic City hospital, 10 at
Galloway Township, nine at Shore Memorial Hospital at Somers Point
and five William B. Kessler Memorial Hospital in Hammonton, Bagnell
said.
   Bagnell said he expected most of the injured to stay in the
hospital overnight. Officials at Shore Memorial said only five of
the nine people brought there would need to stay overnight.
   State police said the passengers boarded the Saddle River Tours
bus at Rutherford in northern New Jersey and were bound for Caesars
Atlantic City casino hotel.
   The accident caused a traffic backup of eight to 10 miles.
