<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     07-26 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Ambassador Says Plane Crash Should Not Hinder Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane crash that killed 42 people in
Angola should not stop the peace process there, even though the
government blamed the crash on a rebel missile, the Angolan
Ambassador was quoted as saying Wednesday.
   Earlier, the Portuguese news agency, Lusa, quoted an
unidentified military source in Luanda as saying the plane attack
and a recent increase in rebel activity, might force the government
to postpone peace talks, scheduled to resume Monday in Zaire.
   Rui Mingas, recently appointed ambassador to Lisbon, said in an
interview that the crash ``should not hinder the continuation of
negotiations'' with the rebels.
   An excerpt from his Tuesday interview with state television was
published Wednesday in the state-owned daily Diario de Noticias.
   A military official in Luanda, the Angolan capital, said the
Soviet-built plane, a twin-propeller Antonov 26, was forced to
crash-land in Angola on Sunday after being hit by a missile.
   He said the missile was fired by the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said rebels
were surrounding the crash site Wednesday and were shelling
government troops to prevent them collecting what he called
``irrefutable evidence'' that the plane was shot down by rebels
with a Stinger missile.
   In Washington, UNITA issued a statement denying its forces shot
down the plane. The group said it suspects a government faction
mounted the attack to undermine the peace talks by throwing the
blame on rebels.
   The statement said the rebels were still committed to reaching a
permanent settlement to the country's 14-year war.
   At a Jun. 22 African summit in Zaire, Angolan President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos and rebel leader Jonas Savimbi sealed a truce in
Angola's 14-year civil war with a historic handshake.
   Both sides have accused the other of violating the ensuing
cease-fire, which lasted only a week. According to a Lusa dispatch
Wednesday, UNITA attacks in the past week have left 115 soldiers
and civilians dead, 218 injured, and 31 missing.
   But both went back to the negotiating table anyway. The last
round of talks ended Saturday under the mediation of Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko.
   UNITA, with Western support, has been fighting to force the
Cuban-backed Angolan government to share power since shortly after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The rebels still receive between $15 million and $18 million in
U.S. military assistance a year. The aid is said to include stinger
missiles.
</TEXT>
