<FIRST>r a AM-Mary'sFirstRide     07-26 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mary's First Ride,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman, 106, Rides Plane for First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing shiny pilot's wings and praising airline
food, 106-year-old Mary Elam fulfilled a 20-year-old wish to ride
in an airplane Wednesday as she landed here amid a throng of
applauding travelers.
   Miss Elam was presented with a dozen roses as she disembarked
from a Delta Air Lines flight at Hartsfield Atlanta International
Airport. She was accompanied by her guardian, Charlotte King, and
Bill Edmiston, a nurse at the nursing home where Miss Elam lives in
Xenia, Ohio, southeast of Dayton.
   She arrived in Atlanta at mid-afternoon, and returned to Dayton
on another flight within a couple of hours.
   ``I'm all right,'' she told her guardian and traveling
companion, Charlotte King, upon leaving the plane.
   Passengers waiting to board their flights gathered around the
arrival gate to greet Miss Elam, who seemed startled by all the
attention.
   ``The least you could do is smile, Mary!'' said Edmiston.
   Miss Elam began her daylong adventure at Dayton International
Airport, where she boarded her flight and took a window seat. She
said the best part of her flight was ``when we got way up high.''
   ``I liked the flight. I liked all of it,'' she said. ``The food
was very good.''
   Was the ride everything she expected?
   ``Yes,'' Miss Elam said. ``And more.''
   Miss Elam said she wanted to fly because she ``just wanted to
try anything anyone else does.'' She said she wants to fly again
but hasn't decided where she wants to go.
   Miss Elam, a nurse during World War I, said the plane ride was
her first major trip since about 1910, when she traveled to
California by train for a world fair.
   Mrs. King, a friend of Miss Elam's for about 50 years, said the
elderly woman had been expressing a desire to fly for the past 20
years. ``She said, `I want to fly before I die,''' Mrs. King said.
   Miss Elam brought up the subject again one recent Sunday, ``so I
thought, `Well, why not?' And after getting her doctor's approval,
we proceeded,'' Mrs. King said.
   So Mrs. King's sister, Mary Anne Howe, arranged the one-day trip
through Delta, which is based in Atlanta. Mrs. King's son, Keith, a
painting contractor in Xenia, paid for the tickets and arranged for
a limousine to take Miss Elam to the airport in Dayton.
   Delta spokesman Mike Detrick said the airline arranged an
economy ticket for Miss Elam, but he said he did not know how much
it cost.
   Once in Atlanta, Miss Elam met another Mary Elam, a Delta Air
Lines employee. The two embraced briefly.
   ``I thought, `Someone with my name? 106 years old?''' said Ms.
Elam, 37. ``I want to know the secret of her success.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
