<FIRST>u w AM-Fauntroy-Probe 1stLd-Writethrua0743   07-26 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fauntroy-Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru a0743,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Issues Subpoenas in Probe of Fauntroy, Savage's Son</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS graf 6: ``Justice Department,'' with no comment from
Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has issued subpoenas to
several former employees of Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., as part of an
investigation into D.C. Del. Walter Fauntroy's employment of
Savage's son, sources familiar with the case said Wednesday.
   The Justice Department is investigating whether Thomas John
Savage, son of Rep. Savage, regularly reported for work while he
was on Fauntroy's payroll for most of the period between September
1987 and June 1988.
   The sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said
three of the people under subpoena worked in Savage's Chicago
office during that period. The three have indicated they frequently
saw the younger Savage in the office, the sources said.
   All of those who received subpoenas are scheduled to testify
before a grand jury in Washington during the next two weeks, said
the sources.
   The grand jury was convened in May, a month after the Justice
Department expanded an investigation to examine all of Fauntroy's
hiring practices over the past five years.
   Justice Department David Runkel said he could not comment on the
case.
   The younger Savage, who now works as an affirmative action
officer for the Chicago Metropolitan Sanitary District, was not in
his office Wednesday and could not be reached for comment.
   Rep. Savage did not return three phone calls to his Washington
office.
   Fauntroy spokeswoman Livonia Perriman-Fairfax said none of
Fauntroy's current employees has been subpoenaed.
   The subpoenas are the latest step in a probe that began last
December after The Associated Press reported that Thomas Savage was
frequently in Chicago while he was on Fauntroy's payroll.
   For part of the time in question, he was a candidate for the
Illinois Legislature, and also was on leave from Fauntroy's payroll.
   Fauntroy says Savage took an unpaid leave from his job for 10
weeks between Jan. 1 and March 15, 1988, to wage the campaign.
House payroll records obtained by the AP show Savage was paid
$1,459.50 in January 1988, an amount equal to nearly three weeks'
pay. In all, he earned $21,398 while on Fauntroy's payroll.
   Illinois election records show that Savage swore he had resided
continuously for two years in his Chicago home, including the
period he was on Fauntroy's payroll. The records also include
numerous affidavits the younger Savage filed in Chicago on behalf
of his father's 1988 reelection campaign.
   The younger Savage told the AP he was in Chicago ``for a couple
of weekends'' and during holidays during the period he was on
Fauntroy's payroll.
   Fauntroy says the younger Savage worked diligently on an effort
to gain statehood for the District of Columbia. The younger Savage
has said publicly that he did not regularly report to Fauntroy's
office and did little more than stuff envelopes when he was there.
</TEXT>
