<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan     07-26 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Ruler returns Home With Good News ^Eds: Incorporates AM-Egypt-Sudan,
a0696, on food shortages and starvation in southern Sudan.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's new military leader indicated
Wednesday that the 6-year-old civil war in the south would be
brought to an end soon.
   ``Some bright news will be heared in the upcoming few days'' Lt.
Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir told reporters at Khartoum airport,
according to the official Sudan News Agency. He returned from a
summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity in the
Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa.
   The civil war has partly been blamed for starvation in the
south, and a relief worker said that a village where 8,000 people
starved to death last summer faces a similar crisis this year
because of insufficient food stocks.
   El-Bashir said President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt had conferred at
the summit with John Garang, leader of the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army, and explained the ``orientations'' of el-Bashir's
regime.
   He said Mubarak asked Garang to ``cooperate'' with el-Bashir's
government to put an end to the civil war, which began in 1983 when
the rebels took up arms to demand greater regional autonomy and
economic and administrative reforms.
   Mubarak and el-Bashir also met in Khartoum on Sunday when the
Egyptian leader was on his way to the African organization's annual
meeting. Mubarak and other African leaders tried to arrange a
meeting between el-Bashir and Garang, but sources at the conference
said the rebel leader declined.
   Egypt has a historical interest in Sudan because the Nile river
runs through both countries on its way to the Mediterranean Sea.
   El-Bashir said putting an end to the civil war was among his top
motives in launching his June 30 military coup that toppled the
civilian regime of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi.
   A Western relief worker said donors were studying possibilities
for sending more food to Abyei, a village 500 miles southwest of
Khartoum.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
United Nations estimates that 250,000 people died as a result of
starvation and civil war in southern Sudan in 1988. The world body
says 100,000 more could die this year unless its huge relief
operation to send 105,000 tons of food into the south succeeds.
   About 70,000 tons of supplies will have been moved by the end of
July, relief officials say.
   The Western official said Abyei received 3,000 tons of food,
normally enough to get 26,000 inhabitants and refugees through the
rainy season, from June to November. During that time, heavy rains
isolate many areas.
   However, the official said in the past few weeks up to 20,000
more refugees have arrived in Abyei, and ``the food is no longer
enough to last them through the rainy season.''
   The official also said many refugees were streaming in daily to
nearby Aweil, where 4,000 other people starved last year. However,
he had no details on food supplies there.
   Sudan's civil war started in 1983. Christians and animists are
fighting for more autonomy from the Arab Moslem majority government
in the north. The rebels claim to control up to 95 percent of the
southern countryside.
   The fighting has forced up to 2 million southerners to flee
their homes and livelihoods, making them dependent on relief food.
About 23 million people live in all of Sudan.
</TEXT>
