<FIRST>r w AM-SpaceJob     07-26 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Job,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aaron Cohen Of Johnson Space Center Named To Moon-Mars Study Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aaron Cohen, director of the Johnson Space
Center in Houston, will lead the participation by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration in a study of the national
goal of exploring the moon and the planet Mars, the space agency
announced Wednesday.
   Richard H. Truly, NASA administrator, said Cohen will be
assigned temporarily to NASA headquarters for the next few months.
   Truly said the assignment is in response to President Bush's
speech last Thursday on the 20th anniversary of the Apollo 11 moon
landing. In that speech, Bush asked the National Space Council to
determine what is needed to establish an outpost on the moon and
later to conduct a manned exploration of Mars.
   Cohen will be direct NASA's participation in preparing those
recommendations, Truly said.
   While Cohen is assigned to Washington, Truly said deputy
director Paul Weitz, a former astronaut, will be in charge of the
Johnson Space Center.
