<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     07-26 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Begin Deliberations In Long-Running Night Stalker Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors began deliberations Wednesday in the
``Night Stalker'' serial murder case, weighing whether a lanky
drifter from Texas committed 13 slayings that terrorized California
four summers ago.
   Richard Ramirez, 29, faces 43 separate verdicts, including 30
non-murder felonies, and he could be sentenced to death if
convicted. The same jury will consider a penalty recommendation for
the El Paso, Texas, native.
   The 12-member panel heard testimony in the courtroom of Superior
Court Judge Michael Tynan from Jan. 30 to July 10, following six
months of jury selection for the highly publicized case.
   Witnesses testified that one victim's eyes were gouged out. A
survivor identified Ramirez as her attacker and said she was raped
and sodomized after her husband was murdered. She alleged that
Ramirez told her during the attack to ``swear to Satan.''
   There also was testimony of inverted pentagrams left at some of
the murder scenes and of Ramirez's own claims during the trial and
preliminary hearing that he was indeed the Night Stalker.
   Defense attorney attorney Ray Clark called his client's
statements jailhouse bravado.
   Courtroom arguments covered more than 8,000 pages of transcript,
some of it concerning arguments over the demeanor of one of
Ramirez's attorneys, Daniel P. Hernandez of San Jose.
   Most recently, Hernandez disappeared from the court for an
afternoon session. He later said he simply failed to tell Clark of
his plans.
   During the trial, the prosecution called 138 witnesses while the
defense called 38 people. There were 654 exhibits admitted into
evidence _ 574 for the prosecution, 80 for the defense.
   When jurors reach verdicts, they will have 106 verdict forms to
fill out, including those asking about findings of facts that could
enhance penalties for the non-murder charges and bring a death
penalty for the slayings.
   Clark told jurors there was enough reasonable doubt raised in
the case to keep them from convicting Ramirez.
   Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin reminded the panel of
the similarity of the crimes and the several surviving victims who
identified Ramirez as the man who entered their homes through
unlocked doors and windows during hot summer nights in 1985.
</TEXT>
