<FIRST>r w AM-MoneyLaundering     07-26 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Laundering,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Bank Officer Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former bank officer pleaded guilty Wednesday
in federal court to conspiring with ex-Illinois congressman Robert
Hanrahan to violate currency reporting requirements in a
money-laundering operation.
   Roger C. Schultz, who was a senior vice president at the
National Bank of Washington, entered the plea to a charge of
conspiring to defraud the Internal Revenue Service by helping
Hanrahan and another man evade the requirement of reporting
currency transactions of more than $10,000.
   Hanrahan pleaded guilty previously in the matter and is awaiting
sentencing.
   A central figure in the case was Charles LeChasney, a political
consultant who testified as a government witness in last month's
criminal trial of former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga.
   Schultz advised LeChasney and Hanrahan in 1987 about the bank's
capability of detecting related accounts, according to a criminal
information filed by the U.S. attorney's office. LeChasney and
Hanrahan used Schultz's advice by setting up three corporate
accounts in such a way as to avoid the bank's detection ability.
   LeChasney and Hanrahan then laundered $300,000 in cash supplied
to them by an undercover IRS agent posing as a representative of a
criminal organization and LeChasney and Hanrahan received more than
$10,000 in commissions for their efforts, according to a statement
issued by the U.S. attorney's office.
   Schultz faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
when he is sentenced Sept. 20. He entered the plea before U.S.
District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
   LeChasney, an admitted con man convicted of money laundering,
was a government witness last month against Swindall, who was
convicted of 10 counts of lying to a federal grand jury about his
1987 dealings with LeChasney.
   The lies concerned an $850,000 loan deal from LeChasney's Gulf
Coast Mortgage Corp.
   Swindall lost his congressional seat last November.
</TEXT>
