<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PublicCorruption     07-26 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Corruption,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorneys Convicted 1,067 Public Officials in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. attorneys won corruption convictions
against 1,067 public officials in 1988, and prosecutors in Chicago
had the best record with 119, the Justice Department said Wednesday.
   ``These totals reflect nearly a three-fold increase in the
average number of corruption convictions obtained annually by
federal prosectors over the course of the past decade,'' Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh said.
   They ``demonstrate how dramatic results can be obtained when a
strong emphasis is placed on rooting out corruption,'' he said.
   Federal prosecutors got convictions against 529 federal
officials, 69 state officials, 229 local officials and 240 private
citizens tied to public corruption, Thornburgh said in a report to
Congress.
   The U.S. attorney's office in Chicago had 119 convictions in
1988, followed by 89 in the Eastern District of New York, covering
the Brooklyn, Queens and Staten Island boroughs of New York City
and the suburban counties on Long Island, 49 in Massachusetts and
48 in the Eastern District of Pennsylvania.
   The Chicago prosecutors put away aldermen, judges, attorneys and
court officers who took and paid bribes for favors. One
investigation, dubbed Operation Deadfall, snagged corrupt police
officers who accepted money to steer bodies to certain funeral
homes.
   ``There are those who believe that taking bribes is a
gratuity,'' said Anton Valukas, the government's top prosecutor in
Chicago. ``That attitude is amazing. Those who are there are
supposed to be assisting citizens, not looting.''
   Since 1978, the U.S. attorney's office for the Southern District
of New York, covering the New York City boroughs of Manhattan and
The Bronx and suburban counties north of the city, has the most
convictions involving public officials, 477. Chicago is second at
412.
</TEXT>
