<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CelebritiesWarned     07-26 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Celebrities Warned,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Denies Inmate Made Threats to Stars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate at a mental health center who allegedly
wrote threatening letters to Olivia Newton-John and dozens of other
celebrities could be ordered released at a court hearing next
month, his attorney said.
   The possible release of Ralph Nau was enough to prompt a
prosecutor who handled his murder trial to write warning letters to
40 prominent women with whom Nau has allegedly had imagined
relationships.
   Prominent among Nau's infatuations is actress-singer Olivia
Newton-John, said Randall Stewart, an assistant Lake County state's
attorney. The prosecutor said Nau twice traveled to Australia in
pursuit of Miss Newton-John.
   Attorneys at a hearing Wednesday worked out details on what
evidence can be presented in Kane County Circuit Court in August on
Nau's petition for release from Elgin Mental Health Center.
   Lake County public defender David Brodsky, who represented Nau
at his murder trial, said the hearing could determine whether Nau
is released from the mental health center.
   Nau was acquitted in May of murdering his 8-year-old stepbrother
after the judge refused to allow a purported confession into
evidence. Nau lived in Antioch, where the boy's body was found.
   Stewart said Nau confessed to killing his stepbrother in 1984
and that he wrote hundreds of letters, many of which are clearly
threatening.
   Stewart said Nau believes that Miss Newton-John was killed by an
evil double, and he has threatened to avenge this imagined crime by
killing the supposed impersonator.
   The prosecutor refused to release the names of other celebrities
he had warned, saying they had requested anonymity.
   Stewart said he wrote in his 40 warning letters that ``we
strongly feel he could be a potential threat to you and your
family's safety upon his release.''
   Celebrities have been occasionally threatened by infatuated
fans. Last week, actress Rebecca Schaeffer was shot dead at the
door to her Los Angeles apartment building, allegedly by a man said
to be obsessed with her.
   Brodsky said that although Nau is mentally disturbed, he never
admitted killing anybody and never threatened the life of any stars.
   ``He's written love letters and fan letters, maybe some people
think excessively,'' said Brodsky, who represented Nau in the
murder trial.
   ``He had delusions of grandeur and believed he was famous, but
never threatened anybody,'' Brodsky said.
   The purported confession, he said, was put in his mouth by
police officers during 12 hours of questioning.
   Prosecutors had Nau committed involuntarily to the Elgin Mental
Health Center for a psychiatric evaluation after his murder trial.
   The center is located in Kane County, where his petition for
release is being heard.
   Brodsky declined to speculate on whether Nau would be a threat
to anyone if he is released.
   ``That's impossible to say,'' he said, but added, ``Ralph
deserves to have his rights adjudicated in as fair a manner as
anybody.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
