<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Crime     07-26 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Crime,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killers to Stay In Jail Until They Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted murderers sentenced to life
imprisonment in New South Wales will stay in jail until they die,
the state government decided Wednesday.
   ``The community has become cynical about life sentences,'' said
state Premier Nick Greiner. ``The public, and relatives of victims
in particular, are entitled to know that when people are sentenced
to life for murder, they will spend the rest of their natural life
in prison.''
   Greiner said the new law will not be retroactive and those
currently serving life terms will still be eligible for parole,
which is usually granted after 12 years.
   The legislation drew criticism from the Council for Civil
Liberties, which accused the state government of ``pandering to
vindictive elements.''
   Civil Liberties President Ken Horler said the new law offered
little chance of rehabilitation of inmates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
