<FIRST>r a AM-FarmAccident     07-26 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Accident,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Die of Exposure to Fumes in Manure Pit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENOMINEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dairy farm worker was overcome by
methane fumes and died Wednesday when he slipped into a manure pit
and four others died trying to rescue him, authorities said.
   ``It appeared they were cleaning it and the first victim just
happened to slip,'' said Dr. Paul Haupt, county medical
examiner.``One man accidentally slipped down the inclined plane; a
second went down in and was overcome also. Then another went down
to get the other two, and so on and so on.''
   One man was dead when deputies arrived at the Elm Brook Farm in
Menominee Township in Michigan's Upper Peninsula, said Menominee
County Sheriff Deputy Gary Corwin.
   Three others died later Wednesday morning at Bay Area Medical
Center in Marinette, Wis., and the fifth was pronounced dead at
3:20 p.m. at Children's Hospital of Wisconsin in Wauwatosa, Wis.,
he said. Menominee is near he Wisconsin-Michigan line.
   The names of the victims, ages 18 to 60, were not released while
relatives were notified.
   Methane is a colorless, odorless gas formed by the decomposition
of vegetable matter.
   The accident occurred in a 6-foot-high unventilated tank with
about 1 foot of manure in the bottom, said Haupt.
</TEXT>
