<FIRST>u a AM-ToxicSite 1stLd-Writethru a0685 07-26 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Site, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0685,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents of Contaminated Trailer Park Await Details of Relocation
Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details from meeting. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `Residents choosing ...; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a trailer park that the
Environmental Protection Agency says is contaminated with toxic
chemicals expressed outrage Wednesday at talk of a temporary
relocation program.
   ``They're not relocating me,'' said John Morreale, one of the
150 residents of the Forest Glen mobile home park. ``They've got to
buy me out, give me a reasonable price for my property.''
   More than 90 residents showed up at a meeting with federal
officials at a fire station Wednesday night to voice similar
sentiments.
   ``Why can't you declare an emergency like they did in Love Canal
and move us out immediately?'' Robert Barclay asked at the meeting.
   Barclay and others said the amount of monetary assistance the
government was offering was not enough.
   ``My wife and I can't afford it. We're on social security,''
Barclay said.
   Robert Salkie, an EPA official, said the government would rush
the site onto a Superfund priority list and that the families would
be permanently relocated perhaps in as few as two months.
   But residents said that was too long. Terry Friermuth said,
``It's too long to wait. It's too much of a disruption for the
family. You don't realize what you're putting us through.''
   The federal Emergency Management Agency began contacting Forest
Glen residents Tuesday to advise them of the findings and canvass
them about whether they wish to stay or relocate.
   Residents choosing to move temporarily will be provided with
three months' rent by the agency, Gerald Connolly, a senior
Emergency Management representative, said before the meeting.
   The agency will also provide food and utility stipends for
relocating residents and in some cases pay for rental insurance and
the cost of kenneling pets, Connolly said. Paying mortgages on
homes in the Forest Glen neighborhood will remain the
responsibility of the owners, he said.
   The EPA said Tuesday that the discovery of five industrial
chemicals in the soil and groundwater beneath the trailer park's 11
acres posed a significant risk to the health of the 51 families
that live in the neighborhood.
   Authorities think the ground on which the mobile home park was
built may have been used as a chemical dumping ground. The site is
near a hazardous waste landfill and a few miles from Love Canal,
which was declared a national environmental disaster a decade ago
because of extensive chemical contamination.
   A spot check of the residents showed that most were opposed to
temporary removal but would accept permanent relocation if the
government would help pay for it.
   Officials said it is too early to discuss plans for a buyout,
however. They have recommended that the evacuation remain in effect
until the health risk is ``eliminated or substantially mitigated.''
   The contamination may be bad enough to force the eventual
abandonment of the entire neighborhood, said the EPA's Richard
Salkie.
   ``We are talking about temporary relocation, but it seems to me
that the long-range answer is permanent relocation,'' he said.
   Salkie said the federal Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease
Registry has agreed to issue a public health advisory, which is a
first step toward placing the community on the national Superfund
priorities list for cleanup and permanently relocating residents.
   The EPA's enforcement division, meanwhile, is investigating who
may have dumped the chemicals in the area, he said.
   Among the chemicals identified so far are aniline,
phenothiazine, benzothiazole and polyaromatic hydrocarbons,
substances officials said are byproducts of industrial processes,
including chemical making.
   Despite health risk from exposure to the chemicals, which are
believed carcinogenic, no illnesses in the mobile home park have
been traced to contamination, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
