<FIRST>u i AM-Guatemala     07-26 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Picket, Mail Piles Up as Strike Drags on</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mail piled up and teachers blocked the
streets of the capital on Wednesday, and President Vinicio Cerezo
said he was losing patience with a weeks-old strike by an estimated
50,000 public employees.
   Cerezo reiterated his opposition to giving the strikers, most of
them teachers and postal workers, a raise this year. He told a news
conference the government does not have the money.
   He also said strikers would not get their July paychecks.
   The walkout has been marked by a series of marches and other
demonstrations, including almost daily traffic blockages.
   On Wednesday, strikers blocked most of the main roads into
Guatemala City, and authorities also reported blockages in the
north at border crossings into Mexico.
   Meanwhile, emergency workers sorted air mail and domestic mail
piled up in warehouses.
   The strike has hurt many Guatemalans who rely on money sent by
relatives working in the United States and other countries.
   The U.S. Postal Service this week declared an embargo on mail to
Guatemala because of the strike. Officials in Washington said
Tuesday that the Guatemala postal administration requested the
embargo.
   The strike began May 31 with a slowdown by teachers. By early
June, the nation's 36,000 teachers had walked out, and by mid-June
the 5,000 postal workers had joined in.
   Several smaller groups of government employees have joined the
walkout, which now involves an estimated 50,000 of the government's
200,000 employees.
   Telegraph workers, who struck with postal workers, went back to
work earlier this week after the Communications Ministry agreed to
negotiate a raise next year.
   Cerezo has maintained from the outset that the government cannot
afford a raise and urged workers to wait until next year. He met
personally with the teachers for the first time on Tuesday.
   The strikers want a monthly raise of $80. Teachers and postal
workers now earn from about $125 to $250 per month.
   In a nationwide television address July 19, Cerezo told the
strikers they were being manipulated by the extreme right and the
extreme left and said their demands were unjust. As the speech
began, the transmitting tower of one television station was knocked
off the air by a bomb.
</TEXT>
