<DOCNO> AP890726-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv27   07-26 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 27 ,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, July 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thinking Short-Term In The American Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Bsiness Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most common criticisms of American
business may also be made of the American family. Both seem to
think short-term, even at the expense of the future.
   This, of course, is a generality with many exceptions. Lots of
companies foresake instant profits in order to fund research that
won't pay off for years. Many families forego today's pleasures for
tomorrow's security.
   Still, a study by a financial planning group reveals a strong
tendency among Americans to dismiss potential problems from their
minds, often because they are forced to by more immediate, pressing
challenges.
   According to a report of the findings:
   _Despite listing saving for retirement as their most important
long-term financial goal, most people do little about it. ``While
concern is high, short-term worries about the mortgage and paying
for college have taken precedence.''
   _The number two financial goal for most Americans is putting
children through college, ``but most have no idea what it will
cost, and harbor unrealistic expectations about how they will pay
for it.''
   _More than one-third of Americans say someone in the family will
need long-term medical care, ``but virtually none have any plans to
pay for it, nor do they seem disposed to plan.''
   Fairly or unfairly, a rap against surveys is that they tend to
generate more suspicion than conviction, especially when results
uncannily coincide with goals of those who conduct or contract for
them. This one may be no exception.
   Conducted by the Gallup Organization for the International
Association for Financial Planning in Atlanta, it suggests strongly
that Americans need professional financial advice.
   One of the findings, as reported by the IAFP, adds to that
feeling, informing recipients that ``financial planners are also
rated far ahead of other professionals in job performance and
qualifications.''
   Still, it has a convincing ring to it, one that conceivably
might be verified in a survey of one's own neighbors or co-workers,
all of whom have been observed to worry about these three areas of
life.
   The three areas _ retirement, education and health _ share other
traits too.
   All are categories of accelerating costs. All have become huge
burdens to business and government as well as to families. And all
three are costs that repeatedly seem to defy solution. Little
wonder that people hide from them!
   The categories, along with housing costs in one form or another,
are among the social challenges for which individuals most often
seek assistance from government or business, from the latter in the
form of employee benefits.
   The responses to coping with long-term medical payments for a
family member seemed especially significant.
   Respondents thought the possibility was quite high _ it rated
3.4 on a scale of 5 _ and said they hoped to pay the bills from the
patient's savings or retirement funds, from insurance and from
Social Security or Medicare.
   Only 11 percent of 1,000 respondents said they would use their
own savings or wages to cover the cost.
   When those who cited insurance coverage were asked if the policy
would specifically provide for long-term care only 15 said yes.
Another 27 said they didn't know.
   According to Robert J. Oberst, the association's treasurer,
people are confused about what their policies will cover. ``Unless
specifically bought for long-term care, most policies will not
cover it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-OnTheMoney Adv27   07-26 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On The Money, Adv 27,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday July 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Property owners Seeking Non-traditional Home-selling Methods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Randee and Mark Goldsmith decided to move
to Florida from suburban Detroit they considered listing their home
with a local broker, but paying thousands of dollars in commissions
didn't appeal to them.
   Doing the work themselves, though, proved too overwhelming. The
couple compromised: they'd show their four-bedroom contemporary
colonial while professionals screened potential buyers and handled
advertising for a flat fee. ``We saved about $8,000,'' said Mrs.
Goldsmith, 34, whose home sold five weeks after the couple listed
it last spring, not much below the $164,900 asking price. ``We used
the money to buy furniture for our new house.''
   An increasing number of homeowners, frustrated by escalating
moving expenses and the soft housing market in many parts of the
country, have been turning to alternate methods of selling their
property.
   Some people, like the Goldsmiths, opt for a discount broker or
real estate counselor while others handle everything themselves,
with different degrees of success. Either way, if you want to save
a buck be prepared to work for it.
   ``You can see this trend on the rise more and more each year. I
expect this is a sign of things to come,'' said J.R. Paine, author
of ``The 30 Day Way To Sell Your Home,'' one of several books on
the subject. Paine founded HMS Franchises Inc., a Southfield,
Mich., non-commission service that helped the Goldsmiths sell their
home.
   ``Most people don't want to throw out about 6 percent to 8
percent in commission. Who can afford that today?'' she asked.
   ``It goes even deeper than people just wanting to save,'' said
Jack Andrews, president of Help-U-Sell Inc., a Salt Lake City
discount broker. ``People are getting more involved in what happens
in their lives. You see more self-service gas stations and
automatic teller machines.''
   The trouble with the traditional home-selling system, critics
argue, is that it's usually unfair to most of the participants.
   A seller has to pay a hefty commission, 6 percent on average.
For a home selling for $200,000 that could mean $12,000 in reduced
profits on what often is a person's single biggest investment.
   But the agent who sells the home won't keep all that money. The
pot usually is split several ways, depending on how many agents
helped peddle the property. Since most work on commission, their
cut sometimes barely covers expenses.
   Discount brokers and counseling services, which comprise between
5 percent and 10 percent of all real estate firms, according to the
National Association of Realtors, claim they've been able to lower
the expense of home-selling.
   For instance, Help-U-Sell, a subsidiary of Mutual Benefit Life
Insurance Co. and one of the nation's largest discount brokers with
more than 500 franchises nationwide, says it offers almost the same
service as a traditional broker at a fraction of the cost.
   For a flat fee payable at the closing that usually averages 2.5
percent of a home's selling price _ around $5,000 for a $200,000
home _ Help-U-Sell promises to handle all advertising and marketing
and help buyers obtain financing, among other things.
   Sellers are required to show their own home, although the
company will handle that task too for a fee of around $500.
However, if a seller decides to list in the Multiple Listing
Service they may have to pay a higher commission to the broker who
finds a buyer for them.
   Discount brokers and do-it-yourselfers argue that homeowners are
by far the most qualified to show their home and they reason that
by saving money on commissions they can be more flexible in the
asking price.
   But Norman D. Flynn, who runs Flynn-Baker Inc., a full-service
realtor based in Madison, Wis., said do-it-yourself selling methods
don't always work well in a soft market.
   ``It seems that this is a phemomenon that comes in cycle when
you have a sellers' market, when there's a very limited supply of a
quality product,'' said Flynn, who is also president-elect of the
National Association of Realtors. ``Most sellers want the most
aggressive marketing approach.''
   Flynn said traditional brokers are best equipped to bring in
qualified buyers, largely because they have the most resources.
``You can't just pluck a sign in your yard and hope someone out
there will buy your home.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a n AM-ReligionRdp Adv28   07-26 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 28,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, July 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The youth department of the Church of God in
Christ, a predominantly black Pentecostal group, has set its
priority into the next century on fighting drugs and called on
other churches for help.
   The program was launched at the annual convention of the
church's United National Auxiliaries. The denomination claims 3
million members in the United States and some 1.5 million in 44
other countries.
   ``We hope to make an impact across the country,'' said Bishop
Charles Brewer of New Haven, Conn., chairman of the youth
department.
   A drug enforcement agent for east-central states, N. John
Wilder, told the convention, ``Drug addiction is not only a social
problem, it is a spiritual problem,''
   Bishop Floyd Perry of Cleveland said, ``When those who are
addicted leave treatment centers they often go back to drugs, and
we have to change that, we have to stop that.
   ``Treatment is the Bandaid, it only patches up the problem, but
the churches must do the healing...Our 6,000 churches are going to
send a message out about drugs that the real permanent answer is
spiritual faith, and we intend to cross denominational lines with
that message.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The divorce rate among Jews who intermarry _ 32
percent _is much higher than for marriages between Jews _ 17
percent, a study finds.
   The study by the North American Jewish Data Bank at the Graduate
School of the City University of New York also found that divorced
Jews who remarry are three times more likely to intermarry than
those marrying a first time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANILA, the Phillipines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China will reflect ``ideological
pluralism'' by the century's end, predicts Jonathan Chao, head of
the Chinese Research Center in Hong Kong.
   Chao, who has examined the ups and downs of freedom and
oppression in China since 1842, told the Lausannne II International
Congress on World Evangelism: ``Whether it will come by civil war
or by peaceful reform, I don't know, but it will come.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A draft of a universal Roman Catholic
catechism is expected to be ready by November, says Archbishop
William J. Levada of Portland, Ore.
   Levada, a member of the catechism's drafting committee set up
after the catechism was asked by a 1985 Synod of Bishops in Rome,
made his comment on a syndicated religious television program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop John L., May of St. Louis, president
of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, addresses the
Knights of Columbus convention here Aug. 1-3.
   About 2,000 delegates of the 1.5-million-member Catholic
fraternal service organization and their wives are expected to
attend.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After converging here late this week, a
convoy of 27 supply-laden trucks called the ``Pastors for Peace''
caravan was scheduled to head for Nicaragua to help meet needs of
its people.
   Driving a pickup truck loaded with items ranging from medical
supplies to musical instruments, the Rev. Robert Holmes of Helena,
Mont., a retired United Methodist minister, said:
   ``It's a cooperative venture and an effort to build bridges with
people we do not believe are in any way a threat to the United
States.''
   The convoy, sponsored by the Interreligious Foundation for
Community Organization, is carrying an estimated $1 million worth
of goods for Nicaraguan people deprived by ravages of civil war and
hurricane.
   The trucks, which began their trip from scattered points in the
country before merging here, was scheduled to reach Managua Aug. 11.
   Doug Colter of Chelsea, N. Y., driver of a truckload of farm
equipment, supplies for craft industry and developing commerical
fishing for El Salvadoran refugees in Nicaragua, said of the convoy:
   ``It makes a statement that there are people in this country who
care about the Nicaraguans' life situation.''
</TEXT>
