<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv05-06   07-26 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 05-06,0943</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 5-6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>``Z'' Is All New Except for Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan did about everything right on its new, fourth-generation
Z car _ except for the name.
   Something more reflective of the car being a real magnet for
young men might be appropriate. And I'm only counting the youthful
males who turned all the way around in their car seats or pulled
alongside my test car and spent minutes taking in every inch of
this auto.
   There also was the fellow who, evidently buoyed by the sheer
sight of the 300ZX, cheered and raised a clenched fist in
admiration. Believe me, none of these guys was looking at me.
   Ask Nissan if young males are the buyers of the 1990 300ZX and
they'll talk about psychographics _ the mental makeup of buyers _
not just demographics such as age, sex and household income. And
they'll say women are likely buyers, too.
   ``The buyers are auto enthusiasts who want to be noticed,'' said
Nissan spokesman E.C. Mueller. ``They have upper education and
income ... They're professionals wanting to make a statement.''
   Judging from the reaction the bright red test car got, there are
plenty of people who want to make a statement on today's roads. The
question for them is, do you have the $27,000-plus for the 300ZX?
   Make no mistake. The car is well done. It's lower and wider than
its predecessor but has a longer wheelbase. Its 3-liter V-6
produces 222 horsepower and is smooth and powerful, getting the car
up to 60 miles per hour in under seven seconds. (There's an even
faster model, a twin-turbo 300ZX, due out this fall that brings
even more horsepower _ 300.)
   The T-bar roof is there, offering the easy option of hardtop or
open roof.
   The optional Nissan Bose sound system was exceptional.
   And the real beauty of the 300ZX was the suspension. It retains
the road-hugging characteristics of a fine sports coupe. Yet it
doesn't jostle riders harshly, as many other sports cars do. It's a
fine blend, a good compromise between comfort and performance.
   As Nissan spokesman Mueller put it, ``On a six- or seven-hour
drive, you don't regret being in the 300ZX.''
   Still, making statements on the road isn't cheap. Like all
upscale sports cars, the 300ZX is pricey, and insurance costs will
be pricey, too.
   This is the fourth major design of the Nissan Z car. It's also
the company's response to critics who in recent years said Nissan
had lost sight of the original Z car image _ that of a fine sports
coupe. In fact, the first Z _ the 1970 240Z that was priced at
$3,526 _ was Motor Trend magazine's Car of the Year.
   Over the years, nearly 1 million Z cars have been sold as the
car evolved, and its name changed as larger engines were added. In
1974, it was renamed the 260Z because of the addition of the
2.6-liter engine, then 280Z in 1975, 280ZX in 1979, and 300ZX in
the 1984 model year.
   Sales of the Z car peaked at 73,101 in calendar 1984, the year
the third generation Z car debuted, then declined each year to just
19,357 in 1988. Nissan attributes some of the decrease to people
waiting until this year for the newly designed Z.
   It comes in two body styles _ a two-seater that was the test car
and a two-plus-two version. Both have rakish, sleek exteriors and
firm, form-fitting front seats.
   Drivers must be ready to drive with their side mirrors, as the
rear hatch lid is so sloping that the rear window is somewhat
small. The lines from the rear window defroster add some
distortion. Also, the side window pillars are thick and large and
make it difficult to see to the right and back.
   Inside the two-seater was a small, indented shelf area in the
midsection behind the seats for storage. Tall items fit well there
but also obstructed the rear view.
   Smaller items fit all the way back, where clearance was least.
The back also had cloth cases for storage of the two T-roof window
parts and straps to buckle them in so they don't slide around.
   The instrument panel had large, easy-to-read numbers and letters
_ no digital gadgets here. But beware of that speedometer that goes
to 160 mph. Nissan decided it could be dangerous to have a car that
might surpass a driver's ability. So there's a fuel cutoff at 148
mph. No burying the speedometer on this car.
   A nice touch was having all the adjustment buttons for the
cruise control embedded in the steering wheel. The cruise couldn't
be activated, however, until a main switch on the dashboard to the
left of the steering wheel was turned on.
   Nissan said competitors include the Toyota Supra, which starts
at more than $22,000, and the Chevrolet Corvette, which starts at
more than $31,000. Over the years, fewer Z car owners are reporting
trouble, according to Consumer Reports magazine. The periodical
ranked the 1984 and 1985 300ZX cars as average, followed by better
than average for the 1986 model and much better than average for
the 1987 model.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for seven years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug. 5-6</NOTE>
