<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-US-MiGs Adv30   07-26 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-US-MiGs, Adv30,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Fighters To Get First-Ever Escort Over US Airspace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a mission designed to enhance superpower
cooperation, two Soviet MiG fighter jets will be escorted over U.S.
airspace next month on their way to a North American air show.
   ``As far as we know, it will be the first time it's happened,''
said a State Department official familiar with preparations for the
event.
   The plan is for U.S. F-15 fighter jets from Elmendorf Air Force
Base in Alaska to escort their Soviet counterparts over U.S.
territory and then hand them over to escorts from the Canadian Air
Force.
   The Soviets are scheduled to attend Airshow Canada, a trade show
in Abbotsford, British Columbia, near Vancouver, as part of a
contingent that will also include an AN-225, the transport plane
that carries the Soviet space shuttle on its back.
   Final details have yet to be worked out, including the exact
date of the flight and the specific route to be flown, but
officials involved in the planning say they expect it to occur
around Aug. 4.
   The Soviets must file a flight plan three days in advance, said
the State Department official, a specialist in Soviet affairs who
asked not to be identified by name.
   The official said that given recent improvement in U.S.-Soviet
relations, there is little question the plan will go forward.
   ``Everybody feels good about this one,'' the official said.
``It's just part of the loosening, the improvement of relations.''
   Lt. Col. Mike Conley, spokesman for the Alaska Air Command, said
pilots there are used to intercepting Soviet aircraft, but only to
point them in the other direction, away from U.S. airspace.
   Usually, they see reconnaisance aircraft or Soviet BEAR bombers,
but not the MiG fighters, Conley said.
   ``This would be a different experience,'' he said.
   Ron Price, the president of Airshow Canada, said the Soviet
visit is the first such opportunity to view the MiG-29 in North
America.
   ``They've only been seen on a couple of occasions in the Western
world,'' Price said.
   Price, who traveled to the Soviet Union to help arrange the
visit, said the Soviets ``are interested in exchanging rides'' with
U.S. and Canadian fighter pilots, but he wasn't sure that could
take place.
   ``I'd love to do it myself,'' said Price, a real estate
developer who is also a private pilot.
   He pointed out that it is not just the spirit of Gorbachev's
policy of glasnost, or openness, that is making the event possible.
   ``They are coming to do business,'' Price said of the Soviets.
   The MiG Fulcrum that will be shown at the trade event is an
advanced fighter that is thought to be comparable to the F-16
Fighting Falcon.
   Airshow Canada, backed by the Canadian government, is being held
at a town that for nearly three decades has hosted an airshow
emphasizing aerobatics. The Canadians are hoping their expanded
aerospace show will become a premier trade event.
   The fighter jet hand-off is being planned amid increasing
cooperation between the U.S. and Soviet military.
   The chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William J.
Crowe, recently returned from a precedent-setting tour of
once-secret Soviet military installations.
   It was the first formal visit of a U.S. chairman to the Soviet
Union and the latest in a series of high-level visits designed to
dispel distrust between the superpowers. Last July, Crowe hosted
Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, then the Soviet chief of staff, on a
U.S. visit.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-BoysClubs Adv30   07-26 1009</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boys Clubs, Adv30,1041</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday AMs July 30 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boys Clubs Target Public Housing Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smacking on a wad of bubblegum,
12-year-old Kiva Henderson chats excitedly about the Boys and Girls
Club of Annapolis Bywater, which operates practically at the front
door of her home. ``They help you with your homework here. It
helped to bring up my grades,'' she says.
   Eleven-year-old Keith Collins chimes in, ``I like it because
it's a good way to stay off the streets. We can't get into trouble
here.''
   While the non-profit Boys Clubs of America has some 1,100
affiliates nationwide, the Annapolis club is one of 76 now located
in public housing projects in an effort to keep disadvantaged kids
from using drugs or dropping out.
   The organization hopes to expand that effort over the next five
years to reach an additional 700,000 disadvantaged children through
300 more such strategically located clubs.
   The clubs organize sports, trips and other activities to build
youngsters' confidence and teach good work habits, teamwork,
honesty and self-reliance.
   Robbie Callaway, the organization's government liaison, says the
first Boys Club at a public housing project was established in East
St. Louis, Ill., in 1953. But he said the national office
``re-energized'' its efforts 3{ years ago because of concerns about
increasing drug abuse and crime by youngsters.
   ``Public housing was identified as the greatest need because no
one else was doing anything there,'' he says.
   Samuel R. Pierce Jr., Housing and Urban Development secretary
under President Reagan, lent his name and influence to the effort.
But no government money was forthcoming from HUD, which is now
under investigation for doling out millions of dollars to projects
backed by prominent Republicans during Pierce's tenure.
   Still, Callaway said, Pierce's public statements of support
caused the organization to be ``swamped with requests'' that led to
the opening of 23 public housing clubs in 1987 and 1988.
   Now, Boys Club officials are looking to new HUD Secretary Jack
Kemp to make a financial commitment.
   Speaking at an April 10 press briefing at the White House, Kemp,
a former Boys Club member and later pro football player, said:
   ``I don't know if there are subsidies for football fields but if
I can find public monies in HUD to support the Boys Clubs and Girls
Clubs of America going into these public housing projects and
setting up athletic teams, I'm convinced that that would have a
significant impact upon putting an end to this scourge of drug
trafficking.''
   To bolster claims of decreased crime with Boys Clubs programs,
officials point to preliminary findings of a three-year study of
clubs in Albany and Binghamton, N.Y.; Jacksonville, Fla.; Peoria
and Rockford, Ill.; Meridian, Miss.; Houston and Brownsville,
Texas; and Martinez, Upland and San Jose, Calif.
   The report's evaluators from Columbia University and the
American Health Foundation said ``substance abuse problems and
juvenile delinquency have decreased in frequency and in severity
within housing projects served by a Boys and Girls Club.''
   Other evidence is anecdotal.
   Ken Darden, director of the Annapolis club, says about six club
members who recently graduated from high school had previously been
``borderline'' students.
   Boys Clubs officials boast that a tough public housing project
in Houston, the Oxford Place Housing Development, already has
experienced a decrease in crime, particularly vandalism.
   At Wilkinson Terrace in Shreveport, La., 10 weeks after opening
a club, officials reported little vandalism at the project as well
as at the nearby mall. The Louisiana results were cited in last
year's report of the White House Conference for a Drug Free America.
   Perfecto Villarreal, head of the Housing Authority of Contra
Costa County, Calif., says a fieldhouse adjacent to one local
housing unit is no longer the target of vandals since a club was
established there.
   ``The fieldhouse itself used to be vandalized,'' he says. ``Now
it is respected.''
   Callaway adds, ``We find that school attendance increases. ...
Also it increases the level of participation of parents and tenant
association in the local school activity, which is a side benefit
we could not have planned for.''
   A key problem is finding start-up money.
   ``Some people don't want to gamble on putting a program in
public housing,'' Callaway says. ``That's what we're finding with
local businesses and local citizens.
   ``Once we're started, though, once we give initial seed money,
it's like giving them a good housekeeping seal of approval and then
the local sector is willing to keep the club going,'' he says.
   Funding from HUD would be a big boost, Callaway says, noting
that the total cost of operating the national organization and its
affiliated clubs exceeded $219 million last year.
   So far, he says, the Justice Department has contributed
$350,000, ACTION agencies have given $362,000, and the Department
of Health and Human Services's substance abuse prevention office
has donated $450,000.
   The average cost to operate a local club on public housing
property is about $55,000, Callaway says.
   The national office works with clubs to find local support to
ensure the program's viability after the seed money dries up.
   `'We do not want, nor do we expect, nor will we allow a Boys and
Girls Club to operate solely on government money,'' Callaway says.
   Boys Club members pay yearly dues from $1 to $5. Youths unable
to pay usually can work off the fee with chores around the
clubhouse.
   The Annapolis club celebrates its first anniversary in September.
   ``The kids don't like to call this a project,'' says Darden, who
was a Boys Club member in Bronx, N.Y. ``They call it a co-op. But
the kids here span the whole spectrum of society, including coming
from low-income or single-parent families and environments of drug
abuse.
   Last September 50 kids joined and now the club has a membership
of 200.
   Robert Randall, 14, breaks away from an intense pool game to
offer his endorsement:
   ``There nothing I don't like about it. We get to play games, go
on trips, and it keeps you out of trouble.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Tate-MansonFamily Adv06-1stLd-Writethru b0605 07-26
0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tate-Manson Family, Adv 06-1st Ld-Writethru, b0605,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 6, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Charles Manson and His `Family' Face Middle Age in Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 18th graf, Lynette ``Squeaky'' ... Alderson, Va., to
make prison location in West Virginia sted Virginia.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Tate Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Manson, the most famous inmate in the
California prison system, lives in solitary confinement, subject to
threats by prisoners who want the glory of killing him.
   At 54, the one-time wild-eyed guru of a murderous communal
``family'' still gets stacks of mail and requests for interviews.
Lately he's been declining, because ``he says he doesn't want to
give away anything for free,'' says Evelyn Mazon, spokeswoman for
the high security state prison at Corcoran, where Manson was moved
early this year.
   The three giggly, long-haired young women who once followed
Manson's commands to murder have drifted into middle age behind
bars. Patricia Krenwinkel, 42, Susan Atkins, 41, and Leslie Van
Houten, who turns 40 this summer, appear regularly at parole
hearings seeking freedom that seems more elusive each year.
   Manson's chief lieutenant, Charles ``Tex'' Watson, is a
Christian minister and father of three children through conjugal
visits with his wife at the California Men's Colony at San Luis
Obispo. Miss Atkins also is married.
   Twenty years after the Sharon Tate-LaBianca murders, the Manson
Family killers have settled into prison life. Most are model
prisoners, but only one, Leslie Van Houten, seems a possible
candidate for parole.
   Miss Van Houten, who was not at the Tate home but admitted
stabbing Rosemary LaBianca, perhaps after she was dead, was the
youngest of those convicted. Her first conviction was reversed, her
second trial ended with a hung jury, her third resulted in another
conviction.
   Will any of them ever be released?
   ``Manson will never get out,'' says Paul Fitzgerald, the lead
defense attorney who represented Miss Krenwinkel. ``He doesn't want
to get out. He's perfectly adjusted to where he is.
   ``The girls, I think, will be released eventually,'' he says.
``I think Leslie will get out first, Patricia second, then probably
Susan.''
   ``They have been rehabilitated,'' he says. ``I don't think the
public safety argument is a good argument anymore. Now it's simply
vengeance.''
   Daye Shinn, who defended Miss Atkins, has a different view.
   ``People may say I'm crazy, but I believe the first one to get
out will be Charlie Manson, because he didn't do any of the
killings.''
   According to testimony, Manson sent his followers to Miss Tate's
home on Aug. 9, 1969, and the next night accompanied them to the
LaBianca house but left before the killing began.
   Deputy District Attorney Stephen Kay is committed to keeping
Manson locked up for the rest of his life. Except for Miss Van
Houten, he says the killers have little hope of parole. Miss Tate's
mother, Doris, has gathered thousands of signatures on petitions
urging that the killers never be released.
   Other members of the communal Manson Family have scattered.
   Somewhere in America, Michael Manson, the cult leader's son, has
turned 21. In New England, Linda Kasabian, the star witness of the
Manson trial, has raised her children to adulthood. Susan Atkins'
son grew up with an adoptive family.
   Bruce Davis and Robert Beausoleil, convicted with Manson in the
murder of Malibu musician Gary Hinman, are imprisoned at San Luis
Obispo.
   Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, who aimed a gun at President Ford in
Sacramento, Calif., is serving a life term at a federal prison in
Florida where she was moved after a brief escape from her quarters
at Alderson, W.Va.
   Sandra Good, who was in federal prison for writing threatening
letters to business executives, is free on parole, as is Steve
Grogan, convicted in the Manson-ordered murder of stuntman Donald
``Shorty'' Shea.
   The Manson trial defense attorneys continue to practice law in
Los Angeles.
   Manson's lawyer, Irving Kanarek, contends the cult leader was a
victim of bad publicity.
   Shinn regrets Miss Atkins wouldn't plead diminished capacity.
Manson ordered his followers to present no defense and they obeyed.
   ``The defendants were naive kids, products of the times,'' said
Fitzgerald. ``Most of them had no arrest records. Yet the public
loathes and detests them and sees them as some symbol of evil. .. .
They were the perfect symbols of innocence, young girls.''
   In 20 years, he said, he has heard no public expressions of
sympathy for these daughters of middle class American families.
   ``People don't say, `There but for the grace of God goes my
daughter,''' he said. ``I haven't heard that once.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
