<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-26 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0916</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for big-ticket factory goods rose a
modest 0.3 percent in June, the government said in a report seen as
evidence that manufacturing, although sluggish, isn't crumbling.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday orders for durable goods _
items ranging from bicycles to battleships _ advanced to a
seasonally adjusted $124.1 billion last month. That followed a 4.4
percent decline in May, the sharpest in 10 months.
   ``This is basically in line with the forecast of modest growth
but no recession,'' said economist Michael K. Evans, who heads a
consulting firm in Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wages, salaries and other benefits rose 4.5
percent in the 12 months ending in June, the Labor Department said
in a report viewed by some economists as a sign that inflationary
wage pressures may be peaking.
   The department's Employment Cost Index issued Tuesday measured
movements in labor costs over the preceding 12 months. For the 12
months ending in March, the last time the index was issued, the
increase was 4.6 percent. That figure was down from a 4.9 percent
increase in the 12 months ending in December.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of cars and trucks made by the eight major
automakers with U.S. plants rose 2.4 percent in mid-July compared
with last year, when sales began leveling off toward the end of the
third-best model year in history, the companies said.
   Vehicles made in North America by the companies sold at an
average daily rate of 39,726 during the July 11-20 period this
year, compared with a rate of 38,807 during the same period last
year, automakers said Tuesday.
   Car sales rose 1.5 percent and truck sales went up by 3.8
percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The capital-gains tax cut favored by a
majority of the House Ways and Means Committee is tilted more
toward high-income Americans than the one recommended by President
Bush, congressional economists said.
   Eighty cents of every dollar of benefit in the cut would go to
those with incomes above $100,000 a year, according to the staff of
the Joint Committee on Taxation.
   Bush's proposal would earmark slightly less _ 79.7 cents of
every dollar _ for the over-$100,000 group. It would give 2.5
percent of the total tax relief to those with incomes under $30,000
a year, compared with 1.8 percent under the bill being debated in
Ways and Means.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
defended Exxon's plans to stop the cleanup of the Alaskan oil spill
Sept. 15, saying the company is living up to its obligations.
   The secretary, who was put in charge of the cleanup by President
Bush, also said Tuesday it doesn't trouble him that Exxon will not
commmit to doing work next year before it assesses the need for
additional cleanup next spring.
   But a spokesman for Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan said Exxon's
obligation does not end in September. And Alaska's governor said he
expects Exxon to fulfill a promise to ``stay until the job was
done.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House investigators said their probe of
Internal Revenue Service involvement in eight cases, starting with
a dispute between jeans makers, uncovered widespread wrongdoing by
the criminal divison of the nation's tax agency.
   Investigators Leonard Bernard and Richard Stana said Tuesday the
Washington headquarters of the service showed a ``serious failure''
to ``effectively manage employee integrity programs.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush extended steel import quotas
for 30 months, but also served notice on the steel industry that
the trade protection would expire afterward.
   The president said Tuesday the 2{-year extension of the import
quotas would give U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills time to
negotiate an end to unfair steel subsidies provided by other
countries.
   Bush's decision will affect 29 countries that have negotiated
so-called voluntary restraint agreements with the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's biggest computer company will run a
large part of the data-processing operations of the world's biggest
photography company.
   The contract announced Tuesday will mean valuable experience in
a relatively new field for International Business Machines Corp.
and cost savings for Eastman Kodak Co.
   IBM will build and run a data center at Kodak's Rochester, N.Y.,
headquarters that will take over data-processing work now spread
out over three centers in Rochester and one in Windsor, Colo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge rejected a request by
North Dakota to block the $3.65 billion sale of Northwest Airlines
to a Los Angeles investment group.
   In a five-page ruling, U.S. District Judge Patrick Conmy said
Tuesday the potential harm to Northwest and its suitor, Wings
Holdings Inc., that would result from blocking the sale outweighed
the ``speculative harm'' to the state.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market settled for a mixed finish Tuesday, struggling
in the face of a setback for technology issues.The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials fell 1.90 to 2,583.08.
   The dollar fell as traders picked out indications that the
Federal Reserve was lowering interest rates.
   Short-term interest rates slid and bond prices advanced on
similar speculation about the Fed.
   Cotton futures prices rose sharply; soybean futures prices fell;
energy futures were lower; livestock and meat were mostly lower;
and precious metals were narrowly mixed.
