<FIRST>r f PM-IBMChip     07-26 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Chip,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces First Products With Latest Memory Chip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp., the
leader in memory chips, has become the first company to announce a
product using a chip that holds 4 million bits of information at a
time.
   IBM said Tuesday its 4-megabit chip can store the equivalent of
about 400 pages of double-spaced typewritten text on a sliver of
silicon the size of a small fingernail.
   The major Japanese computer makers are also making 4-megabit
chips, but have not announced any products using them. IBM was also
the first to bring out products using the previous generation 1
million-bit chip.
   ``This clearly demonstrates IBM's world leadership in this area
and our commitment to put technology to work for our customers,''
said Patrick A. Toole, IBM's general manager of technology products.
   Rather than a full-fledged computer, the first product using the
chip will be a memory expansion card that can be installed in the
powerful Model 70 and Model 80 of IBM's Personal System-2 line of
personal computers.
   One version of the memory card is available immediately at a
price of $1,795. Versions holding more data will be available in
limited quantities later this year and generally in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
