<DOCNO> AP890726-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Boeing     07-26 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Boeing,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Rise 22 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. says it second-quarter profit
increased 22 percent primarily because of higher sales and lower
research and development costs.
   The aerospace manufacturer said Tuesday it earned $195 million,
or 85 cents per share, on sales of $5.07 billion in the period
ending June 30. That compares to second-quarter 1988 earnings of
$160 million, or 70 cents per share, on sales of $4.73 billion.
   For the first half of 1989, earnings were $356 million, or $1.55
per share, on sales of $9.07 billion, compared with $296 million,
or $1.29 per share, on sales of $8.37 billion in the same period
last year.
   Boeing attributed the increase to the 7.2 percent quarterly
sales rise, research and development cost cuts, and other new
business expenditures related to commercial aircraft and computing.
   Commercial aircraft orders set a quarterly record, with 22
customers announcing orders for 502 jets and 8 de Havilland Dash 8
commuter aircraft, valued at $25 billion. The comparable figure in
second quarter 1988 was $13.3 billion.
   The gains were offset somewhat by performance problems on U.S.
government developmental and production programs; increased
research and development and other new business expenditures
related to electronics, defense and space programs; and higher
federal taxes.
   Boeing Chairman Frank Shrontz said the company still is
experiencing ``serious work force skill dilution problems'' because
of production rate increases on the firm's 737, 747, 757 and 767
production lines.
   Although a revised 747-400 delivery schedule was met through
June, the company faces ``substantial risk'' in ``being able to
produce and deliver on time all the airplanes we're committed to,''
Boeing spokesman Paul Binder said.
   The new schedule calls for more than 60 percent of the remaining
44 747-400 aircraft in 1989 scheduled for delivery in the last
quarter.
   Boeing is not revising the new 747-400 schedule now, Binder said.
   The company delivered 174 airplanes in the first six months of
1989, compared to 169 airplanes in the first half of 1988. Current
schedules call for the delivery of 220 airplanes the rest of the
year.
   Total firm backlog orders at June 30 were $67.7 billion,
compared with $53.6 billion at the same time last year.
</TEXT>
