<DOCNO> AP890726-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Exxon     07-26 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Said It Will Return Next Year, But Won't Commit To Resuming
Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. says it will return to the site of
the nation's worst oil spill next year but stopped short of making
a commitment to further cleanup.
   A July 19 internal memo to Exxon oil spill managers, which was
quoted in media reports Monday, suggested that the oil company's
cleanup crews would leave Alaska for good after shutting down for
the winter.
   But at a hastily called news conference Tuesday in Valdez,
Alaska, Otto Harrison, general manager for Exxon Valdez operations
in Alaska, said that the memo was not intended to ``extend to any
other phase of our cleanup operations.''
   The news conference was relayed by satellite to New York.
   The memo said that the company would demobilize cleanup
operations for the winter ``for safety and operational reasons.''
   But it went on to say that ``all equipment will be fully
demobilized'' and that ``our only commitment for the spring of 1990
is to survey the shorelines.''
   Exxon made the document public Tuesday.
   During the winter the company plans to conduct scientific
studies in Prince William Sound and the Gulf of Alaska, he said. A
survey team consisting of about 20 people will return to Alaska in
the spring, he added, but declined to say whether the company would
mobilize another massive effort to resume the cleanup.
   ``We'll be here to determine what the condition is and we'll
make our decision at that time in consultation with the federal
government,'' Harrison said. ``I can't speculate on cleanup in the
spring until we make that determination,'' he said.
   The Coast Guard has said that the cleanup is only one-third
complete and state officials and environmentalists have criticized
Exxon for suggesting that it could finish the work by its
self-imposed Sept. 15 deadline.
   Nevertheless, Harrison insisted that the cleanup operation would
be completed by the deadline.
   ``By the end of this cleanup season we will have the shorelines
environmentally stable,'' Harrison said.
   Asked if that meant clean, Harrison said, ``What I'm talking
about is having shoreline conditions so that it does not harm
otters, seals, birds and the normal flora and fauna that inhabit
the area.''
   Harrison suggested that Exxon might remain beyond the September
deadline.
   ``We'll work until wintertime weather shuts us in,'' Harrison
said. ``We think that's about Sept. 15.''
   He said studies under way are analyzing weather conditions into
the fall and that the company may change the September date based
on the findings.
   Exxon spokesman Jim Morakis in New York said the company had
rented warehouse space in Alaska to store cleanup machinery and
equipment over the winter.
   Exxon said Monday that it charged $880 million against
first-half earnings for out-of-pocket costs associated with the
spill. The company also said $400 million from insurance policies
will help with the cleanup and other spill-related claims, bringing
the total spill costs to more than $1.25 billion, excluding
lawsuits.
   Meanwhile Tuesday in Washington, Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner defended Exxon's plans to stop the cleanup Sept. 15, saying
the company is living up to its obligations.
   The secretary, who oversees the Coast Guard and was put in
charge of the cleanup by President Bush, also said it doesn't
trouble him that Exxon will not commmit to doing work next year
before it assesses the need for additional cleanup next spring.
   But a spokesman for Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan said Exxon's
obligation does not end in September. And Alaska's governor said he
expected Exxon to fulfill a promise to ``stay until the job was
done.''
   The Exxon tanker Exxon Valdez crashed into a charted reef on
March 24 and spewed millions of gallons of oil into Prince William
Sound, fouling hundreds of miles of beaches and killing numerous
wildlife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
