<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Apples-Alar     07-26 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apples-Alar,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Announces Details of Program Reimbursing Apple Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has announced the
operating details of a $15 million bailout to help apple growers
recover from the Alar scare.
   Officials announced the program on July 7 to help move some of
the huge apple supply from the market into donation channels.
   ``USDA is not purchasing apples for distribution, but is
reimbursing the industry up to $15 million once they remove
supplies from normal channels of trade,'' said Kenneth C. Clayton,
acting administrator of the department's Agricultural Marketing
Service.
   Clayton added Tuesday in a statement: ``Payments will be made
for 1988-crop apples donated to organizations that request them, or
for apples used in the manufacture of ethanol (fuel-grade alcohol)
and livestock feed, or dispersed through other USDA-approved,
non-traditional outlets.''
   He said the apple industry will be responsible for distribution
to organizations that request the surplus apples.
   In Washington state, spokesman Chuck St. John of the Washington
Apple Commission said organizations interested in receiving apples
should contact the Wenatchee, Wash.-based commission.
   Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., whose district includes the nation's
leading apple-producing region, said the plan was welcome but late.
   ``We've lost vital time waiting for the plan to be worked out,''
Morrison said. ``It's far from perfect, but I'm pleased we now have
a mechanism that will help clear the pipeline of 1988 apples before
the 1989 crop is ready to harvest.''
   Apple prices fell sharply after the Alar controversy began in
late February when a private environmental advocacy group said
eating apples treated with the chemical Alar substantially
increases the risk of cancer.
   The Environmental Protection Agency and the Food and Drug
Administration disputed the group's report as a major exaggeration
of the risk, but sales dropped. Alar is used to enhance apple
color, make harvesting easier and to extend storage life.
   Apples for donation will be allowed to contain traces of Alar,
which currently is permitted on crops at the rate of 20 parts per
million. The EPA plans to ban the use of Alar next spring and in
the interim has proposed reducing the allowable limit to one part
per million.
   Clayton said an inspector authorized or licensed by USDA must
inspect and certify the quality, size, condition and amount or
weight of the apples to removed from the marketplace.
   The assistance program will be available in any state where
apples are available from the 1988 crop, he said. The agency will
accept applications until Aug. 2 and will decide by Aug. 8 who can
participate in the program.
   ``I'm concerned with the amount of time before apples will
actually be distributed,'' Morrison said. ``The apple industry is
now forced to react quickly and creatively to make this program
work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-High-DefinitionTV     07-26 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Definition TV,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Official Lukewarm On Funding For HDTV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level Commerce Department official has
given lukewarm approval to a plan by Sen. Ernest F. Hollings to
pump hundreds of millions of dollars into developing new American
technologies such as high-definition television.
   Deputy Secretary of Commerce Thomas J. Murrin said Tuesday that
while he supported the principle of encouraging U.S. industry to
rapidly commercialize new technologies, he wasn't sure Hollings,
D-S.C., was adopting the right approach with a plan to spend $305
million on the department's new Technology Administration.
   The Hollings proposal essentially would double the $159 million
appropriated in fiscal 1989 for the Commerce Department's National
Institute of Standards and Technology, and it includes $50 million
in loan guarantees to spur private research and development in such
areas as advanced television.
   ``We do have several concerns about particular provisions in
this proposal, including the loan guarantee plan,'' Murrin told the
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
   ``We have progressed to the point where we agree with the
purposes behind these programs, but there may be more
cost-effective alternatives by which we could achieve the same
objectives,'' Murrin said. ``We have to make choices about which
programs would be most important, and what level of support would
provide us with a critical mass to ensure success.''
   Murrin is a longtime executive at Westinghouse who assumed his
Commerce post only a month ago. He said Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher had asked him to head the department's role in addressing
technology competitiveness issues such as high-definition
television.
   He said he considered it ``crucial'' that the United States
develop HDTV, which would use semiconductors and other advanced
technology to generate high-quality images. Proponents say HDTV
could revitalize a sagging U.S. consumer electronics industry and
have important military, medical, educational applications.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., suggested that if HDTV is so
important, ``maybe we need to put our money where our mouth is''
and that perhaps it needs ``presidential attention, just not the
secretary of Commerce.''
   Congress is considering ways to help a fledgling U.S. HDTV
industry overtake the big lead that Japan and Europe already have
in this area. Congress asked Mosbacher earlier this year to
recommend quickly ways the government might build a U.S. industrial
policy on advanced electronics.
   But Murrin said it would be ``some weeks'' before a report was
forthcoming because expert consultants could not agree on what time
frame to establish for development complicated new technologies.
   Murrin noted that President Bush has proposed that new
technology be spurred by a reduction in the capital gains tax; a
permanent research and development tax credit; and changes in
antitrust laws to encourage joint R&amp;D and production ventures.
   The Hollings bill, the Technology Administration Authorization
Act of 1989, would authorize fiscal 1990 appropriations for the
Technology Administration, which includes the National Institute of
Standards and Technology.
   Among other things, the bill authorizes funds for NIST's
in-house laboratory programs, its technology extension activities
and loan guarantees to raise $50 million in seed money for
industry-led projects in areas such as advanced electronics and
television, superconductivity; manufacturing and X-ray lithography,
a new method of making semiconductor chips.
   The $305 million for the Technology Administration would be
combined with $15.5 million already authorized in the 1988 Omnibus
Trade Act.
   The bill would exclude foreign companies, which Murrin said may
not be in America's best interests. He said he favored considering
foreign companies' requests to join R&amp;D consortia on a case-by-case
basis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Penney-Philippines Bjt   07-26 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penney-Philippines, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailer to Promote Philippine Merchandise in National Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. is planning the
biggest-ever promotion of Philippine merchandise outside that
nation, hoping that apparel in bright-colored batiks and tropical
prints plus other items will not only be eye-catching but
customer-catching.
   The two-week Festival of the Philippines in May might even
feature an in-store appearance by Philippine President Corazon
Aquino.
   The promotion, being produced in cooperation with the Philippine
Ministries of Trade and Tourism, could help give the Pacific island
nation a higher profile in the United States that would benefit its
tourism and manufacturing industries.
   David F. Miller, vice chairman and chief operating officer of
J.C. Penney stores and its catalogue, said the promotion at the
1,400 Penney department stores nationwide would be the largest ever
featuring Philippine merchandise outside that country.
   Penney plans to present details of its plans, which will include
Philippines cultural exhibits and other special events, at a news
conference today in Dallas.
   The Philippines has been a source of goods for Penney's for some
time, accounting for more than $50 million a year of its $15
billion in overall retail sales. With the promotion, Penney's could
sell an additional $50 million to $70 million of Philippines-made
merchandise.
   The company said its consumer research shows Americans are very
receptive to the Philippine culture.
   Penney, which will support the May 13-26 promotion with
television and print advertising, will launch the festivities at
its Dallas corporate headquarters and at five stores in cities
chosen for their large Philippine populations.
   Miller said in a telephone interview that the Festival of the
Philippines _ the fourth country-oriented sales campaign Penney has
run _ will give Penney a merchandising focus and some pizazz to
catch customers' attention.
   ``Stores can get to be so humdrum if they offer the same
assortment, the same merchandise,'' Miller said. ``Stores tend to
look alike and their assortments tend to look alike.
   ``We expect double-digit sales gains during the weeks of those
promotions,'' he said.
   Many retailers, including Bloomingdale's and Neiman-Marcus, have
built selling strategies around countries or regions, but Penney is
believed to be making the most ambitious attempt to capitalize on
the approach.
   The tactic usually has been used by upscale department stores
catering to the tastes of cosmopolitan consumers.
   In using the technique to appeal to its more middle-income
customers, Penney has an opportunity to present itself in a
slightly different light and stand out from the pack of competing
department store chains.
   ``If you walked into Bloomingdale's and saw this, you wouldn't
get all that excited about it. For Penney's, it's different,'' said
Norman McMillan of the retail consulting firm McMillan Doolittle.
``It's unexpected for them to do something international. Penney
has a thoroughly American reputation.''
   Penney's three past country promotions featured merchandise from
Italy, Britain and India.
   Penney managed something of a publicity coup with its British
promotion. The Prince and Princess of Wales visited its
Springfield, Va., store to help launch the Best of Britain
promotion in October 1985.
   Despite the royal seal of approval, the Best of Britain wasn't a
king-size success at every Penney store. The somber British tones
and heavy woolens didn't play well in parts of the South, for
instance.
   The Indian promotion, held in 1988, was considered highly
successful by the retailer, with sales from it approaching $100
million. It was featured in virtually every Penney store whereas
the earlier British and Italian ones weren't in all the smaller
stores and the catalogue.
   Penney wouldn't disclose how much it will spend to pitch the
Philippines but Miller said the promotional budget alone topped $10
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     07-26 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mid-July Sales Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued strong truck sales in mid-July offset
sluggish car sales during the period as the U.S. industry posted a
2.4 percent increase in vehicle sales over the same period last
year.
   The eight major companies making cars and trucks in the United
States reported Tuesday they sold vehicles at a daily rate of
39,726 during the July 11-20 period this year, compared with a rate
of 38,807 during the same time last year.
   Light truck sales rose 3.8 percent during the period while car
sales went up a modest 1.5 percent. Among the Big Three automakers,
car sales dropped 4.2 percent while light truck sales rose 3.7
percent.
   But analysts wondered how long and how strong the truck market
actually was.
   So far this year, car and truck sales among all the companies
were running 4 percent below last year's levels, with car sales
slipping 5.3 percent and truck sales dropping by 1.8 percent.
   ``The truck market has held up better than the car market,''
said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. of New York. ``If
you go back five or six months, I don't think there is any question
that the market has slowed down from a momentum point of view.''
   Kirnan and Tom Webb, senior economist with the National
Automobile Dealers Association in McLean, Va., agreed that the
truck market as a whole probably will shrink in the near future,
but the minivan segment of it likely will grow and the
sport-utility segment will stay about the same.
   That spells trouble for pickups, which have been the
best-selling vehicles in the past several years in the United
States.
   ``Pickups will continue to slow down where the economy is
slowing down,'' Kirnan said. ``That's going to reduce the
commercial demand for those types of vehicles.''
   Over the past several years, the truck market has shown solid
growth, mostly because of minivans, which are considered trucks but
blur the distinction between cars and full-size vans, and
sport-utility vehicles, including Chrysler Corp.'s Jeep line.
   On Tuesday, Chrysler again reported that its trucks outsold its
cars. So far this year, Chrysler has sold 550,745 trucks and
530,607 cars. The ratios at General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
favor cars way over trucks.
   Chrysler's car sales came in 18.5 percent lower in mid-July
compared with a year ago, while its truck sales rose 4.1 percent.
Ford suffered a 2.4 percent decline in mid-July car sales and
posted a 4.2 percent gain in truck sales. GM said its car sales
during the period fell 1.4 percent and truck sales rose 3.1 percent.
   ``The industry has settled in at a lower level here than '88 on
average,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. Inc.
of New York. ``It's stopped falling off the cliff; it's stopped its
free-fall.''
   Through the first 20 days of the month, cars and trucks sold at
a rate 5 percent above last year's.
   Sales typically flatten in the third quarter as manufacturers
shut plants to retool for the coming model year, which begins every
Oct. 1, and as they sell the last of the current model year's cars.
   This year, automakers have offered incentives and there has been
widespread speculation of price increases for 1990 models, both of
which can fuel sales late in the model year.
   Kirnan wondered whether some of the sales reported this month
are being ``borrowed'' from later on in the year, as consumers take
advantage of incentives now and avoid price increases later.
   ``I'm more convinced that the sales numbers that we are seeing
in the last 20 days in July are probably coming at the expense of
the fourth quarter and the first quarter (of 1990),'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
