<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports-Reax     07-26 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports-Reax,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plan Disappoints Some, Pleases Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Steel Imports, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big steel and its allies were disappointed
that President Bush extended steel import quotas for only 2{ years,
and some small steelmakers and steel users were disappointed he
didn't end them sooner.
   The American Iron and Steel Institute, the leading voice of the
major producers, expressed great concern and disappointment Tuesday
at the length of the extension.
   The trade group nonetheless welcomed the administration's
decision to free no country and exempt no product category covered
by the 5-year-old voluntary Rrstraint agreements, or quotas,
instituted by President Reagan.
   The bottom line for the Washington-based group is that 2{ years
is too little time to achieve Bush's goal of an international
consensus on ending government subsidization of steel production.
The big producers say subsidies lead to unfair pricing that
violates U.S. trade law and victimizes domestic companies.
   One of the most successful small producers, or mini-mills, Nucor
Corp., said the giants of steel are addicted to government
assistance.
   ``It's like dope,'' said F. Kenneth Iverson, Nucor's founder and
chairman. ``These guys have had protection for 25 years. It's part
of their way of life to ask the government to continually protect
them.''
   Iverson said the quotas ``cost taxpayers and customers a lot of
money.''
   ``If anything, they have delayed the modernization of our
industry, and in the long run they could do harm to the economy by
having cheaper steel in the international market to produce steel
parts that are imported in competition with American
manufacturers.''
   The Steel Manufacturers Association, representing 46 mini-mills
and their 36,000 employees, thanked Bush for extending the quotas
for 30 months and for seeking an international consensus.
   The 300 steel-using companies represented by the Precision
Metalforming Association applauded Bush's decision and were
encouraged that quotas would be increased 1 percent per year from
the 18.4 percent rate under the original program.
   But the association's president, Jon Jenson, said the
organization would have preferred that the restraints expire this
year.
   The United Steelworkers, however, joined in the criticism.
   ``The termination of the VRA program is assured by the Bush
administration, despite the fact that there will be no assurance
that the foreign government subsidizing measures will be
terminated,'' USW President Lynn Williams said.
   ``The limited duration of the extension will remove any further
pressure to end unfair trade practices because the American market
will soon be open without any rules,'' he said.
   Added U.S. Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., ``The president's
decision indicates he still does not fully understand the needs of
America's steel industry.''
   U.S. Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., joined the criticism. ``The chances
are slim to none that even the most determined U.S. negotiators can
end a generation of foreign government subsidizing and unfair
practices in a mere 2{ years,'' he said .
   The General Accounting Office recently declared that the
nation's steel industry has returned to normal levels of
profitability. Reagan imposed the quota program at the peak of a
slump that bled the industry of $12 billion over five years and
eliminated thousands of jobs.
   National Steel Chairman Howard M. Love said as late as Tuesday
morning that a five-year extension of the VRAs was essential to
allow U.S. steel producers to finish modernizing their plants.
   ``We're very disappointed,'' Love said late Tuesday, pledging
support for negotiating an international consensus but saying time
is short.
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. expressed regret over the length of the
extension.
   ``The basic conditions that dictated the need for VRAs in 1984 _
excessive global steelmaking capacity and unfair trade _ are still
in existence today,'' said Chairman Walter F. Williams.
   Japan said today it would cooperate with the decision to extend
steel import quotas.
   Seiroku Kajiyama, head of the Ministry of International Trade
and Industry, said Japanese steel companies have worked for many
years with the American steel industry to assist in its
restructuring through technology transfers and joint ventures.
   In upcoming negotiations with U.S. trade officials, Kajiyama
said, Japan will specifically take up ``some vital issues'' such as
the development of free market conditions in world steel trade, the
continuing modernization of the U.S. steel industry and the sound
development of steel industries in both countries.
</TEXT>
