<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LIN-McCaw     07-26 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Broadcasting President Sets Deadline For Deal with McCaw</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp.'s president imposed a
Monday deadline for the conclusion of buyout talks with its
unsolicited suitor, McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
   LIN President Donald A. Pels told McCaw officials Monday in a
letter that despite some misgivings, he was willing to support a
buyout at no less than $127.50 a share if a definitive agreement is
reached by 9 a.m. EDT July 31.
   A buyout at that price would value the New York-based cellular
telephone, television broadcasting and publishing company at nearly
$6.9 billion, although McCaw's cost would be lower because it
already owns 9.8 percent of LIN's stock.
   Pels said that if there was no agreement by the deadline, ``we
intend to take such other actions and to pursue such other
available alternatives as our board of directors determines to be
in the long-term interests of LIN's stockholders.''
   A spokesman for Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw, Steven Bruce, said
McCaw had received the letter and its lawyers and investment
bankers planned to respond, although he could not say when.
   In national over-the-counter trading, LIN rose $2.37{ a share
Tuesday to $111.87{, while McCaw rose $1.75 a share to $37.
   McCaw, the nation's biggest cellular telephone company, said
last week it was suspending negotiations with LIN on the
possibility of a buyout at $127.50 a share and was extending its
tender offer of $110 a share for LIN's stock until Aug. 11.
   LIN released a copy of a letter in which its president told
McCaw Chairman Craig O. McCaw that the suspension of talks
disturbed LIN's negotiators because the only apparent obstacle was
how soon the deal could be completed.
   ``We seriously doubt that you are willing to negotiate a `real
deal' to acquire LIN at a fair price to its stockholders,'' Pels
wrote.
   He said McCaw appeared to ``be trying to get an option on LIN or
through your tender offer to steal the company at the lowest
price'' and said LIN had doubts about McCaw's ability to obtain
financing.
   Nonetheless, Pels wrote, he still was prepared to recommend that
the LIN board approve a definitive agreement for McCaw to pay no
less than $127.50 a share for LIN stock provided the agreement is
reached by Monday.
   ``The continued uncertainty about your interest in acquiring LIN
at a fair price is harmful to our stockholders and extremely
disruptive to LIN's ongoing operations and our ability to implement
LIN's long-term strategic plans,'' Pels said.
   McCaw started bidding for LIN in early June with an unsolicited
offer of $120 a share.
   LIN rejected that offer as inadequate and McCaw subsequently
reduced it to $110 a share, citing an unfavorable court ruling
relating to LIN's interest in some cellular telephone operations it
jointly owns with Metromedia Inc.
   On July 13, LIN and McCaw said they were in talks on a possible
buyout at $127.50 a share in cash and stock.
   But McCaw said Friday it was suspending those negotiations and
extended its previous tender offer of $110 a share.
</TEXT>
