<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     07-26 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Widens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to
$3.1 billion in June as the growth in imports outpaced exports, the
government said Wednesday.
   The seasonally adjusted deficit compared with a $2.8 billion
shortfall in May, the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   Meanwhile, the current account deficit widened to $2.4 billion
from $2.2 billion. The current account includes invisible trade,
such as services, overseas investment earnings and official
transfer payments.
   The figures were better than the markets has expected. Forecasts
had called for a merchandise trade deficit of $3.3 billion and a
current account gap of $2.6 billion.
   The pound rose strongly on the news, jumping to $1.6435 after
the report was released at 11:30 a.m. local time, from $1.6380
before.
   A dock workers' strike at some ports may have depressed recorded
exports, and to a lesser extent imports, the department said.
   Exports rose 3.3 percent, to $12.8 billion from $12.4 billion,
the department said.
   Exports were at record levels but continued to be affected by
production problems as well as by a routine maintenance program
carried out by oil operators in the North Sea, the department said.
   Imports rose 4.5 percent, to $15.9 billion from $15.3 billion.
   Since the beginning of 1989, Britain's merchandise trade deficit
has grown to $19 billion, compared with a deficit of $14 billion a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
