<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 0821EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest     07-26 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies North Dakota's Bid to Block Sale of Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has cleared the way for
the $3.65 billion sale of Northwest Airlines to a Los Angeles
investment group, likening North Dakota's attempt to impede the
transaction to ``David vs. Goliath.''
   In a five-page decision issued Tuesday, U.S. District Judge
Patrick Conmy refused North Dakota's request for a court order
blocking the sale.
   Conmy said the potential harm to Northwest and its suitor, Wings
Holdings Inc., that would result from blocking the sale outweighed
the ``speculative harm'' to the state.
   David Duffy, a spokesman for Wings, an investment company headed
by Alfred Checchi, a former treasurer of Marriott Corp., said the
one-day uncertainty of whether a judge might block the proposed
sale has not jeopardized the deal.
   ``Our view was the suit was utterly without merit,'' Duffy said.
``We will have an announcement (today) as to the status of the
offer.''
   State officials filed a lawsuit Monday contending the Northwest
buyout would lead to higher fares and violate an agreement
Northwest made with North Dakota in 1986.
   North Dakota's lawsuit claimed the acquisition of Northwest by
Wings would require the airline to restructure to finance its debt,
leaving the state vulnerable to higher fares and radical cuts in
service.
   Conmy said North Dakota Attorney General Nicholas Spaeth should
be commended ``for his efforts _ David vs. Goliath as they may be _
to attempt to force some degree of regulation upon the airline
industry.''
   But in this case, the judge added: ``David is weaponless ... The
attorney general has simply not satisfied his burden of
establishing that the acquistion under the present arrangement
would have the claimed effect on air travel in North Dakota.''
   Checchi said Tuesday he had the financing in place to close the
deal, but he was awaiting a Federal Trade Commission ruling to
clear the way. Wings had asked the FTC to shorten the waiting
period requirement that was scheduled to expire today.
   More than 99 percent of the shares of NWA Inc., Northwest's
parent, have been tendered to Wings, which has offered $121 a share.
   Spaeth on Tuesday acknowledged he had only a ``reasonable
chance'' of convincing a judge to block the sale.
   ``I would have felt bad if I hadn't tried to do something, when
I knew this thing was going to be a disaster for the state,''
Spaeth said at a news conference.
   If Wings acquires the airlines, changes in Northwest's North
Dakota operations will be seen within months, Spaeth predicted.
Northwest will not be able to repay its debts without some ``pretty
drastic steps,'' he said.
   Spaeth's 15-page lawsuit also seeks $50 million in damages from
Northwest for breach of contract between North Dakota and the
airline, meaning the litigation will continue, Spaeth said.
   A court order delaying the sale would have given North Dakota
some leverage to negotiate protections for the state similar to
those obtained in 1986, when Northwest acquired Republic Airlines,
the attorney general said.
</TEXT>
