<HEAD>LIRR Head Resigns; Metro-North Chief Steps In For Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president and general manager of the Long
Island Rail Road, the nation's largest commuter-train network, has
resigned.
   Bruce McIver, who headed the railroad since 1985, announced his
departure Tuesday saying he wanted to pursue other interests.
   The state Metropolitan Transportation Authority, which oversees
LIRR operations, appointed Peter Stangl, president of the
Metro-North Commuter Railroad, as acting LIRR president.
   Last week the LIRR's state-appointed Commuter's Council called
for McIver's resignation as it released an annual report card
giving the railroad a mediocre grade for overall performance for
the second year in a row.
   LIRR and MTA spokesmen said McIver's decision was not related to
the council's criticism.
   The LIRR carries 272,000 passengers daily.

