<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0368</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market got off to an indecisive start
today amid disappointment about recent corporate earnings reports
and uncertainty about the economy's health.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials declined 6.45 to
2,576.63 by 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues held a narrow lead over declines on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 487 up, 405 down and 551 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 26.5 million shares after the
first 30 minutes of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dipped 0.06 to 186.04. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index headed up 0.52 to 370.64.
   Numerous companies have released second-quarter results lately
that have fallen short of or merely matched analysts' expectations.
   Confusion about just how well the economy is doing has made the
market nervous about profit prospects. A significant slowdown,
combined with continuing strength in the dollar, could make things
difficult for many companies.
   The market is hoping a clearer picture about the economy will
emerge from Thursday's report on the Gross National Product for the
second quarter.
   After the first half hour of trading, Ford Motor topped the list
of actively traded NYSE issues and was up \ to 50.
   The second most heavily traded issue was Unisys, the Big Board's
most active issue Tuesday. Unisys perked up a bit, rising \ to 20{,
after losing 1] in the previous session.
   Among heavily traded blue chips, International Business Machines
plunged 1{ to 111\. It was disclosed today that the big computer
maker had to cancel a major new product announcement on Tuesday due
to last-minute technical problems.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average edged down 1.90 to
2,583.08.
   In the broader market, advancing issues outpaced declines by
about 9 to 8 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks, with 772 up, 684 down and 529 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index rose 0.94 to 182.16.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board picked up to 179.27 million
shares from 136.26 million on Monday.
