<FIRST>r f BC-Sweden-Borg     07-26 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sweden-Borg,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Call in Bankruptcy Office to Save Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of Bjorn Borg's business
operations in Sweden asked bankruptcy officials Wednesday to
examine the company's books in an effort to avert liquidation.
   The five-time Wimbledon champion said Tuesday he would close
down the Scandinavian part of his fashion empire after the partners
rejected his offer to pay the company's debts and sell shares to
employees.
   ``The Bankruptcy Office will make a financial investigation into
the company, which will take 10 to 14 days,'' Peter Smedman, head
of the Central Bankruptcy Office, said on Swedish Radio.
   ``I hope and believe that we will sort this out and enable the
company to live on,'' he said.
   It was not clear whether Borg had agreed to the investigation of
Bjorn Borg Invest AB, which controls Borg's clothing operations in
Sweden.
   Borg's other holdings, registered in Monaco and the English
Channel island of Jersey, apparently were not affected by the move.
