<DOCNO> AP890726-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-GE-DC-10Crash 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GE-DC-10 Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspection Team Arrives at Engine Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with NTSB inspector's arrival.
Picks up 9th graf, the plant....</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal inspector arrived today to
examine records at the General Electric Co. plant that made the
engines on the United Airlines DC-10 that crashed last week in Iowa.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said its
Washington-based inspector, Jack Young, would be at GE's suburban
Cincinnati plant for perhaps two days to examine manufacturing
records.
   Young was accompanied this morning by about 10 representatives
of other organizations assisting the NTSB with its investigation of
the July 19 crash of United Airlines Flight 232 at Sioux City,
Iowa. Of the plane's 296 passengers and crew, 111 people were
killed.
   NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said Tuesday that investigators
want to know why the fan section of the No. 2 engine, mounted on
the tail of the jetliner, apparently disintegrated about 45 minutes
into the flight from Denver to Chicago.
   ``We have an uncontained engine failure. We know that. So we're
trying to learn all we can about the manufacturing history of the
engine,'' he said.
   The Federal Aviation Agency's Aeronautical Center in Oklahoma
City said there was no record of any service problems with the No.
2 engine on Flight 232.
   The NTSB said those accompanying Young would include
representatives of the FAA, GE, United, McDonnell Douglas and the
Airline Pilots Association and International Association of
Machinists. The group is one of eight teams set up by the NTSB to
investigate various aspects of the crash.
   The plant made all three of the DC-10's engines. GE and NTSB
officials have declined to disclose the age of the CF6-6 engines,
introduced on the DC-10 in 1971. The DC-10 is the only commercial
jet on which the engine is used, GE officials said.
   The engine has established a record of reliability during its 17
million total flight hours in commercial service, GE said.
   GE said plans are being made to ship the remains of the engine
from Sioux City to the plant for examination. Lopatkiewicz said the
missing engine fan had accumulated 41,009 flight hours since it was
built and 2,170 hours since its last detailed inspection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
