<FIRST>r f PM-ExxonValdez 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez, 1st Ld-Writethru,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Agrees to Post $20 Million to Get Crippled Tanker Into Dry
Dock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to move higher Exxon comments on oil cleanup,
include comments by Transportation Secretary Skinner that he is satisified
with cleanup, other details. Picks up 12th graf, `The Coast Guard...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Shipping Co. has agreed to post $20
million and meet other requirements to get its crippled tanker
Valdez into dry dock for repairs.
   The oil company signed an agreement Tuesday to comply with state
restrictions as the damaged tanker underwent continued emergency
repair work on the high seas about 56 miles offshore.
   Also Tuesday, Exxon Corp. said it will return to the site of the
nation's worst oil spill next year but stopped short of making a
commitment to further cleanup.
   Nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil spilled into Alaska's
Prince William Sound March 24 when the Exxon tanker hit a submerged
reef.
   A July 19 internal memo to Exxon oil spill managers, which was
quoted in news reports Monday, suggested that the oil company's
cleanup crews would leave Alaska for good after shutting down for
the winter.
   But at a hastily called news conference Tuesday in Valdez,
Alaska, Otto Harrison, general manager for Exxon Valdez operations
in Alaska, said the memo did not rule out a resumption of cleanup
operations.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Tuesday that
Exxon's plan to halt cleanup efforts Sept. 15 was justified because
little can be accomplished once cold weather arrives.
   Skinner, previously a critic of Exxon's cleanup effort, said in
remarks at Republican fund-raising dinner in Chicago he now is
satisfied with it.
   He said more than 10,000 Exxon employees are ``working 16 hours
a day to make sure that everything that can be done, will be done
in Alaska before the weather sets in this fall.''
   During the winter the company plans to conduct scientific
studies in Prince William Sound and the Gulf of Alaska, Harrison
said. A survey team will return to Alaska in the spring, he added,
but he would not say whether the company would mobilize another big
cleanup effort then.
   ``We'll be here to determine what the condition is and we'll
make our decision at that time in consultation with the federal
government,'' Harrison said. ``I can't speculate on cleanup in the
spring until we make that determination.''
   In San Diego, the California Assembly's Select Committee on Oil
Spill Prevention and Response Preparedness heard testimony Tuesday
on the status of the tanker Valdez and Exxon's efforts to bring it
into dry dock.
   ``The state of California is in the same position as the state
of Alaska when they had the (Valdez) accident, and it must be
corrected,'' said Assemblyman Gerald Felando, who visited Alaska in
June.
   The Coast Guard denied the ship entry to San Diego Bay on July
10 because of an 18-mile slick and other discharges. The ship faced
navigational problems as well when steel plates separated from the
hull during the 2,500-mile trip from Alaska.
   The plates cut loose Monday were dangling too deep to negotiate
the bay.
   Samples from two slicks that coincided with the Valdez's arrival
in Southern California waters showed traces of Alaskan North Slope
crude mixed with heavy concentrations of marine life now living in
the ship's shredded cargo tanks.
   But Coast Guard Cmdr. Don Montoro said other preliminary test
results showed no toxicity and barely detectable hydrocarbon levels.
   ``As far as the Coast Guard is concerned, as long as everything
else has been put in place, I see no reason why the vessel can't
come into port,'' he said.
   Montoro has the final say on when the Valdez can enter San Diego
Bay en route to National Steel and Shipbuilding Co. for a $25
million repair. He said the entry would likely take place between
Friday and Sunday.
</TEXT>
