<FIRST>r f PM-QuintsInsurance     07-26 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quints Insurance,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Loses Loses Insurance After $2.75 Million in Medical Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family has lost its health insurance after
running up $2.75 million in medical bills since the births of
quintuplets two years ago.
   Provident Life and Accidental Insurance of Chattanooga, Tenn.,
canceled the group policy that covers Ron and Roz Helms and their
family effective next month.
   Other insurers have refused to provide a policy for the family
after the multimillion-dollar payout, Mrs. Helms said Tuesday.
   ``It doesn't look good for us right now,'' Mrs. Helms said.
``It's pretty scary to think we won't have any insurance.''
   The family's claim was the biggest in the history of
Transamerica Life Co., the original carrier, said Jeff Shaw,
general agent for Transamerica. Transamerica sold its group
insurance division, which carried the group policy, to Provident a
year ago.
   ``They stayed on as long as they could for the Helmses,'' said
Shaw, who is trying to find another company willing to insure the
family.
   The family was insured under a group policy that originally
covered about 30 employees of Mercedes Restaurants Inc., which owns
the restaurant that Helms manages. Provident canceled the group
policy because of declining membership blamed on premium increases.
   The premium hikes were needed to cover increased claims,
including those for the quintuplets, said Provident spokeswoman
Jane Overbeck.
   ``The group didn't have enough members and the group's claim
losses were taken into consideration,'' Ms. Overbeck said.
   Mrs. Helms said she's worried her family may have to sell their
house and cars and take pay cuts to qualify for public assistance.
   ``It's crazy that they'd drop us now when we're basically
healthy,'' she said. ``The worst is over. It's behind us.''
   The babies were born prematurely on March 2, 1987, and suffered
a variety of medical problems that kept them in the hospital for
long periods of time. Samantha, the smallest and most frequently
ill, lived most of her first year in a hospital bed.
   Mrs. Helms said Provident canceled its coverage effective Aug.
1, although its contract requires it to continue paying for
existing medical conditions for a year until a new insurer can be
found for the children: Shannon, Meredith, Bevin, Samantha and
Benjamin.
   Those payments include $3,000 per month for oxygen, medicine and
a home nurse for Samantha, and the $50 per week spent on physical
therapy for Benjamin, who has cerebral palsy. But new illnesses,
injuries and medicine will not be covered, Ms. Overbeck said.
</TEXT>
