<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     07-26 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0368</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved lower in moderately
active trading today, weighed down by weakness in International
Business Machines and other technology issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials declined 9.48 to
2,573.60 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues overtook advances on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 636 down, 517 up and 555 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 58.35 million shares after the
first 90 minutes of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dipped 0.11 to 185.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 0.05 to 370.21.
   Numerous companies have released second-quarter results lately
that have fallen short of or merely matched analysts' expectations.
   Confusion about just how well the economy is doing has made the
market nervous about profit prospects. A significant slowdown,
combined with continuing strength in the dollar, could make things
difficult for many companies.
   The market is hoping a clearer picture about the economy will
emerge from Thursday's report on the Gross National Product for the
second quarter.
   Part of the downturn in the Dow Jones industrial average was due
to a drop in IBM, which fell 1{ to 111\. It was disclosed today
that the big computer maker had to cancel a major new product
announcement on Tuesday due to last-minute technical problems.
   Other losers among technology stocks included: Compaq, down 1~
to 86\; Cray Research, down 2} to 41]; Data General, down { to 17\;
Hewlett Packard, down ] to 51[; and Prime, down 1 to 16[. In
over-the-counter trading, Apple Computer showed a loss of 1 to 37}
and Lotus Development declined 1 to 22}.
   Traders started unloading technology stocks Tuesday on news of a
bearish forecast for the personal computer industry.
   Ford Motor topped the list of actively traded NYSE issues and
was up [ to 49~.
   The second most heavily traded issue was Unisys, the Big Board's
most active issue Tuesday. Unisys perked up a bit, rising [ to 20],
after losing 1] in the previous session.
</TEXT>
