<FIRST>u f PM-PrimeComputer 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Postpones Stockholders Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs to CORRECT to May sted April; PICKS UP 7th
graf pvs `Tustin, Calif.-based...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. postponed its annual
meeting set for today to give shareholders more time to weigh
competing offers for the minicomputer maker.
   The meeting was postponed until Aug. 9, Prime said in a
statement released 90 minutes before the meeting was to begin.
   Prime's seven directors, who face re-election against a slate of
candidates from hostile suitor MAI Basic Four Inc., also
recommended again that the company accept a $1.2 billion buyout
offer from J.H. Whitney &amp; Co.
   J.H. Whitney, the nation's oldest venture capital firm, has
offered $21.50 a share in case for about 50 million Prime shares
and would exchange notes for the rest.
   Prime's board said the offer from the New York firm is
``economically superior'' to MAI Basic's proposal to buy Prime's
minicomputer division for $450 million in cash and $150 million in
notes.
   An MAI Basic spokeswoman no comment on the delay in the annual
meeting. It was the third time Prime postponed the meeting, which
previously had been scheduled for May 12 and June 15.
   Tustin, Calif.-based MAI Basic has been attempting to acquire
Prime in a hostile bid since last November, but J.H. Whitney made
its friendly offer last month.
   MAI Basic then offered to buy Prime's minicomputer business,
which accounted for about one-third of the company's 1988 revenue
of $1.6 billion. MAI Basic's slate of board candidates has said it
would sell the minicomputer division to MAI Basic and use the
proceeds to buy back Prime stock.
   The promise of a stock repurchase was considered an enticement
to shareholders because it would likely drive up Prime's share
price.
   In addition to its minicomputer business, Prime is the
second-largest producer of computer-aided design and manufacturing
systems, surpassed only by International Business Machines Corp.
</TEXT>
