<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-26 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On Technicals, Higher Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
rebounding from recent declines.
   Analysts said the rally was largely a reaction to steep recent
declines. Soybean futures prices, for example, had fallen in each
of the four previous sessions.
   ``I think we got the markets oversold; prices got a little too
cheap in the short run,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of
trading-floor operations for Balfour Maclaine Corp., a New
York-based futures brokerage.
   But he said corn and soybean prices were likely to fall further
if normal weather patterns _ mild temperatures and weekly showers _
continue in the Midwest.
   With more than half the corn crop now past the sensitive
pollination phase, Zusel said traders were shifting attention to
the soybean crop, which is entering its critical flowering and
pod-setting stage.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was
1\ cents to 2} cents higher with September at $2.30 a bushel; oats
were 2 cents to 2} cents higher with September at $1.45 a bushel;
soybeans were 5{ cents to 8 cents higher with August at $6.68 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .33 cent higher with August
at 72.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .17
cent higher with August at 83.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .20
cent lower to .08 cent higher with August at 46.05 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .40 cent lower with August at
27.70 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
