<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computers     07-26 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computers,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Earnings Jump 43 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. said Wednesday its earnings
for the second quarter of 1989 jumped 43 percent.
   Rod Canion, president and chief executive officer of Compaq,
said international sales were especially high during the quarter,
accounting for 44 percent of total sales.
   For the three-month period ending June 30, Houston-based Compaq
had earnings of $83.9 million, or $1.95 per share, on sales of
$722.1 million compared to earnings of $58.6 million, or $1.45 per
share on sales of $456.8 million in the 1988 quarter.
   ``Worldwide demand for our two recently-introduced desktops, the
Compaq Deskpro 386@33 and Compaq Deskpro 286e, as well as
continuing strong sales of the Compaq SLT@286 laptop and 386
desktop line gave Compaq another outstanding quarter,'' Canion said.
   On the international market, Compaq said its share of Europe's
seven largest personal computer markets grew during the first
quarter of 1989 to 10.2 percent, making it the second largest
supplier of personal computers to the European business market.
   In May, the company announced plans to almost double the size of
its manufacturing and office facility in Erskine, Scotland. The
$37.5 million expansion is the third at the facility since its
opening in 1987. The workforce at the facility is expected to
double over the next three years.
   Compaq expanded into South America during the quarter with sales
beginning in Chile, Venezuela and Colombia. New subsidiaries also
were established in Denmark and Norway.
   The company announced earlier this month that it had signed a
patent cross-license agreement with rival IBM in which each company
granted to the other a worldwide non-exclusive license covering
patents having an effective filing date before July 1, 1993.
   For the first six months of 1989, Compaq recorded a net income
of $167.1 million, or $3.89 per share, on sales of $1.4 billion,
compared to $105.5 million, or $2.66 per share, on sales of $896.3
million during the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
