<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1509EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Pepsico     07-26 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Pepsico,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 21 Percent Earnings Gain for Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. said Wednesday its second-quarter
earnings climbed 20.6 percent, as its soft drink, snack foods and
restaurant divisions each contributed double-digit gains in revenue
and operating profits.
   ``We have tremendous momentum in all three of our businesses,''
said D. Wayne Calloway, chairman and chief executive.
   The Puchase, N.Y.-based company said it earned $264.9 million,
or $1 a share, in the three months ended June 17 compared with
$219.6 million, or 84 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 23.8 percent to $3.59 billion from
$2.9 billion a year earlier.
   The latest results included an after-tax credit of $15 million
for several one-time events, the largest of which was a decision to
keep rather than sell a foreign bottling operation.
   The operating profit from the company's soft drink business
soared 60 percent to $239.6 million while sales rose 33 percent to
$1.5 billion.
   Excluding one-time events and the net effect of bottling
acquisitions, operating profits still rose 32 percent and sales
rose 9 percent.
   The growth in operating profits reflected strong domestic
results, due to volume growth, higher pricing and efforts to
control costs, the company said.
   It said its Diet Pepsi and Mountain Dew brands posted
double-digit growth in case sales in the United States.
   The snack foods business had an operating profit of $191.7
million, up 24 percent from a year earlier, on a 17 percent revenue
increase to $958 million. Its domestic profits rose at a
double-digit pace while international profits more than tripled.
   The company said domestic volume for Frito-Lay rose 8 percent
led by gains in the Ruffles, Fritos and Doritos brands.
   The company's restaurant business earnings rose 15 percent to
$102.1 million, while sales rose 20 percent to nearly $1.2 billion.
   Earnings were up 41 percent to $51.8 million at the Pizza Hut
restaurants and 60 percent to $32.4 million at Taco Bell
restuarants, but fell 44 percent to $17.9 million at Kentucky Fried
Chicken.
   The decline at Kentucky Fried Chicken was blamed on an $8
million charge for consolidating its field operations, higher costs
for chicken and labor and lower customer counts.
   For the first six months, Pepsico earned $430 million, or $1.62
per share, up 29.2 percent from $332.9 million, or $1.27 a share, a
year earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose 21.7 percent to $6.55 billion from $5.38
billion.
</TEXT>
