<FIRST>u f PM-EnergyPolicy 1stLd-Writethru f0030 07-26 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Policy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0030,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Legislation Ending Price Controls on Natural Gas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Bush signing and remarks. Pickup 4th graf
pvs, Full natural. Also on general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, declaring the the best way to
deal with energy problems ``is to let our market economy work,''
today signed legislation ending the last vestiges of price controls
on natural gas.
   The president used the White House signing ceremony to reiterate
his call for increased domestic oil exploration and drilling to
curb the country's reliance on oil imports.
   ``The bottom line is, a strong domestic drilling and producing
business is essential for the national security of the United
States of America,'' Bush said.
   He said Energy Secretary James Watkins will develop a detailed
national energy strategy in the coming months to deal with future
energy requirements.
   Watkins was to present a general outline of the administration's
energy policy at a congressional hearing. It is expected to include
emphasis on expanded reliance on nuclear power and a call for more
oil exploration along coastal areas.
   In signing the natural gas decontrol bill, which was passed by
Congress earlier this year, the president signaled the end to 35
years of price control on the fuel.
   Full natural gas decontrol is not expected to affect retail
prices significantly because most gas already is selling below the
official ceilings. However, critics maintain that full decontrol
will set the stage for price increases in the 1990s.
   The administration's energy strategy was expected to include
renewed efforts to win public acceptance for an expanded nuclear
power industry and a call for more oil exploration, including along
coastal areas.
   Offshore oil drilling has raised widespread concerns because of
the devastating damage and pollution caused by the massive oil
spill from the Exxon Valdez tanker in Alaska's Prince William Sound
in March.
   Legislation is advancing in Congress that would extend a
moratorium on such drilling to vast offshore stretches from New
England to Alaska. The Bush administration has opposed any such
moratorium extension.
   Shortly after he became energy secretary, Watkins ordered the
department to develop an ``action plan'' for dealing with expected
energy needs, including more accurate estimates on future energy
requirements.
   Calls for a revised national energy policy have intensified amid
falling U.S. petroleum production and increasing demand. At the
same time, there has been increasing pressure from
environmentalists to curb the use of fossil fuels because they are
a chief contributor to global warming.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore has said the department had
no preconceived notions about the focus of a national energy
policy. But he suggested an effort would be made to revive the
nuclear industry by making nuclear power more acceptable, and that
oil companies could be given more latitude to explore for oil on
federal lands or in promising offshore areas.
   Moore acknowledged the department must assemble more in-depth
information on energy needs that is viewed as credible by producers
and consumers alike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0278 </DOCNO>
