<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-26 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices rose while corn and soybean
futures closed narrowly mixed Wednesday in quiet trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts attributed most of the buying in all the markets to
perceptions that prices were exaggeratedly low after recent
declines.
   Selling in the corn and soybean pits was based largely on ideas
that recent rains in the Midwest had improved crop conditions.
   Gerald Zusel, manager of exchange floor operations with Balfour
Maclaine Corp., a futures brokerage firm, said that with more than
half the corn crop now past the sensitive pollination phase,
traders had begun to shift their focus to the soybean crop, which
is nearing its critical flowering and pod-setting stage.
   ``It'll be pretty difficult to damage the corn crop from here on
in but weather can still be an important factor for the beans,''
Zusel said. ``If we get normal-type temperatures and fair coverage
by showers on a weekly basis over the next four to five weeks, the
bean crop will be made, too.''
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.88\ a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to { cent higher with September at $2.29\ a bushel;
oats were { cent lower to 1\ cents higher with September at $1.42}
a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher with August
at $6.62 a bushel.
</TEXT>
