<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Goodyear     07-26 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Goodyear,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goodyear Second-Quarter Profits Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. said Wednesday its
second-quarter earnings tumbled 80 percent primarily because of
losses from the sale of its South Africa unit and unused pipe
inventories.
   Goodyear said it made $27.1 million, or 47 cents a share, in the
quarter ended June 30. That compared with earnings of $134.9
million, or $2.35 per share, for the same 1988 period.
   Second-quarter sales rose about 1 percent to $2.81 billion from
last year's $2.79 billion.
   Goodyear said after-tax loss provisions totaling $95 million
were responsible for the downturn. The provisions included $43
million in the sale of its unit in racially segregated South Africa
and $48.3 million for the sale of unused pipe held by its All
American Pipeline subsidiary.
   Sales of the South African subsidiary and the unused pipe are
expected to be completed during the third quarter, the company said.
   Cash proceeds of $41 million for the South Africa unit and a
pipe sale price of $70 million had been expected, Goodyear said in
a statement.
   Goodyear Chairman Tom H. Barrett said the company would focus on
``cost reduction and profit improvement programs as well as adjust
production plans, mostly in relation to the extended shutdown in
automotive scheduling.''
   For the first six months of 1989, Goodyear reported earnings of
$121.6 million, or $2.11 a share, on sales of $5.45 billion. That
compared with earnings of $230.2 million, or $4.02 a share, on
sales of $5.33 billion in the first half of 1988.
</TEXT>
