<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SmithKlineMerger     07-26 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SmithKline Merger,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>SmithKline Shareholders Approve Merger with British Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beecham, a new international
pharmaceutical firm, was created Wednesday after SmithKline Beckman
Corp. shareholders overwhelmingly approved a merger with Beecham
Group PLC of Britain.
   ``We have a unique opportunity to take the strengths and
traditions of both companies and create a new global competitor in
the very first rank of the health care industry,'' said Henry
Wendt, SmithKline's chief executive officer and chairman of the
merged company.
   With combined sales exceeding $6 billion, SmithKline Beecham
becomes the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company after
Merck &amp; Co.
   About 59 percent of SmithKline's 126,906,109 million outstanding
shares voted on the merger proposal, with 99 percent supporting it,
although a few stockholders were disappointed that the new
company's headquarters would be in London and future annual
meetings would be held there.
   Wendt said, however, that satellite meetings would be held in
Philadelphia, which will remain the center of American operations,
``so we are not leaving Philadelphia, we are gaining London.''
   Beecham stockholders approved the merger in June.
   In the merger, each SmithKline Beckman shareholder will receive
a package of five common shares and one preferred share of
SmithKline Beecham, plus a half share of Allergan, one-eighth share
of Beckman Instruments and a $5.50 dividend.
   SmithKline Beecham's leading consumer products will be the
antacid Tums, the over-the-counter cold medicine Contac and throat
lozenge Sucrets.
   The company also will have three of the 10 most widely
prescribed drugs in the United States _ Tagamet, the leading ulcer
medication; Dyazide for hypertension and high blood pressure; and
Augmentin, an antibiotic that Beecham had been marketing.
</TEXT>
