<SECOND>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries, 1st Ld - Writethru,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Hughes Electronics, EDS Up; GMAC Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBs 4th graf pvs, GMAC said... to RESTORE full first reference
to General Motors Acceptance Corp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising interest costs cut second-quarter earnings
at General Motors Corp.'s financing subsidiary, while the
automaker's two other major subsidiaries reported increases for the
period, the companies said Wednesday.
   Sales of communications satellite services pushed earnings to
new highs at GM Hughes Electronics Corp. Demand for data processing
services by banks and other customers boosted results at Electronic
Data Systems Corp.
   The parent company's earnings report was expected Thursday.
   The finance subsidiary, General Motors Acceptance Corp., said
net income from its financing, insurance and mortgage operations
was $268.6 million for the three months ended June 30, nearly a 20
percent drop from $333.9 million in the second quarter of 1988.
   GMAC said its financing and leasing business in the United
States increased 27 percent in volume from the earlier period, but
interest costs soared. The company said its average cost of
borrowings worldwide was 9.53 percent for the quarter, up from 7.94
percent a year earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, GMAC reported consolidated
net income of $625 million, down from $688.3 million for the first
half of 1988.
   GMAC had total assets of $102.8 billion June 30, up from $99.9
billion a year earlier, spokesman John Andrews said.
   GM Hughes Electronics said its telecommunications growth
included sales of satellite services to three operations: a joint
venture of HBO and Turner Broadcasting System; ESPN, the nation's
largest cable network; and CBS.
   The company reported second-quarter earnings of $240 million, or
60 cents a share of General Motors Class H stock, up from $180
million, or 50 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1988.
   The per-share earnings set a second-quarter record, the company
said. The previous record was in the year-earlier period. GM Class
H stock is an issue with earnings based on GM Hughes Electronics'
performance.
   The second-quarter earnings a year earlier were boosted by
one-time gains from stock sales. Earnings from operations
comparable to 1989 would have been $180 million, or 45 cents a
share, spokesman Bruce McCristal said.
   GM Hughes Electronics said second-quarter revenue was $2.88
billion for the quarter, up slightly from $2.87 billion a year
earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, the company reported
earnings of $450.4 million, or $1.11 a share, on revenue of $5.89
billion, compared with earnings of $453 million, of $1.13 a share,
on revenue of $5.54 billion in the first half of 1988.
   The six-month figures in 1988 were boosted by one-time gains
from the second-quarter stock sales and a first-quarter accounting
change, McCristal said. Without those changes, comparable operating
earnings for 1988 would have been $366 million, or 90 cents a
share, he said.
   EDS said its second-quarter net income was $104.9 million, or 87
cents a share of GM Class E Stock, on revenue of $1.38 billion, up
from $95.7 million, or 78 cents a share, on revenue of $1.20
billion in the second quarter of 1988. GM Class E stock earnings
are based on EDS performance.
   For the first six months of the year, EDS reported net income of
$204.9 million, or $1.69 a share, on revenue of $2.66 billion. That
was up from $184.8 billion, or $1.51 a share, on revenue of $2.32
billion for the first half of 1988.
</TEXT>
