<FIRST>u f PM-IBMOffer 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Offer, 1st Ld-Writethru,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Offers Baltimore $700,000 to Allow 26-Story Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to update with city approval, CORRECT that
standards were not zoning restrictions, picking up at the 5th graf previous.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city gave final approval today for IBM
Corp. to build a 26-story office building on the desirable Inner
Harbor section, where buildings were limited to 17 stories, in
exchange for a payment of $700,000.
   IBM also agreed to maintain public spaces at the two-acre site,
a commitment valued at $300,000 a year, and donate $45,000 to a
fund to maintain public art.
   The final approval came from the city Board of Estimates, which
had to approve any change in the restrictions.
   The City Council passed a bill last month that would lift the
current 175-foot height limit in the area that was part of the
standards established under a urban renewal plan in the late 1960s,
said Albert M. Copp, president of Center City-Inner Harbor
Development Inc. The non-profit company handles development
management for the city of Baltimore.
   The $50 million office tower would house the expanded
headquarters of T. Rowe Price Associates as well as IBM's Baltimore
offices and other office space.
   City officials said negotiations began recently between IBM and
the city because the price of the tract, $1.42 million, when the
city sold it to IBM in 1970, reflected restrictions placed on the
site. If the restrictions are lifted the value of the land
increases, and the city deserves more for it, city officials said.
   Lessening zoning restrictions in exchange for cash or public
amenities is an arrangement used in many major cities. It has come
under fire particularly in New York, where critics say the benefits
do not compensate for the problems caused by overbuilding.
</TEXT>
