<FIRST>r f AM-Dunkin'Donuts     07-26 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkin' Donuts,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dunkin' Donuts Gets Injunction Against Canadian Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS HOPKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday temporarily blocked a
hostile $305 million takeover bid for Dunkin' Donuts, saying the
Canadian bidders failed to disclose prior securities law violations.
   U.S. District Judge Edward F. Harrington ordered D.D.
Acquisition Corp., a partnership formed by Kingsbridge Capital
Group, a subsidiary of Unicorp Canada Corp., and Cara Operations
Ltd., to give Dunkin' Donuts shareholders a revised purchase offer.
   The judge also ordered Unicorp to provide information from the
Ontario Securities Commission staff saying the company had violated
Canadian securities regulations in a previous unrelated takeover
offer.
   Unicorp, a Toronto-based real estate, banking and energy firm,
owns 12 percent of Dunkin' Donuts' stock. It joined with Cara, a
food services company, in the $43-a-share tender offer.
   The judge also ordered the partnership to delay buying any more
Dunkin' Donuts stock until the revised purchase offer had
circulated among shareholders for 10 business days.
   Dunkin' Donuts Chairman Robert M. Rosenberg issued a letter to
stockholders Wednesday advising them to disregard the tender offer.
   ``Any drastic change in ownership, in our opinion, will threaten
and-or destroy this delicate balance and jeopardize our future
prospects,'' Rosenberg said in the letter.
   Eric Evans, associate director of Kingsbridge, played down the
significance of the injunction, saying the company would either
appeal the decision or provide the required information.
   He said the takeover bid cited by the judge _ for Canada's
second-largest utility corporation about five years ago _ was not a
violation of Canadian securities law.
   Evans said shareholders ``weren't treated fairly'' initially in
the deal, but added: ``We still deny that there were any
violations. Things run differently here.''
</TEXT>
