<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar sank Wednesday in response to more
signs that the Federal Reserve was loosening credit and speculation
of continued sluggish economic growth.
   The dollar lost about 1{ Japanese yen and 1{ West German
pfennigs while the cost of a British pound in dollars rose 2 cents.
   The Federal Reserve failed for a second day to drain reserves
from the banking system, an indication it was seeking to lower
interest rates and stimulate the economy.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, fell sharply to 8{ percent from 91-16 percent on Tuesday.
However, dealers said the sharp drop was mainly the result of
window-dressing by major banks at the end of the two-week
settlement period, when they report their balance sheets to the Fed.
   There was also speculation that Thursday's report on
second-quarter gross national product, and subsequent reports,
would confirm evidence of slow growth, said John Lynam, a vice
president in the New York office of Security Pacific National Bank.
   Britain's pound sterling was boosted by a report that the
nation's trade gap grew less than expected in June.
   The pound climbed in London to $1.6455, compared to $1.6255 late
Tuesday. In New York the pound rose further to $1.6585 from $1.6385
on Tuesday.
   In Tokyo the dollar fell to 141.43 Japanese yen from 142.35 yen
on Tuesday. Later in Europe the dollar closed at 140.50 yen. In New
York the dollar fell to 140.08 yen from 141.55 on Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates in New York compared with late Tuesday's
rates included: 1.8680 West German marks, down from 1.8835; 1.6060
Swiss francs, down from 1.6202; 1.1837 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1874; 6.3255 French francs, down from 6.3830; and 1,342 Italian
lire, down from 1,357.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
1.6115 Swiss francs, down from 1.6300; 6.3475 French francs, down
from 6.4265; 2.1190 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1348; 1,352.50
Italian lire, down from 1,364.00; 1.1872 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1876.
   Gold traded at a bid price of $373.25 a troy ounce in London
late Wednesday, up from $372.25 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, gold finished at $374.50, up from $371.25 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 97 cents to a closing bid of
$372.44.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $374.90 an ounce from $373.70 on Tuesday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $374.10 an
ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $373 an ounce on Tuesday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.22 a troy
ounce, up from $5.20 bid late Tuesday. On New York's Comex silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $5.224 an ounce from $5.208
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
