<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-26 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Slips To 5{-Month Low As Bearishness Builds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices slipped to a 5{-month low on the New
York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, the fourth straight day of
declining prices in a market weakened by slack demand for gasoline
and a dearth of bullish factors.
   On other markets, precious metals advanced; grains and soybeans
were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 24 cents lower to 3
cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $18.30
a barrel, the lowest near-month settlement since March 7. Heating
oil futures finished .07 cent to .17 cent higher with August at
49.49 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .43 cent to .84 cent
lower with August at 51.34 cents a gallon.
   Tuesday's weekly American Petroleum Institute report, which
showed a 1.4-million-barrel drawdown in U.S. supplies of crude, was
initially perceived as slightly supportive.
   But analysts said closer examination of the report showed an
increase of more than 3 million barrels in the Gulf Coast region,
an indication that demand for gasoline is not keeping pace with
crude-oil production.
   The report also showed overall gasoline production running at a
rate of 7.3 million barrels a day.
   ``That's a lot, especially given that demand seems to be
slacking off a bit,'' said Jerry Samuels, an analyst in New York
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The factors that contributed to a sharp rise in oil prices
earlier this year _ OPEC production cutbacks, tightening supplies
and labor tensions in the North Sea oilfields _ have faded or been
overshadowed by the downturn in gasoline demand, and traders are
increasingly prone to selling as the market moves lower.
   Crude oil for September delivery traded as low as $18.27 on
Tuesday. Analysts said a drop below $18.25 would likely spark a new
round of heavy selling.
   Gold and silver futures advanced slightly on New York's
Commodity Exchange in reaction to a weaker dollar. Gold settled 90
cents to $1.20 higher with August at $375 a troy ounce; silver was
1.5 cents to 1.6 cents higher with September at $5.275 a troy ounce.
   Wheat futures prices rose while corn and soybean futures
finished narrowly mixed in quiet trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Analysts attributed much of the buying to perceptions that
prices were exaggeratedly low after recent declines.
   Selling in the corn and soybean pits was based largely on ideas
that recent rains in the Midwest had improved crop conditions.
   Gerald Zusel, manager of exchange floor operations with Balfour
Maclaine Corp., a futures brokerage firm, said that with more than
half the corn crop now past the sensitive pollination phase,
traders had begun to shift their focus to the soybean crop, which
is nearing its critical flowering and pod-setting stage.
   ``It'll be pretty difficult to damage the corn crop from here on
in but weather can still be an important factor for the beans,''
Zusel said.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 6 cents higher with September at $3.88\
a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to } cent higher with September at
$2.29{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent lower with September
at $1.42} a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to } cent higher
with August at $6.61} a bushel.
   Pork belly futures made new life-of-contract lows across the
board on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, reflecting lower prices
for fresh bellies, deteriorating demand and increased production.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent lower to .40 cent higher with
August at 72.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to
.30 cent higher with August at 83.52 cents a pound; live hogs were
.18 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August at 45.92 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .33 cent to .85 cent lower with
August at 27.10 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
