<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Viper Bjt   07-26 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Viper, Bjt,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Snake in Chrysler's Future?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. executives and
engineers are wondering if there is a Viper in the company's
future, an executive said Wednesday.
   A key element in whether the Viper _ a muscular two-seater
sports car _ ever sees the showroom floor could be a new
computer-aided design system, which Chrysler says slashes the time
between design and assembly.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker plans to announce within six months
if it will produce the Viper, which snared a lot of attention on
this winter's car-show circuit.
   The car, a low, sleek sports car billed as having a big V-10
engine, could come to production in as little as a year and a half,
said Thomas Gale, Chrysler's vice president for product design.
   The Viper introduced at the winter auto shows was a devoid of
the pricey electronics loaded into other two-seaters such as the
Nissan 300ZX. Mazda recently used a similar concept for its
low-priced, limited production Miata convertible, which has been
met with torrid demand.
   Gale supports the Viper. Chrysler Motors Corp. President Robert
Lutz wants to build it and Chairman Lee Iacocca said in a recent
interview that he leaned toward producing the car.
   ``Even the bean-counters here are saying we've got to find a way
to build it,'' Iacocca said.
   But there's a roadblock to the Viper _ timing.
   Chrysler is developing an array of engines and a new car
platform for the 1990s. But before then, Chrysler officials are
predicting a softening of the auto market.
   That could force Chrysler and other automakers to look more
toward their bread-and-butter cars and away from anything exotic,
like the Viper.
   One way to pare costs of developing a new vehicle like the Viper
and to make it more attractive to executives is to cut the time
between the drawing board and assembly line.
   Gale said Wednesday a newly installed computer-driven design
tool could slice design time from about a year to eight months.
While it was impossible to tell now, it could cut as much as 25
percent off the time to bring a totally new car to market, dropping
the period to three years, he said.
   The tool, called the conceptual design and rendering system,
began work at Chrysler's studios late last month. Its first project
was the Viper.
   Like other computers, the system gives a designer a computer
generated, three-dimensional depiction of a car. The roof line or
the shape of windows and doors can be changed on the screen, saving
modeling time.
   The difference with the new system, Gale said, is that it also
includes specific mathematical measurements that can be translated
by a machine used to cut a full-size clay model.
   The mathematical information also can be sent to other computers
in engineering and manufacturing divisions, where feasibility
studies can be performed quickly and changes can be recommended.
   For example, if an engineer looks at a design and determines
that it won't work because of aerodynamics, the computer model can
be returned to the design studio for alterations.
   The system was developed by Evans &amp; Sutherland of Salt Lake
City. The company has talked about the system to other companies,
including Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp., said E&amp;S
Chairman David C. Evans.
   ``In the past, it's been a little like a relay race,'' Gale said
of the process, in which the designer gave plans to an engineer who
altered them and sent them to a manufacturer to determine if
tooling could be made to assemble the vehicle.
   ``We're changing the way the race is run,'' Gale said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-XeroxPaper Adv30   07-26 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Xerox Paper, Adv 30,0860</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, July 30 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Xerox Sells a Lot of Copiers, Even More Paper</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next time the office copier breaks,
jams or refuses to cooperate, pause a moment before delivering that
swift kick to the machine's side.
   You may want to aim your frustration at the paper, the more
likely cause of your grief.
   The paper that goes into the copier, and some times doesn't come
out, probably is responsible for more repair visits by copier
technicians than anything else.
   ``It's the biggest problem because it's the one thing no one has
control over,'' said Robert Sostilio, a copier industry analyst at
Dataquest Inc., a San Jose, Calif.-based market research company.
   He said virtually every copier manufacturer sells its own brand
of paper to ensure smooth copier performance. Dozens of other
companies also peddle copier paper.
   ``The problem is what's good in Miami may not be good in
Minnesota. And what's good on a machine that makes eight copies a
minute may be miserable on a machine that makes 100 copies a
minute,'' Sostilio said.
   Enter Xerox Corp., the leading seller of copiers, and its Paper
Technology Division, where paper scientists work at engineering
what the company claims is the finest copier paper in the world.
   They expose paper to oppressive humidity, mile-high altitudes
and meticulous examination. They say things like, ``There's a whole
anatomy to a piece of paper.''
   Xerox is the leading distributor of cut-sheet copy paper and the
only company that sells copy paper worldwide. Last year, the
company sold more than 600,000 tons.
   However, the company's stronghold is under attack, partly
because of new technology that Xerox actually invented in 1977.
   It's called the laser printer, a machine that, in many ways, is
similar to a copier.
   A laser printer uses a concentrated beam of light to convert
electronic data into a printed document. A copier uses a flash of
light, mirrors and lenses to reproduce an existing document.
   Many paper suppliers and copier makers have started selling
paper, at a slightly higher price, that's designed specifically for
use in laser printers, and Xerox has taken exception.
   ``You don't need special paper for a laser printer. That's not
how people should be making their decisions about what paper to
use,'' said Stephen Galloway, business planning manager for Xerox's
paper operation.
   The company recently redesigned storage cartons, package
wrappers and ream-end labels to emphasize their multi-purpose
applications. The package now says, ``The most versatile paper you
can use, from copying to electronic printing.''
   ``You can use any one of our papers in any machine. That's what
we want people to know,'' Galloway said. ``So if you're sending out
an inter-office memo and printing it on a laser prnter, there's no
reason to use more expensive paper. Use basic copy paper.''
   Xerox says it goes to extraordinary lengths to ensure paper
quality.
   Paper-checkers riffle through sample reams of shipments from
paper plants around the world, scrutinizing possible defects, dirt
and dust.
   Xerox uses all kinds of paper manufacturers, from a small mill
in Portugal to some of the largest mills in Japan and the United
States, and every supplier must meet the same specifications.
   ``Probably the most elegant paper is made in Switzerland. Egypt
probably produces the poorest locally produced paper,'' said
Dominic Sherony, manager of paper and special products.
   The company has about 50 major suppliers and hundreds of minor
suppliers, who must undergo an approval process that can take up to
three years.
   Paper scientists like Gary Chapin and John Viavattine use all
kinds of measuring devices to determine how smooth it is.
   ``Unless you analytically examine a piece of our paper, you
probably wouldn't know why it's the optimal paper for copiers,''
said Viavattine, as he turned on a machine he designed that
collects dust from cartons of paper.
   Paper dust in copiers is the latest ``paper problem'' Viavattine
and Chapin have been trying to solve.
   Because today's copiers can spit out 135 copies a minute, and in
many places they're running around the clock, Xerox has found that
the accumulation of dust has become a major problem.
   ``Xerox spends more money on service calls just going out and
vacuuming out machines. All because of dust,'' said Viavattine.
   The company is examining ways of improving the way its suppliers
cut the sheets of paper at the mill as one way of trimming dust
from a ream of paper.
   The paper laboratory also includes devices that can peel four
very thin layers from a single sheet of paper, measure the
roughness of a piece of paper or what kind of wood it's made from.
   ``You probably didn't know that paper has a top and a bottom,''
Viavattine said. ``But it does and that's important. That's why we
put arrows on the package to make sure people load the paper
correctly.''
</TEXT>
