<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1753EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-26 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures prices resumed their recent
slide Wednesday, putting downward pressure on the crude market,
while heating oil futures rose.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for
unleaded gasoline fell another 0.73 cent to close at 51.34 cents a
gallon after falling 1.09 cents on Tuesday. The September contract
lost 0.84 cent and contracts for delivery latr in the year posted
similar declines.
   West Texas Intermediate for September delivery slid 24 cents to
finish at $18.30 a barrel after a drop of 20 cents in the previous
session. Oil prices have declined steadily in the last seven
sessions, with the near-term contract falling $2.15 since July 17.
   Contracts for delivery after September had smaller declines.
   Domestic heating oil for August delivery, meanwhile, rose 0.7
cent to 49.49 cents a gallon, and other contracts also gained.
   Gasoline prices began deteriorating last week after an American
Petroleum Institute report that showed inventories were building,
reflecting a softening in demand, according to analysts.
   Although this week's lower API statistics were perceived by many
traders as bullish for the market, selling of gasoline futures
remained strong.
   ``The market didn't like gasoline even with with lower stocks,''
said Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
``Even though they were down they were still well above a year ago,
although last year they were at an all-time low. The perception in
the market is that they still might be too high.''
   Gasoline supplies fell by 1.5 million barrels to 221.3 million
barrels in the week ending July 21, according to the API report.
Inventories remained 13.4 million barrels ahead of last year,
however.
   The API report also showed crude oil stocks fell 1.4 million
barrels to 330.5 million in the week and were down by 19.2 million
barrels over last year.
   Heating oil inventories were down by 800,000 barrels to 109.4
million for the week and by 7.8 million from last year.
   Andrew Lebow, senior broker and analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc., said falling gasoline prices continued
to put pressure on the crude market. The API report, he said, was
considered neutral for the market.
   In addition, he said, reports that some members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries are still producing
above expectations, are keeping crude prices soft.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
