<DOCNO> AP890726-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1812EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAW-Smyrna Bjt   07-26 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW-Smyrna, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Vote Goes Beyond Nissan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Autoworkers voting Wednesday in Tennessee were
deciding not only whether or not the United Auto Workers union
would represent them, but also the course of the union's broader
future, according to labor experts.
   The vote at Nissan Motor Corp.'s car and truck assembly plant in
Smyrna, Tenn., was viewed as critical for the union, which was
attempting to organize a plant in a right-to-work state.
   It also may foreshadow the results of the drive by the UAW _
which has seen membership shrink by 33 percent in the last 10 years
_ to organize the widespread, mostly unorganized automobile
supplier industry.
   ``What's at stake isn't 2,400 Nissan workers, but rather all the
parts that are coming into that plant, which also go to Ford, GM
and Chrysler plants,'' said Harley Shaiken of the University of
California in San Diego. ``A loss here is going to make it very
difficult.
   ``If they win, they are well positioned to take on the other
transplants and to take on the nonunion auto suppliers,
particularly the Japanese suppliers,'' said Shaiken, who has
watched the UAW for years.
   Dan Cornfield, a Vanderbilt University professor of sociology
who focuses on labor relations, also said the broader effect of the
vote could be among the supplier industries.
   A UAW victory, Cornfield said, ``could possibly lead to further
unionization of other workers, especially the supplier plants, and
in other industries.''
   It's not the first time that the UAW has tried to organize a
Japanese ``transplant,'' a U.S. assembly plant operated by a
subsidiary of a Japanese automaker.
   In March 1986, on the eve of a federal hearing to set a date for
a representation election at Honda Motor Corp.'s Marysville, Ohio,
plant, the UAW withdrew its election petition.
   ``They pulled it prior to it coming to a vote because they
didn't want an embarrassing vote,'' Shaiken said. ``The Honda
campaign had some problems.
   ``Here (with Smyrna), they've apparently run an effective
campaign.''
   In addition to the Honda plant in Marysville, the UAW still has
not organized Toyota Motor Corp.'s assembly plant in Georgetown, Ky.
   The union represents workers at Mazda Motor Corp.'s plant in
Flat Rock, Mich., south of Detroit; the New United Motor
Manufacturing Inc. plant in Fremont, Calif., a joint venture
between Toyota and General Motors Corp.; and the Diamond-Star
Motors Corp. plant in Normal, Ill., a joint venture between
Chrysler Corp. and Mitsubishi Motor Corp.
   Each of the Big Three automakers has been organized for years.
   Intensifying the importance of the transplants is their growth
in the U.S. auto industry.
   Nissan has announced an expansion of its Smyrna facility that
will put production at about 400,000 vehicles a year by 1992. Honda
is opening a new assembly plant in East Liberty, Ohio, later this
year which will add capacity for about 150,000 more cars. It can
make about 365,000 vehicles a year at Marysville.
   In 1991, Ford Motor Co. and Nissan expect to begin producing a
minivan at a joint venture in Avon Lake, Ohio.
   If Honda sells its entire capacity in the United States and
Chrysler's sales continue to fall, Shaiken said, ``Honda may tend
to displace Chrysler in the early 1990s as the No. 3 automaker.
   ``Imagine a non-union Chrysler,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
