<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1823EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dutch-BankMerger     07-26 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dutch-Bank Merger,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biggest Dutch Bank to Buy Exchange Bancorp of Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. subsidiary of the largest Dutch banking
firm said Wednesday it had agreed to buy Chicago's sixth-largest
banking concern for $420 million.
   The proposed acquisition of Exchange Bancorp Inc. by LaSalle
National Corp. would give LaSalle's parent, Algemene Bank Nederland
NV, a greater share of the small- and mid-size U.S. corporate
banking market and would expand its retail operations in this
country.
   Chicago-based LaSalle National said it would pay $420 million in
cash for all common stock and convertible preferred stock of
Exchange, which owns four banks in the Chicago area and has about
$3 billion in assets.
   LaSalle owns five community banks in the Chicago area and has
assets of $3.2 billion.
   The acquisition is subject to the signing of a definitive
agreement and the approval of Exchange shareholders and regulatory
agencies.
   ``This is the ideal marriage of two financial institutions,''
said Harrison F. Tempest, president and chief executive of LaSalle
National and manager of Algemene's North American operations.
   ``It creates a Chicago banking group that will be in an enviable
position to meet the challengs of the 1990s,'' Tempest said in a
prepared statement.
   Algemene, based in Amsterdam, is the world's 43rd largest bank
holding company with assets of more than $85 billion. It has made
no secret of its plans to grow in North America.
   Acquisition of Exchange Bancorp will boost the Dutch company's
U.S. assets to more than $13 billion. Algemene also has offices in
Atlanta, Boston, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, New York, Pittsburgh,
San Francisco and Seattle, and in 43 countries.
   Exchange Bancorp is controlled by a management group that owns
more than 45 percent of its outstanding shares. The balance is
owned by 1,500 shareholders and 30 major financial institutions.
   Jon Rau, currently president of Exchange, would become president
of the combined Chicago-area banks, which will keep the LaSalle
National name and become Illinois' fifth largest bank-holding
company.
   ``By merging the two groups, we are creating a major force in
the commercial banking market,'' Rau said. ``The combination of our
market shares in the Chicago-area middle market will put LaSalle at
the very top of of this market.''
</TEXT>
