<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Airlines     07-26 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Airlines,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Southwest Airlines Report Earnings Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines and Southwest Airlines reported sharply
higher second-quarter earnings Wednesday, attributing the results
to stronger passenger traffic at the fast-growing carriers.
   America West, based in Tempe, Ariz., reported earnings of $3.03
million or 14 cents a share, an 18.4 percent gain over the $2.56
million or 15 cents a share reported a year earlier. The company
had fewer shares outstanding in 1988.
   Second-quarter revenues totaled $238.6 million vs. $191.8
million, a 24 percent gain.
   For the first six months of 1989, America West reported earnings
of $13.1 million, or 64 cents per common share, on revenues of
$471.7 million, compared with a loss of $13.7 million on revenues
of $362.6 million in the first six months of 1988.
   At Dallas-based Southwest, increased traffic helped overcome the
expense of opening two new terminals to boost quarterly earnings to
$19.24 million or 64 cents a share, a 27.2 percent gain over the
$15.13 million or 48 cents a share a year earlier. Revenues totaled
$263.65 million vs. $216.93 million, a 21.5 percent gain.
   In the first half of 1989, Southwest earned $38.88 million, or
$1.28 per share, on revenues of $493.03 million, compared with
$15.29 million, or 49 cents per share, on $395.5 million in the
first half of 1988.
</TEXT>
