<FIRST>u f AM-Disney 1stLd-Writethru f0233 07-26 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0233,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Stock Up Sharply On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The stock ...,' to restore dropped word and
fix typo.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. stock rose sharply
Wednesday amid speculation that the entertainment kingdom might be
the next takeover target of Paramount Communications Inc.
   Disney would not comment other than to say it had no information
to explain the rise.
   The stock, up more than $7 at one point from Tuesday's close,
finished up $4.75 at $109.12{ a share in New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   A group led by Sid Bass, one of the Fort Worth, Texas, family of
investors, owns about 16 percent of Disney's shares, but that
holding has been described as long-term and amicable. There was no
comment from the Bass group Wednesday.
   The Bass family in 1984 spent $333 million and took a 25 percent
share of Disney stock to help the company ward off hostile takeover
attempts by financiers Saul Steinberg of New York and Irwin Jacobs
of Minneapolis.
   However, there has been market speculation that the Bass group
might sell its holdings to Paramount, which on Monday dropped its
$12.2 billion hostile bid for Time Inc.
   New York-based Paramount, which built itself into a media and
entertainment conglomerate largely through acquisitions, indicated
Monday that it would pursue other acquisitions or ventures after
losing a Delaware court battle seeking to block Time's acquisition
of Warner Communications Inc.
   But some analysts consider Disney, which in May reported its
profit for the first half of the fiscal year was up 35 percent at
$297.3 million, an unlikely target for a takeover bid.
   Considered by some to be a more likely trigger for the
speculation was anticipation of a third quarter report that
analysts estimate would show earnings of $1.40 a share, compared
with $1.20 a share for the same period last year.
</TEXT>
