<DOCNO> AP890726-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PatentThefts     07-26 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Patent Thefts,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patent Microfilms Missing From University Libraries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials are investigating the
theft of thousands of microfilm copies of U.S. patents from at
least a dozen research universities, officials said Wednesday.
   Librarians at the University of Massachusetts, Virginia
Commonwealth University and the University of Maryland first
discovered parts of their files missing in late June, university
officials said.
   About a dozen FBI offices across the United States are looking
into the thefts, said Paul Cavanagh, a spokesman for the FBI's
Boston office.
   ``One of the things we are still considering is whether a
violation of federal statutes is involved,'' he said.
   The missing files fall between the years 1968 through 1988, said
Prudence Adler, a spokeswoman for the Washington-based Association
for Research Libraries.
   ``There's a very deliberate pattern. They are not going in and
repeating what has been stolen previously,'' she said. ``Each
institution is losing different files.''
   Ms. Adler said the files, which are open to the public, are
designed to help individual inventors and corporations check
whether they are duplicating previous lines of research.
   ``The question we all have is why someone would steal this
material,'' said Prudence Adler, a spokeswoman for the
Washington-based Association for Research Libraries.
   Through last week, at least 2,000 reels of microfilm have been
reported missing from the dozen universities, she said. A 20-year
collection of patent records from 1968 through 1988 consists of
3,126 reels of microfilm and costs about $100,000, she said.
   Other schools missing patent microfilms include Rice University,
the University of New Mexico, the University of Utah, Georgia Tech,
Texas A&amp;M, the University of Texas, the University of Idaho, Ohio
State University and the University of Michigan, she said.
</TEXT>
