<DOCNO> AP890726-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Oil 1stLd-Writethru   07-26 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil, 1st Ld - Writethru,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Qtr. Profit Down At Texaco, Up At Occidental, Shell, Maxus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, Maxus Energy...to CORRECT earnings per
share, add detail on preferred stock payment. Picks up final graf, Dallas-based
Maxus...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. reported a 21 percent drop in its second-quarter
earnings Wednesday due partly to lower production and refinery
slowdowns, while Shell Oil Co. and Occidental Petroleum Corp. said
their profits rose during the period.
   Higher crude oil prices benefited all three companies as did a
steep rise in gasoline and other oil product sales prices. But
those gains were partially offset by dwindling production.
   Texaco's net income fell to $366 million, or $1.39 a share, from
$464 million, or $1.91 a share, in the comparable 1988 period.
Second-quarter 1988 results included a restructuring gain of $225
million, or 92 cents a share, from the sale of its West German
subsidiary.
   Quarterly revenue declined 10 percent to $8.4 billion from $9.3
billion a year ago.
   Occidental Petroleum's earnings rose about 4 percent to $80
million, or 29 cents a share, from $77 million, or 34 cents a share
a year earlier. The decline in per-share earnings reflected an
increase in the average number of common shares outstanding, the
company said.
   Occidental said quarterly earnings reflected extraordinary
losses of $4 million in 1989 and $10 million in 1988 from the early
payment of debt.
   Revenue rose 7 percent, to $5.1 billion from $4.7 billion in the
year-earlier quarter.
   Shell said second quarter earnings soared 61 percent to $440
million from $274 million a year ago. Revenue totaled $5.9 billion
vs. $5.4 billion, a 9 percent gain. The company does not release
per-share figures because it is a subsidiary of Royal Dutch Shell
based in the Netherlands, which reports its consolidated earnings
separately.
   Higher crude prices benefited Texaco's exploration and
production business, while a steep rise in gasoline prices early in
the quarter helped refining and marketing businesses.
   But those gains were offset partly by declines in foreign
exploration and production earnings stemming from last year's
platform explosion in the North Sea and the sale of Texaco
subsidiaries in Canada and West Germany.
   Occidental's Piper Alpha oil platform off Aberdeen, Scotland
exploded and burned July 6, 1988 in the North Sea's worst oil
disaster. The platform was destroyed and 167 men were killed.
Texaco and Occidental were two of four companies operating the
field, where production has been delayed since the accident.
   Texaco also said its refining margins were reduced by a
softening of gasoline prices toward the close of the quarter and
scheduled maintenance at three refineries.
   For the first six months of the year, Texaco's net income more
than doubled to $1.821 billion, or $7.19 a share, from $734
million, or $3.02 a share, a year earlier. First-half results
included a gain of $1.19 billion from the sale of its Texaco Canada
Inc. subsidiary.
   Revenue in the six months rose to $18.1 billion from $17.98
billion a year ago.
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., is the nation's third
largest oil concern behind Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp.
   Occidental, based in Los Angeles, said the North Sea accident
reduced its exploration and production earnings, but that was
partially offset by higher crude oil prices.
   Occidental said coal division earnings tumbled to $1 million
from $3 million due to strikes by miners in Kentucky and Tennessee,
who joined a wildcat sympathy strike in sympathy with a walkout
against Pittston Coal Group's operations in Virginia and West
Virginia.
   Net income in the first half declined 23 percent to $147
million, or 53 cents a share, from $190 million, or 85 cents a
share, a year ago.
   Revenue rose 11 percent to $10.2 billion from $9.2 billion in
the 1988 period.
   Houston-based Shell, the nation's sixth-largest oil company,
said first-half earnings totaled $801 million, up 21 percent from
$663 million a year ago. Revenue rose to $11 billion, 5 percent
higher than $10.5 billion in the 1988 period.
   Strong demand and higher sales prices for chemical products
produced record earnings in the chemicals division, while an
increase in foreign crude oil production helped offset declines in
domestic production, Shell said.
   Maxus Energy Corp. reported net income of $3.6 million in the
second quarter compared with a loss of $9.6 million a year earlier.
Earnings per share for the second quarter amounted to less than one
cent due to an $11.7 million preferred stock dividend. Revenue
slipped to $149.9 million from $151.6 million.
   Dallas-based Maxus, formerly Diamond Shamrock Corp., posted a
loss of $7 million the first six months of 1989 compared with a
loss of $89.9 million a year earlier. Revenue fell 6 percent to
$295.7 million from $314.3 million in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
