<FIRST>u f AM-Banks-Securities     07-26 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Securities,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed OK's Three More Bank Companies to Underwrite and Deal in Corporate
Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday gave
the go-ahead for three more New York banking companies to
underwrite and deal in corporate debt, moving further to break down
a 56-year barrier between traditional banking activities and the
securities industry.
   The Fed's latest actions involve requests from Citicorp, the
nation's largest banking concern; Chase Manhattan Corp. and Bankers
Trust New York Corp.
   The Fed said that the three large banks can establish
subsidiaries to raise money for corporations in the bond market,
traditionally an activity reserved to securities firms.
   A month ago, the Fed had given similar approval to J.P. Morgan,
the first bank to win such approval.
   The Fed, which regulates bank holding companies, had signaled
its intention to allow banks to move into the area of dealing in
corporate securities in January. In that decision, the Fed
governors said they would decide in a year whether to allow banks
to sell new issues of corporate stock.
   In 1987, the Fed had given approval for banks to underwrite
municipal revenue bonds, commercial paper, mortgage-backed
securities and securities backed by consumer loans.
   The securities subsidiary set up to handle the underwriting
activities may earn no more than 5 percent of its revenue from all
these activities, according to the Fed order.
   The strict limits set on the amount of corporate bond business
that banks can do will prevent banks from quickly challenging the
dominance of the largest securities firms in this area, officials
believe.
   The Fed's actions have still raised protests from lawmakers, who
have complained that the central bank should wait until Congress
addresses the issue of revamping the nation's financial industry.
   The banking industry has been trying for years to get Congress
to overhaul the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act, which separated the
banking and securities industries in response to abuses which were
uncovered in the wake of the 1929 stock market collapse. But so far
those efforts have not succeeded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
