<FIRST>r f AM-BoeingDeliveries     07-26 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing Deliveries,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Delivers 747s to British Airways Two Months Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. on Wednesday delivered two
747-400s to British Airways, whose chairman said concerns with the
structural quality of Boeing's jets had been resolved.
   British Airways Chairman Lord King said the delivery, which was
two months late, would not have a problem with certification by the
Joint European Airworthiness Authorities.
   The group had considered withholding certification of Boeing
planes because of structural quality concerns. The JEAA has
requested Boeing improve the 747-100's metal skin and some
electrical systems.
   King said problems with Boeing planes have been overcome with
``a constant stream of communication between Boeing and British
Airways.''
   Those problems were addressed in a letter last year by Don
Craig, former chief engineer of British Airways. Complaints
included missing fasteners and wrong or missing parts on planes
manufactured at Boeing's Everett plant.
   British Airways has $9.5 billion in Boeing orders. The company
is due 17 more 747-400s under the current order.
   The two planes delivered Wednesday have already been certified
by the British government's Civil Aviation Authority. They will
make their first commercial flights on a London-to-Philadelphia run
Friday.
</TEXT>
