<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Bethlehem     07-26 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Bethlehem,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Earnings Down 44 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. on Wednesday
reported a 45 percent drop in second-quarter profits it attributed
in part to a $50 million charge associated with the restructuring
of its BethForge division.
   Despite the decline, the nation's second-largest steelmaker
declared common stock dividends for the first time since the third
quarter of 1985.
   The company said it will pay 10 cents per share, reflecting its
recovery from an intense steel industry slump, company officials
said.
   For the second quarter, Bethlehem's earnings fell to $84
million, or 98 cents a share, from $151 million, or $1.85 per
share, during the same quarter last year. Quarterly sales increased
2.7 percent to $1.43 billion from $1.39 billion.
   Basic steel activity generated operating profits of $147
million, down 11.4 percent from $264 million, Bethlehem said.
   The steelmaker said it is paying more for alloys and other raw
materials, while selling less of its high-value products and more
low-value semi-finished steel.
   ``Order entry declined in the second quarter from strong
first-quarter levels as a result of customer inventory adjustments,
seasonal factors and an easing of demand from the automotive
industry,'' Bethlehem Chairman Walter F. Williams said.
   For the first half, Bethlehem reported a 37 percent decline in
profits to $149 million, or $1.73 a share, from $236 million, or $3
per share. Sales for the comparable six-month periods rose 4
percent to $2.84 billion from $2.72 billion.
</TEXT>
