<SECOND>BC-Earns-Robins,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robins Sales, Earnings Down in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The A.H. Robins Co., whose Chapter 11
bankruptcy reorganization survived a federal appeals court
challenge last month, said Wednesday its sales and profit declined
in the second quarter.
   Net earnings for the three months ended June 30 were $2.8
million, or 11 cents a share, down 68 percent from $8.7 million, or
36 cents a share, in the corresponding period last year.
   Sales for the quarter totaled $187.2 million, down 2 percent
from $191.5 million in the second quarter of 1988.
   The sales decline resulted from the impact of converting foreign
currencies into U.S. dollars, the company said. The profit drop was
caused primarily by a higher effective income tax rate, it said.
   Robins, a Richmond-based pharmaceutical manufacturer that sold
the ill-fated Dalkon Shield birth control device in the early
1970s, is to be acquired by the New York-based American Home
Products Corp. under its reorganization plan, which also includes a
$2.5 billion trust fund to compensate women injured by the Dalkon
Shield.
