<FIRST>u f AM-Psychiatrist-InsiderTrading     07-26 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Psychiatrist-Insider Trading,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Charged With Using Inside Information From Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatrist was indicted Wednesday on
securities and mail fraud charges for allegedly using inside
information from a patient to make a profitable deal involving
BankAmerica Corp. stock.
   A 46-count indictment filed in Manhattan federal court alleged
that the psychiatrist, Robert Howard Willis, received non-public
information during a patient consultation about an attempt by
Sanford I. Weill, the former chief executive officer of Shearson,
Loeb Rhoades, to become head of BankAmerica.
   Willis was told by the patient that Weill, who previously had
left Shearson, had received a commitment from his former firm to
invest $1 billion in BankAmerica if Weill became BankAmerica's
chief executive officer, the indictment said.
   Using that information, Willis allegedly bought $171,130.50
worth of BankAmerica stock between Jan. 14, 1986 and Feb. 6, 1986.
   He sold the stock Feb. 21, 1986, after a public announcement
about Weill's attempt to become a BankAmerica executive, making a
profit of $27,475 for himself and family members, the indictment
alleges.
   Weill, who now heads Primerica Corp., was unsuccessful in his
bid to join BankAmerica. Neither Weill or BankAmerica were charged
with any wrongdoing.
   The patient, identified only as Jane Doe, had been told about
the bid by her husband, who had knowledge about it through his
business dealings, the indictment said.
   If Weill had been successful, the change would have caused
``substantial upheavals'' in the personal life of the patient and
her husband, it said.
   Willis, 55, of Tenafly, N.J., has an office in Manhattan.
   He was charged in U.S. District Court with 23 counts of
securities fraud and 23 counts of mail fraud. If convicted, he
faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on each of the
46 counts. Willis is to be arraigned Aug. 3
</TEXT>
