<FIRST>u f AM-ComputerVirus 2ndLd-Writethru f0258 07-26 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Virus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0258,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Cornell Student on Computer Virus Allegation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf: ``Robert Tappan,'' to CORRECT number of computers
to four sted six. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cornell University graduate student was
indicted Wednesday on a felony charge stemming from the creation of
a rogue computer ``virus'' that paralyzed as many as 6,000
computers last fall.
   Robert Tappan Morris, 24, who has been suspended from the
university for one year, was indicted by a federal grand jury in
Syracuse, N.Y., on a single count of accessing without
authorization at least four university and military computers.
   The computer-crime indictment charged that the virus, which
spread across a nationwide network of computers, prevented the
authorized use of those computers by universities and military
bases.
   The Justice Department said in a statement released here that
Morris was the first person to be charged under a provision of the
Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 that outlaws unauthorized
accesss to computers by hackers. The provision also makes it
illegal to gain entry to a computer to damage or destroy files.
   The indictment comes after months of deliberations within the
Justice Department over whether to charge Morris with a felony or a
misdemeanor.
   Morris, of Arnold, Md., could face a possible five-year sentence
and a $250,000 fine if convicted of the charge.
   The law also provides for restitution of victims of a computer
crime, but prosecutors did not specify how much damage was caused
by the Nov. 2, 1988, incident that virtually shut down a
military-university computer network used to transmit
non-classified data.
   An industry group estimated that as much as $96 million worth of
damage was caused by the virus to 6,200 computers.
   But a Cornell University commission, which criticized Morris'
actions as ``reckless and impetuous,'' called this estimate
``grossly exaggerated'' and ``self-serving.''
   Defense attorney Thomas A. Guidoboni, said Morris ``accepts this
event as a step toward the final resolution of this matter.''
   ``An indictment is simply a formal accusation,'' Guidoboni said.
``Mr. Morris will enter a plea of not guity and contest the charge
against him.'' Morris ``looks forward to his eventual vindication
and his return to a normal life,'' the defense lawyer said.
   As many as 6,000 university and military computers on the
nationwide ARPANET network were infected by the virus or computer
``worm'' that the Cornell University commission concluded was
created by Morris.
   The panel called the incident ``a juvenile act that ignored the
clear potential consequences'' and showed a ``reckless disregard of
those probable consequences.''
   But the commission noted that ``it appears to have been an
uncharacteristic act for Morris,'' who had graduated from Harvard
University last year before beginning a graduate program in
computer science at Cornell.
   Guidoboni said Morris, who has been on leave from the university
since the incident, was placed on a one-year's suspension that
begins in September.
   The defendant's father is chief computer scientist for the
National Computer Security Center near Baltimore.
   The indictment charged that the younger Morris ``intentionally
and without authorization'' accessed computers located at the
University of California at Berkeley; the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration in Moffett Field, Calif.; Purdue University in
West Lafayette, Ind.; the U.S. Air Force Logistics Command at
Wright Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio, and others not
specified.
   The spread of the virus ``prevented the authorized use of one or
more of these federal interest computers and thereby caused a loss
to one or more others'' of more than $1,000, the indictment charged.
   Although the virus disrupted the operations of thousands of
computers, Cornell University spokesman Dennis Meredith said it did
not erase any files of electronically stored data.
   But he said ``there is absolutely no doubt that the computer
worm did serious damage to computer systems around the country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890726-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 2131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     07-26 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stock Prices Move For New High in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in early trading against the
Japanese yen Thursday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange scored new highs.
   The U.S. dollar opened at 139.35 yen, down 2.08 yen from
Wednesday's close of 141.43 yen. It closed at 140.05 yen in New
York overnight, down from Tuesday's close of 141.60 yen.
   Dealers said the initial trading in Tokyo followed its overnight
trend in New York, where the dollar dropped over signs that the
U.S. Federal Reserve was loosening credit and over speculation
about the country's sluggish economic growth.
   Naoto Kawamura, a senior dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, said the
Federal Reserve did not drain reserves from the banking system
Thursday, despite a sharp decline in the federal funds rate to 8{
percent from more than 9 percent Tuesday.
   The federal funds rate, controlled by the Federal Reserve, is
the interest charged on overnight loans between banks, and it
influences other interest rates throughout the economy.
   The market's general sentiment toward the dollar is bearish,
Kawamura said, adding that many market players predict poor
performance in the second-quarter U.S. gross national product,
showing evidence of slow economic growth. The GNP figures are
scheduled to be released later Thursday in Washington.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which shed 23.07 points Wednesday, gained 126.27
percent, or 0.36 percent, shortly after the market opened to move
to 34,642.10, a new high.
   On Tuesday, the market's main index reached a new closing high
of 34,538.90 points before holding back Wednesday.
</TEXT>
