<FIRST>r f BC-Ashland-7-Eleven     07-26 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ashland-7-Eleven,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Division Buys 66 Convenience Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SuperAmerica, the retail gasoline marketing
division of Ashland Oil Inc., has bought 66 7-Eleven stores and
other properties in Minnesota and Wisconsin from Southland Corp.,
Ashland said Wednesday.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   The 7-Eleven units will be renamed under the SuperAmerica brand
name, said John F. Pettus, president of SuperAmerica.
   Of the 66 properties, 54 are in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area.
SuperAmerica already runs 73 stores in the two cities.
   About half of the 7-Eleven stores in the deal sell gas and
merchandise, while the other half sell only merchandise. Seven of
the properties don't contain 7-Eleven stores.
   SuperAmerica has 590 convenience stores in 18 states. The
division also markets gasoline under brand names in nearly 1,500
other company or dealer-operated outlets.
   Dallas-based Southland is the world's largest convenience
retailer with about 7,000 7-Eleven and other stores in the United
States and Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
